<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reds Call Up Boone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Third baseman Aaron Boone rejoined the  
Cincinnati Reds on Tuesday, while pitcher Denny Neagle received 
reassurances that he won't need shoulder surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	The Reds called up Boone from Triple-A Indianapolis to fill  
Neagle's spot on the roster. Neagle went on the disabled list 
Monday with weakness in his shoulder and has an appointment 
Wednesday with Dr. James Andrews in Birmingham, Ala. 
</P>
<P>
	General manager Jim Bowden told reporters during a game against  
Los Angeles that four doctors had recommended putting Neagle on a 
strengthening program. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors who have either examined Neagle or looked at his test  
results concurred that there's no need for surgery, Bowden said. 
</P>
<P>
	``With the information we've received today, it's very clear  
that surgery is not even an alternative to solve the problem,'' 
Bowden said. 
</P>
<P>
	The information changed Bowden's mind. Before the game, he  
thought that Neagle should have exploratory surgery to find out 
what's wrong with his left shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's great news. I'm glad I'm wrong,'' Bowden said.  
</P>
<P>
	The Reds got Neagle from Atlanta last November as part of a  
five-player deal that included second baseman Bret Boone. Neagle 
was supposed to become the cornerstone of the rotation, but he 
pulled thigh muscles and had weakness in the shoulder in spring 
training. 
</P>
<P>
	After opening the season on the disabled list, he was activated  
and hit hard in six starts. He's 0-3 with an 8.17 ERA and batters 
are hitting .340 off him. 
</P>
<P>
	Neagle is willing to do whatever Andrews suggests, even if it  
means arthroscopic surgery to examine the rotator cuff. 
</P>
<P>
	``In my mind, I've already prepared myself for whatever he might  
say,'' Neagle said. 
</P>
<P>
	Neagle has base salaries of $4.75 million this year and next. He  
could demand a trade after the season, but has said he'll wait to 
make a decision. 
</P>
<P>
	Bowden said the four doctors recommended putting him back on a  
program to strengthen the shoulder. That could take four to six 
weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Aaron Boone was optioned to Indianapolis on May 12 to open a  
spot for reliever Ron Villone. The Reds considered calling up 
either Boone, Carlos Baerga or Jeff Branson to fill Neagle's spot. 
</P>
<P>
	Bowden said Boone was the choice because he was hitting the best  
of the three -- .341 in 11 games -- and was playing well overall. 
</P>
<P>
	Another factor was that Baerga would not allow himself to be  
sent back to the minors if he were called up and his roster spot 
was needed later on, Bowden said. 
</P>
<P>
	Baerga is hitting .294 in 44 games at Indianapolis. He agreed to  
a minor league deal during spring training that allows him to 
become a free agent if another team wants him for its major league 
roster. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
