<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.C. Death Row Inmate Wins Retrial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WILKESBORO, N.C. (AP) -- A man sentenced to death for beating a  
woman to death with a shotgun has won a new trial after a judge 
ruled authorities wrongly withheld another man's confession. 
</P>
<P>
	Charles Munsey, who on May 14 was granted a new trial, was  
ordered held Tuesday on $250,000 bond while he awaits retrial. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's been credible evidence to show that after six years in  
custody, three on death row, Mr. Munsey is innocent of these 
crimes,'' defense attorney Ben Sendor said in arguing for Munsey's 
release. ``Mr. Munsey ought to be free.'' 
</P>
<P>
	District Attorney Tom Horner said he would not appeal the  
ruling, and will seek an indictment against the man who confessed, 
Mike Hawkins. 
</P>
<P>
	Munsey, 51, was convicted in 1996 of the murder of Shirley  
Weaver, who was bludgeoned with a shotgun stock at her boyfriend's 
trailer three years earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Munsey had known the victim and her boyfriend,  
investigators found no fingerprints, hair or blood connecting him 
to the crime scene. 
</P>
<P>
	A witness, Tim Hall, testified that Munsey confessed to him, but  
after Munsey was sentenced to death, Hawkins came forward and told 
police that he killed Weaver and gave the pistol he stole to 
Munsey. 
</P>
<P>
	The confession was never disclosed, and it was later disclosed  
that Hall claimed he lied on the stand under pressure from the case 
prosecutor, who threatened to revoke Hall's parole if he recanted. 
</P>
<P>
	The prosecutor, District Attorney Randy Lyon, committed suicide  
in January 1998 just days after a judge ordered case records 
reopened. It was not know if the two events were related. 
</P>
<P>
	Munsey still faces charges in another, unrelated slaying.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
