<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Police Fire on Indonesia Protesters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- At least 15 people were wounded when  
police fired rubber bullets to disperse an anti-government protest 
by students and farmers Tuesday in northern Sumatra, witnesses 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	About 1,500 people took part in the demonstration outside the  
state-owned Nusantara II Plantation complex in Tanjung Marawa, said 
Nur Alamsyah, a spokesman for the local Legal Aid Foundation. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Tuesday, the group protested in front of the governor's  
office in Medan, provincial capital of the island of Sumatra. They 
were demanding dissolution of the ruling Golkar Party and the end 
of the military's role in politics. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesia has been plagued by violence since the ouster a year  
ago of President Suharto, who ruled the country for more than three 
decades. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
