<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Gore Staffer Wins in Kentucky </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRANKFORT, Ky. (AP) -- Jonathan Miller, who returned to Kentucky  
intent on winning a political race and outspent a series of 
opponents to do it, won one Tuesday with the Democratic nomination 
for state treasurer. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller, a member of a wealthy Lexington family and former  
staffer to Vice President Al Gore, defeated state Rep. Susan Johns, 
who was making her first run for statewide office. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, publicist and farmer Peppy Martin held a slim lead  
over David L. Williams in the Republican gubernatorial primary. 
Williams was a Democrat a year ago when he ran for the U.S. Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin spent only $10,000 on her campaign, and Williams spent  
next to nothing. Williams, who lives in a trailer with his 
running-mate wife, Joanna, a candidate for lieutenant governor, had 
declined interviews and had his telephone disconnected. 
</P>
<P>
	Registered Democrats vastly outnumber Republicans in Kentucky,  
and the incumbent, Gov. Paul Patton, is favored to win re-election 
in the first gubernatorial race in which an incumbent has been 
allowed to succeed himself. 
</P>
<P>
	A state constitutional change in 1992 allowed succession in  
constitutional offices, an event which has been banned in Kentucky 
for nearly 200 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller, who returned to Kentucky in 1997, started out by running  
for the Democratic nomination for Congress in the 6th District. 
Despite outspending all his opponents, he finished sixth out of 
seven candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, Miller was expected to have spent nearly $500,000 as  
opposed to about $50,000 for Johns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
