<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reform Jews Debate New Principles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- The governing body of Reform Judaism, the  
biggest and most liberal branch of American Jewry, debated a new 
set of principles Tuesday that would represent a return to 
traditional practices such as keeping kosher and praying in Hebrew. 
</P>
<P>
	The Central Conference of American Rabbis was expected to  
approve a major revision in the Principles of Reform Judaism, which 
are not enforceable regulations but more like suggestions or 
guidelines. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the new platform, ancient rituals scoffed at or ignored in  
Reform communities and usually associated with Conservative or 
Orthodox Jewry would once again be embraced, such as the wearing of 
yarmulkes and prayer shawls, the observance of Jewish dietary laws 
and the use of Hebrew during prayer services. 
</P>
<P>
	Reform leaders said many of the 1.5 million Reform Jews in the  
United States already have been returning to traditional practices, 
and the new principles would only reinforce that. 
</P>
<P>
	``On the eve of a new century, when so many individuals are  
striving for religious meaning, moral purpose and a sense of 
community, it is important that we have a modern set of principles 
that clearly define Reform Judaism,'' said Rabbi Paul J. Menitoff, 
executive vice president of the 1,700-member rabbis' group. 
</P>
<P>
	Ellis Rivkin, professor emeritus of Jewish history at Reform  
Judaism's Hebrew Union College in Cincinnati, said he has seen a 
strong shift toward tradition among students since he joined the 
faculty in 1949. In the past four to five years, he said, the trend 
has become more noticeable. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a kind of security that (tradition) brings when the  
external world is in an insecure state, and when Jews are 
threatened by the assimilation process and the high rate of 
intermarriage. They fear there might be a dissolution of Judaism 
because of its openness to the world at large,'' Rivkin said. 
</P>
<P>
	A leader of Orthodox Judaism, President Norman Lamm of Yeshiva  
University, was skeptical about how much Reform has really changed, 
since the statement allows every rabbi to be ``a law unto 
himself.'' But he said: ``They have come a long way, and that 
journey is to be applauded.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday's meeting was only the fourth time since Reform Judaism  
was established in North America in the mid-19th century that the 
rabbis' group set forth comprehensive principles. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1885, 15 Reform rabbis met and issued the Pittsburgh  
Platform, which rejected traditional Jewish practices as ``entirely 
foreign'' for modern American times. 
</P>
<P>
	A platform adopted in 1937 encouraged rabbis to incorporate  
science into their views of sacred literature. And a conference in 
1976 produced a call for diversity, individuality and change. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest platform was not reached without controversy and  
several rewordings. 
</P>
<P>
	An earlier draft was dubbed ``Conservative lite'' by Rabbi  
Robert M. Seltzer, professor of Jewish history at the City 
University of New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Reform leaders said the final draft maintains the traditional  
Reform ethos that sets their branch apart from Conservative Judaism 
-- the idea that Jews should choose traditions that help them and 
bypass those that do not. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
