<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets closed lower Tuesday  
on the back of a sharp fall overnight on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo's benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 176.26  
points, or 1.08 percent, to finish at 16,214.23. On Monday, the 
average rose 97.51 points, or 0.60 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said investors were worried that Japanese banks might  
have another difficult fiscal year. The fears were sparked by news 
reports Tuesday that 16 of Japan's largest banks held a total of 
20.9 trillion yen ($171.3 billion) in bad loans as of March 31, the 
end of the last fiscal year. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first time that banks have reported the loans under  
new standards which more accurately illustrate the true scale of 
the problem, according to the reports. 
</P>
<P>
	Also dampening sentiment was an overnight fall on Wall Street,  
where the Dow Jones industrial average shed 174.61 points -- or 1.6 
percent -- to stand at 10,654.67 at Monday's close. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. dollar was quoted at 122.72 yen in late trading, down  
1.32 yen from late Monday in Tokyo and also below its late New York 
level of 123.21 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	Thai share prices slumped, with the key index falling 4 percent  
in a late selling spree. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stock Exchange of Thailand, or SET, Index fell 18.93 points  
to 451.05. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, the key Hang Seng Index fell 89.95 points, or 0.7  
percent, closing at 12,346.91. On Monday, the index had gained 
164.72 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Brokers said prices fell in reaction to the overnight tumble on  
Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors were also cautious because of uncertainty over whether  
interest rates will rise, but ``quite a number of them'' were 
waiting for buying opportunities when the index falls a bit lower, 
said Josephine Hui, director at Celestial Asia Securities Holdings 
Ltd. 
</P>
<P>
	New Zealand share prices closed sharply lower as weaker global  
share markets sent the key index plummeting into negative 
territory. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark NZSE-40 Capital Index fell 62.47 points, or 2.9  
percent, to 2,094.50. It was the index's lowest close since Dec. 
31, 1998 when it finished at 2065.28. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Share prices closed sharply lower as investors dumped  
stocks on fear of more corporate failures following reports that 
Shin Yen Industrial Co. was in financial trouble. The Weighted 
Stock Price Index fell 171.20 points, or 2.3 percent, to 7,417.03. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian shares closed sharply higher, raising  
hopes that the market's recent bull run would remain intact even 
after its current consolidation, dealers said. The benchmark 
Composite Index rose 2 percent, or 14.76 points, to 758.10. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine shares closed lower as investors cashed in on  
gains following Wall Street's loss Monday, traders said. The 
30-company Philippine Stock Exchange Index, the PSE Index, fell 
35.10 points, or 1.5 percent, to 2,370.37. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Australian share prices closed lower in reaction to the  
fall on Wall Street. The All Ordinaries Index closed at 2911.5, 
down 1.3 percent, or 37.7 points. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: Share prices closed slightly higher. The Korea Composite  
Stock Price Index rose 3.09 points, or 0.4 percent, to 698.69. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Indonesian shares closed higher on speculative buying  
in telecommunication blue chips and second-line stocks. The 
Composite Index rose 1 percent, or 6.236 points, to 619.877. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
