<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Panel Hears Testimony on JFK Film </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Is Abraham Zapruder's home movie of the  
assassination of President Kennedy just a thin strip of celluloid 
wrapped on a reel or more like Vincent van Gogh's ``Sunflowers,'' 
which sold for $40 million in 1987? 
</P>
<P>
	A three-member arbitration panel began hearing testimony Tuesday  
to decide how much the government must pay the Zapruder family for 
the half-minute of history captured on 8mm film. The government 
must compensate the family because the Assassination Records Review 
Board in 1997 declared the film the permanent possession of the 
people of the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The question is how much. The Zapruder family, represented by  
LMH Co., is asking $30 million. The government is offering $1 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	Government appraiser C.C.M. Associates says that without  
projection, the 8mm Zapruder film is a ``tiny strip of celluloid 
tightly wound on a plastic reel.'' Moreover, the government argues 
that Kennedy memorabilia sells for thousands, not millions, of 
dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, the Sotheby's auction house in New York sold 1,200  
items from the estate of former first lady Jacqueline Kennedy. The 
most expensive piece -- an antique French desk where President 
Kennedy signed the Nuclear Test Ban Treaty -- sold for $1.4 million. 
The entire collection took in about $34 million, government 
appraisers said. 
</P>
<P>
	``When compared to those results, LMH's demand of $30 million  
for the Zapruder film, an item President Kennedy never touched, is 
staggering,'' the government wrote in a brief. 
</P>
<P>
	Appraisers for the Zapruder family argue, however, the film is a  
piece of history or artwork that should be valued like the works of 
van Gogh or pop artist Andy Warhol's ``Orange Marilyn'' silkscreen 
of Marilyn Monroe, which sold for $17.3 million last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a cultural icon, a historic document and a unique object  
that has itself become the embodiment of one of the most 
significant and well-remembered events of the 20th century,'' 
appraiser Beth Gates Warren wrote in a brief to bolster the 
Zapruders' case. ``Additionally, the film is inextricable bound to 
the powerful Kennedy mystique and the controversy surrounding 
President Kennedy's murder.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sylvia Leonard Wolf, who appraised the Zapruder film for $40  
million, says the film is an example of vernacular photography -- 
``photography with no artistic intent'' -- that's been moving onto 
the art scene. ``Modern art museums often show videos that lack 
narrative and simply record aspects of everyday life,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Thirty years ago, the Museum of Modern Art displayed pictures of  
bank robberies taken by automatic bank cameras, according to Ms. 
Wolf. 
</P>
<P>
	``Is the Zapruder film, which captures a profound moment of the  
20th century in a deeply moving and visually compelling way, any 
less artistic than a picture developed from film taken of burglars 
by a bank surveillance camera?'' she asks. ``I would say that the 
Zapruder film as a work of art far surpasses these pictures.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The two sides initially tried to negotiate a price for the film.  
In October, with negotiations going nowhere, they summoned 
arbitrators and agreed on a $30 million ceiling price. The deal 
does not include the copyright on the film, which the Zapruder 
family will retain. 
</P>
<P>
	After the hearing at the U.S. Court of Federal Claims, the  
arbitrators have 30 days to determine how much the government must 
pay for the film, preserved in 25-degree temperature in a room at 
the National Archives in College Park, Md. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990525.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 07:21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cathay Threatens To Fire Pilots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- The dispute between Cathay Pacific Airways and  
its senior pilots worsened Tuesday after the company threatened to 
fire pilots who refuse a revised pay package and the pilots 
responded with threats of industrial action. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will use all means at our disposal to resist Cathay  
Pacific's tactics,'' said John Findlay, general secretary of the 
Hong Kong Aircrew Officers Association. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if the pilots would strike if Cathay refused to return to  
the table, he said: ``We will rule out nothing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After nine weeks of unsuccessful talks with the association, the  
Hong Kong carrier decided Tuesday to bypass the union and sent 
letters directly to its pilots, offering them a sweetened deal. 
</P>
<P>
	But the letter also said they risk losing their jobs if they do  
not accept the deal or choose a resignation package. The airline 
extended its deadline for acceptance to June 11; it had been next 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The pilots' union issued a statement calling Cathay's demands  
``totally unreasonable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Our members will not sign a non-negotiated contract,'' the  
statement said. It added that the union believed ``agreement can 
still be reached by negotiation, and we remain ready to talk.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cathay Pacific, which plunged into the red for the first time in  
35 years because of Asia's financial crisis, asked its senior 
pilots in March to take pay cuts averaging 8 percent in exchange 
for stock options. 
</P>
<P>
	But the pilots accuse Cathay of using a short-term economic  
problem to slash pay permanently. 
</P>
<P>
	They rejected the original package, asking instead that the  
company promise the senior pilots pay increases of 3 percent after 
two years of pay cuts and one year of a pay freeze. They also asked 
Cathay for guarantees of annual pay increases for junior pilots and 
higher provident fund contributions. 
</P>
<P>
	In the revised offer, Cathay is asking its pilots to accept a 7  
percent pay cut phased in over two years. It is also giving the 
pilots 10 years to exercise their stock options, instead of eight 
as proposed previously. 
</P>
<P>
	Cathay also is offering junior pilots, who joined after 1993 and  
are subject to different pay scales and conditions, a 7 percent to 
10 percent pay rise over the next two years. 
</P>
<P>
	The pilots' pay dispute follows Cathay's recent battle with its  
flight attendants, who eventually conceded to management demands 
that they work more hours in exchange for a pay increase. 
</P>
<P>
	Cathay lost 542 million Hong Kong dollars ($69 million) last  
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990525.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 07:41:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Mixed; Dow Down 1.47 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed in the first half-hour of  
trading today as technology stocks continued to languish. 
</P>
<P>
	At 10 a.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
down 1.47 at 10,653.20. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were mostly lower. The Standard &AMP;  
Poor's 500 index was down 2.42 at 1,304.23, and the Nasdaq 
composite index, dominated by technology issues, was down 22.30 at 
2,431.36. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday, the Dow fell 174.61 points to close at 10,654.67 as  
high-flying Internet stocks tumbled. Analysts say that as hints of 
inflation have prompted the Federal Reserve to consider raising 
interest rates, investors are moving away from high-priced stocks 
that earn little or no profits. The sector failed to rebound in 
early trading today, as Yahoo shed another 4 3/8 to trade at 133 1/2. 
</P>
<P>
	Banking stocks also dropped Monday after an investment analyst  
downgraded several major banks, citing concerns about the Year 2000 
computer bug. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, First Union Corp. offered a more old-fashioned warning.  
The bank said it expects its second-quarter earnings to fall far 
short of analysts' estimates as it continues paying for its 1998 
acquisition of CoreStates Financial Corp. Its shares plunged 5 
15/16 to 44. 
</P>
<P>
	Cyclical stocks, which tend to mirror the trends of the broader  
economy, were mostly higher today. 3M rose 1 3/8 to 91 3/16, the 
strongest gainer among the Dow components. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 10-to-9 margin on  
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 94.1 million 
shares, ahead of Monday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was down 0.73 at 625.32, and the  
American Stock Exchange composite index was up 0.51 at 785.92. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.60 percent. In  
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was up 1.04 percent, 
Britain's FT-SE 100 was down 0.49 percent, and France's CAC-40 was 
down 0.54 percent. 

</P>
</TEXT>
