</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO warplanes attacked Slobodan  
Milosevic's villa and other targets across Yugoslavia today, and 
the military alliance approved a revised plan for an enlarged 
peacekeeping ground force of up to 50,000 in Kosovo as soon as Serb 
troops depart. A new wave of refugees -- as many as 150,000 -- were 
reported bound for Macedonia, and a U.N. report detailed in graphic 
fashion ``a significant upsurge'' in sexual violence against ethnic 
Albanian women in Kosovo since NATO airstrikes began two months 
ago. 

</P>
