</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Six California cities and two counties sued  
handgun manufacturers today, arguing that sloppy marketing 
practices put deadly weapons in the hands of criminals and 
children. Among the defendants are Colt, Smith &AMP; Wesson, Glock and 
Berretta, as well as weapons industry trade groups. The suits seek 
injunctions against dangerous marketing practices, profits from 
illegally marketed guns and penalties of up to $2,500 for each gun 
traceable to an illegal marketing practice. 

</P>
<P>
	Starr Won't Retry McDougal, Steele  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Kenneth Starr decided today he won't retry  
Whitewater figure Susan McDougal and another woman accused of 
hindering his investigation. Starr said prosecuting anew Mrs. 
McDougal and Julie Hiatt Steele wasn't worth the trouble given 
earlier hung juries in the two cases. The independent counsel's 
decision came after juries handed him consecutive setbacks in his 
effort to punish two witnesses he contended were uncooperative or 
gave false testimony, and delayed his investigation. 

</P>
<P>
	Americans Give $175B to Charity  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Americans opened their pocketbooks wider in  
1998, donating nearly $17 billion more to charities than the 
previous year. A strong economy, low inflation, a growth in 
personal wealth and more sophisticated fund raising helped fuel the 
10.7 percent increase and raise overall charitable giving to 
$174.52 billion, said the American Association of Fund-Raising 
Counsel's Trust for Philanthropy. 

