<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 06:11:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Mulls TV-Police Partnerships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The scene is repeated every day across  
America: Police officers armed with warrants burst into a house in 
search of a quarry. 
</P>
<P>
	When a camera crew is invited to follow, the images often make  
powerful television, appearing on ``COPS,'' ``LAPD: Life on the 
Beat'' and the Spanish-language program ``Placas'' (``Shields''), 
among others. 
</P>
<P>
	But such reality TV shows may find police less welcoming  
following two Supreme Court decisions Monday allowing police to be 
sued financially over the filming of arrests or searches on private 
property. 
</P>
<P>
	The high court ruled that so-called ``media ride-alongs'' may  
violate the Constitution's Fourth Amendment ban on unreasonable 
searches and seizures. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think this may dampen officers' desire to take media with  
them. This is one more thing on the side of `is it worth it?''' 
said Penny Parrish, spokeswoman for the Minneapolis Police 
Department. 
</P>
<P>
	Other departments said the ruling reinforces a trend.  
</P>
<P>
	The New York Police Department decided several years ago to bar  
camera crews from accompanying its officers because of privacy 
concerns, spokeswoman Marilyn Mode said. 
</P>
<P>
	In March, the Los Angeles Police Department reaffirmed  
guidelines barring TV crews from entering private property without 
an owner's permission. When it comes to weighing ride-along 
requests, a news program would get priority over a reality show, a 
police spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're satisfied with the court's ruling,'' police Lt. Anthony  
Alba said. ``We're already engaged in a media ride-along policy 
that mirrors their ruling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	John Langley, the executive producer of ``COPS,'' said he  
expects his camera crews to conduct ``business as usual'' since the 
show already tries to respect privacy rights. 
</P>
<P>
	```COPS' routinely obtains permission when filming on private  
property and also obtains releases from everyone involved in the 
program,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Erik Nelson, a reality TV producer for Termite Art Productions,  
also said the court ruling won't affect his operations. His company 
makes sure people sign release agreements and that victims' faces 
are blurred and their names omitted. 
</P>
<P>
	``There already are restrictions applied due to common sense and  
common decency,'' Nelson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The rulings still will allow media to accompany police officers  
as long as journalists stay outside when officers enter private 
homes, said attorney Richard Cordray, who represented police 
officers in the two cases. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling also only concerns people's homes and does not  
restrict reporters' right to join police officers at work, or 
photographers' right to shoot pictures in public places. 
</P>
<P>
	News organizations including The Washington Post, CNN and The  
Associated Press argued the ruling may discourage police from 
allowing the media to accompany them even for permissible purposes. 
</P>
<P>
	The rulings involved cases in Maryland and Montana.  
</P>
<P>
	In the Maryland case, Montgomery County sheriff's deputies and  
deputy U.S. marshals took along a Washington Post reporter and 
photographer when they entered Charles and Geraldine Wilson's home 
in Rockville. 
</P>
<P>
	The officers wanted to arrest the Wilsons' fugitive adult son,  
who was not at their home but turned himself in later. Photographs, 
one showing Wilson wearing only his undershorts with a police 
officer's gun at his head, were not published. 
</P>
<P>
	The Montana case was filed by Paul and Erma Berger against  
federal agents and a prosecutor who let a CNN reporter and camera 
crew accompany them to the couple's ranch. 
</P>
<P>
	Government agents were seeking evidence of eagle poisoning, but  
Paul Berger was convicted only of improper use of a pesticide, a 
minor offense. CNN later aired footage of the raid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
