<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Air Force Sees No Conflict in Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Air Force said Monday it found no conflict  
of interest with a general who led the investigation into the crash 
of a Lockheed-Martin plane and then took a job with the plane's 
manufacturer. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1996 crash of the Lockheed HC-130P Hercules cargo plane,  
known as ``King 56,'' killed 10 Portland, Ore.-based Air Force 
Reserve crewmen. One man survived. 
</P>
<P>
	Maj. Gen. Bobby O. Floyd ordered tests on the last major issue  
of the crash investigation in August 1998, five months before his 
Lockheed Martin job interviews began, the Air Force said. 
</P>
<P>
	Floyd also recused himself from actions involving  
Lockheed-Martin more than two months before his first job interview 
with the company. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our review establishes there was no conflict of interest,''  
said a letter from Lt. Gen. David Vesely, the Air Force's assistant 
vice chief of staff. 
</P>
<P>
	But Vesely acknowledged that Floyd did not recuse himself from  
the crash investigation until March -- more than a month after his 
first job interviews with Lockheed Martin. 
</P>
<P>
	That finding prompted a sharply worded statement from Sen. Ron  
Wyden, D-Ore. 
</P>
<P>
	``I find it astonishing that the Air Force does not deny General  
Floyd's continued involvement in the King 56 investigation well 
after he sought employment with Lockheed-Martin, yet concludes 
there is nothing wrong with this,'' Wyden said. 
</P>
<P>
	He has been critical of the Air Force investigation and had  
asked the service to look into the timing of Floyd's 
Lockheed-Martin job and whether it presented a conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	After receiving Vesely's letter, Wyden said the Air Force still  
seems more interested in protecting itself and its contractors that 
in conducting an unbiased investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	He called for a ``truly independent'' inquiry.  
</P>
<P>
	Floyd's 21-man investigation team, which included an  
investigator from the National Transportation Safety Board, could 
find no fatal flaws with Hercules aircraft. 
</P>
<P>
	The final report on the crash found that the crew ran a fuel  
tank dry, causing all four engines to fail and the plane to 
tailspin into the Pacific off Northern California. 
</P>
<P>
	But family members of some of the dead airmen dispute those  
findings. 
</P>
<P>
	Several claim a drop in electrical voltage crippled fuel flow to  
the plane's engines, and they filed a 1997 federal lawsuit accusing 
Lockheed and the Allison Engine Co. of building an aircraft with 
defective parts. 
</P>
<P>
	Floyd retired April 1. He and Lockheed Martin Aircraft &AMP;  
Logistics Centers said earlier this month that his employment with 
the South Carolina company presented no conflict of interest. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
