<HEADLINE> Japanese Stocks Close Lower / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Concern about the future of Japan's debt ridden  
banks coupled with an overnight drop on Wall Street pushed Tokyo 
stocks lower today. The dollar fell against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 176.26 points,  
or 1.08 percent, to finish at 16,214.23. On Monday, the average 
rose 97.51 points, or 0.60 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 122.72 yen in late trading, down 1.32 yen from  
late Monday in Tokyo and also below its late New York level of 
123.21 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, share prices slipped amid concerns about  
the health of Japan's banking sector. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said investors are worried that Japanese banks may have  
another difficult fiscal year. The fears were sparked by news 
reports today that 16 of Japan's largest banks held a total of 20.9 
trillion yen ($171.3 billion) in bad loans as of March 31, the end 
of the last fiscal year. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first time that banks have reported the loans under  
new standards which more accurately illustrate the true scale of 
the problem, according to the reports. 
</P>
<P>
	Also dampening sentiment was an overnight fall on Wall Street,  
where the Dow Jones industrial average shed 174.61 points or 1.6 
percent to stand at 10,654.67 at Monday's close. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, trading was thin in Tokyo as many investors kept to the  
sidelines to monitor corporate earnings results, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	``With little macroeconomic or policy news to absorb, trading is  
focused on individual stocks,'' said Kunihiro Hatae, general 
manager at Tokyo Securities Co. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 445.06 million shares changed hands on the first  
section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange, up from 410.78 million shares 
Monday. Decliners outnumbered advancers 795 to 380, while 138 
issues were unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
exchange's first section was down 8.83 points, or 0.67 percent, to 
1,308.68. The TOPIX was up 7.84 points, or 0.60 percent, the day 
before. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar remained under selling pressure  
from overseas players taking profits on recent gains. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, the dollar climbed to a seven month high against the  
yen, rising above 124 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The fall in the Dow also worked against the dollar in Tokyo on  
today, analysts said. In addition, some dealers cited jitters about 
Argentina abandoning its currency board, although others downplayed 
such concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 130.35 yen, down  
from 131.22 yen late Monday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark No. 212 10-year Japanese  
government bond fell to 1.3150 percent from Monday's finish of 
1.3500 percent, pushing its price up to 101.64 yen from 101.32 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
