<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bill Would Give Customs More Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The U.S. Customs Service would get more money  
to fight drug trafficking and online child pornography under 
legislation passed by the House. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill, passed Tuesday on a 410-2 vote, would allow Customs an  
additional 1,745 officers to work along the borders and at major 
drug and money-laundering locations. It provides $10 million, up 
from the current $2.4 million, for the Child Pornography/Child 
Sexual Exploitation Program, which tracks international Internet 
sex predators and traffic in child pornography. 
</P>
<P>
	The program also coordinates with the FBI to expose domestic  
child pornography. 
</P>
<P>
	``As more kids go online every day we need to ensure their  
safety, and it's time to let online pedophiles know that they can 
no longer hide behind their computer screens,'' said Rep. Nancy 
Johnson, R-Conn., chief sponsor of the provision. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill authorizes $2.4 billion for the Customs Service in  
fiscal 2000 and 2001, $400 million more than the administration 
requested. It includes $150 million each year to help the agency 
replace its 16-year-old computer system, which has had difficulty 
processing trade quickly and efficiently. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats supported the basic bill but criticized the Republican  
majority for inserting language that changes Customs employee 
overtime and night differential pay systems. They also complained 
that they were not allowed to offer an amendment to remove the 
provision. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Sander Levin, D-Mich., said Democrats would urge the Senate  
to remove the labor provisions when it takes up the legislation. 
Last year the House approved the Customs bill by a large margin but 
the Senate never voted on it. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is H.R. 1833.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
