<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alaska Airlines, Mechanics Settle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATAC, Wash. (AP) -- Less than a week after Alaska Airlines  
chairman John F. Kelly assured stockholders that labor peace was 
his top priority, a potentially critical settlement was reached 
with leaders of the mechanics union. 
</P>
<P>
	Following weeks of flight cancellations, six firings and the  
filing of a federal court lawsuit, tentative agreement was reached 
Monday on a 42-month contract for more than 1,000 members of the 
Aircraft Mechanics Fraternal Association. 
</P>
<P>
	Louie Key, a vice president of AMFA Local 14, said the local  
leadership would recommend approval in voting that should be 
completed in about three weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very excited and very proud to be taking this contract out  
to our members,'' Key said. 
</P>
<P>
	The union's national director, O.V. Delle-Femine, would not give  
specific terms but said the pact ranked in the middle of the 
industry and included gains in pay, benefits, health care and 
retirement provisions. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were not looking for any takebacks whatsoever,'' company  
chairman John F. Kelly said. ``We've always said we want to pay 
market wages.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the deal could improve the chance of resolving three  
other contract disputes dogging the West Coast regional carrier for 
as long as 2 1/2 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Kelly cited a provision for binding arbitration of unresolved  
issues after 120 days of negotiations once the contract comes up 
for renewal. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the Railway Labor Act, airline contracts do not expire but  
are subject to periodic renegotiation. 
</P>
<P>
	Kelly and Delle-Femine said government mediation under the law  
took too long to arrange, an obstacle that will be avoided by 
arbitration. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's certainly a model. We also have that model in existence  
with our pilot contract. We have a similar approach (in talks) with 
the Association of Flight Attendants. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement was announced at Alaska Airlines offices near  
Seattle-Tacoma International Airport five days after questions 
about stalled contract talks dominated the annual meeting of 
corporate parent Alaska Air Group Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Alaska Airlines has been in talks with unions representing all  
of the company's hourly workers except pilots and dispatchers. 
</P>
<P>
	About 650 flights have been canceled since April 26, roughly  
twice the typical number, because of what company officials 
described as a slowdown by mechanics and a sickout by passenger 
service agents and baggage handlers. 
</P>
<P>
	Six accused sickout instigators were fired, and Alaska Airlines  
sued the mechanics' union and sought a federal court injunction 
over the slowdown claims. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit will be withdrawn Tuesday, Kelly said.  
</P>
<P>
	``We've never condoned any of these slowdowns or alleged  
slowdowns,'' Delle-Femine said. ``I think we've been falsely 
accused... . 
</P>
<P>
	Kelly said contract talks covering 3,400 clerks, ticket agents  
and other passenger service employees represented by the 
International Association of Machinists and Aerospace Workers and 
about 1,750 flight attendants are going well. 
</P>
<P>
	The company and the Machinists union remain at loggerheads in  
talks covering about 1,060 ramp agents and stock clerks. Kelly said 
the Machinists won't discuss anything except union security and 
subcontracting. 

</P>
</TEXT>
