<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Democrats Push Finance Privacy Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Democratic lawmakers are pushing legislation  
that would give consumers the right to stop affiliated banks, 
brokerage firms and insurance companies from sharing personal 
financial data. 
</P>
<P>
	Banks and most of the financial services industry oppose the  
bill by Rep. Jay Inslee, D-Wash., which would allow consumers to 
``opt out'' of personal data-sharing among affiliated financial 
companies by notifying the firms in writing. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill embodies a proposal made earlier this month by  
President Clinton, who urged Congress to bolster consumers' rights 
when banks and other financial companies seek to share information 
about them. 
</P>
<P>
	As Congress crafts sweeping legislation to remove Depression-era  
barriers between banks, brokerages and insurers and allow them to 
merge, there is growing concern about the privacy of consumers who 
will use the new consolidated financial companies. 
</P>
<P>
	``The consumer is naked and helpless in (his) inability to tell  
banks not to share that information,'' Inslee said Tuesday at a 
news conference. ``This is going to allow consumers the right to 
decide their own fate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Inslee also maintained that for online commerce to flourish,  
consumers must have confidence their privacy will be protected. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate recently passed a financial overhaul bill, attaching  
to it a provision that would make it a federal crime for anyone to 
misrepresent himself to obtain someone's private financial data. 
</P>
<P>
	Legislation to rewrite the financial services laws now is before  
a House Commerce subcommittee, which has scheduled a drafting 
session for Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Edward Markey, D-Mass., plans to propose an amendment which  
includes Inslee's ``opt out'' but goes farther by prohibiting 
financial companies from selling personal data to outside firms 
without the consumer's express written consent. 
</P>
<P>
	The House Banking Committee in March adopted a version of  
financial overhaul legislation that would restrict sharing of 
customers' health information among affiliated companies. However, 
the bill still would allow customers' transaction data, such as 
checking account history, to be shared even if they made an opt-out 
request. Under current law, opt-out requests apply to a consumer's 
credit history but not to his or her transaction data. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumer activists such as Ralph Nader have maintained that  
rewriting the financial services laws would create serious privacy 
risks for Americans as banks, brokerages and insurers compiled 
profiles of customers' buying habits, hobbies and health data. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, lobbyists for the banking, securities and  
insurance industries have warned that adoption of tough privacy 
measures could kill their support for the overhaul legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, one of the key reasons the industries have been pushing  
financial overhaul legislation is that it would open numerous 
opportunities for them to market their services by using shared 
customer data. 
</P>
<P>
	Patricia Cinelli, a spokeswoman for the American Bankers  
Association, said the group was ``deeply concerned about any 
legislation'' such as Inslee's that would allow consumer opt-outs. 
Consumers could deprive themselves of useful financial services by 
doing so, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The industry believes that disclosure of companies' privacy  
policies is the best way to protect consumers, Ms. Cinelli said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990525.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 21:41:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Democrats Push Finance Privacy Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Imagine a bank and a brokerage firm merge.  
Will bank employees tip off stock brokers every time bank customers 
have sudden increases in their account balances that could be 
invested? 
</P>
<P>
	Now the bank and brokerage merge with an insurance company. Will  
the bank scour customers' account records for signs of risky 
behavior and pass the data to insurance agents, who can raise rates 
on the risk-prone customers' policies? 
</P>
<P>
	These are the kinds of scenarios that frighten some Democratic  
lawmakers, who are pushing legislation that would give consumers 
the right to stop affiliated banks, securities firms and insurers 
from sharing personal financial data among themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	Banks and most of the financial services industry oppose the  
bill by Rep. Jay Inslee, D-Wash., which would allow customers to 
forbid personal data-sharing among affiliated financial companies 
with a written notice. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill embodies a proposal made earlier this month by  
President Clinton, who urged Congress to bolster consumer rights 
when banks and other financial companies seek to share information 
about them. 
</P>
<P>
	As Congress crafts sweeping legislation to remove Depression-era  
barriers among banks, brokerages and insurers and allow them to 
merge, unease is growing about the privacy of people who use the 
new consolidated financial companies. 
</P>
<P>
	``The consumer is naked and helpless in (his) inability to tell  
banks not to share that information,'' Inslee said Tuesday at a 
news conference. ``This is going to allow consumers the right to 
decide their own fate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Inslee also maintained that for online commerce to flourish,  
people must have confidence their privacy will be protected. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate recently passed a financial overhaul bill, attaching  
to it a provision that would make it a federal crime for anyone to 
use misrepresentation to obtain another person's private financial 
data. 
</P>
<P>
	Legislation to rewrite the financial services laws is before a  
House Commerce subcommittee, which has scheduled a drafting session 
for Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Edward Markey, D-Mass., plans to propose an amendment that  
includes Inslee's ``opt out'' provision but goes further by 
prohibiting financial companies from selling personal data to 
outsiders without the customer's written consent. 
</P>
<P>
	The House Banking Committee adopted a version of financial  
overhaul legislation in March that would restrict sharing of 
customers' health information among affiliated companies. The bill 
still would allow customers' transaction data, such as checking 
account history, to be shared despite an opt-out request. Under 
current law, opt-out requests apply to a person's credit history 
but not to transaction data. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumer activists such as Ralph Nader have maintained that  
rewriting financial services laws would create serious privacy 
risks for Americans as banks, brokerages and insurers compile 
profiles of customers' buying habits, hobbies and health data. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, lobbyists for the banking, securities and  
insurance industries have warned that adoption of tough privacy 
measures could kill their support for the overhaul legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, a major reason the industries have been pushing  
financial overhaul is to open numerous opportunities for them to 
market their services by using shared customer data. 
</P>
<P>
	Patricia Cinelli, a spokeswoman for the American Bankers  
Association, said the group was ``deeply concerned about any 
legislation,'' such as Inslee's, that would allow consumer opt 
outs. Customers could deprive themselves of useful financial 
services by doing so, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The industry believes that disclosure of companies' privacy  
policies is the best way to protect consumers, Ms. Cinelli said. 
</P>
<P>
	Declaring their support for Inslee's bill were fellow Democratic  
Reps. Michael Capuano of Massachusetts; Jan Schakowsky of Illinois; 
Barbara Lee, Bob Filner and Pete Stark of California; Lynn Rivers 
of Michigan; Paul Kanjorski and Joe Hoeffel of Pennsylvania; 
Maurice Hinchey of New York; Jim McDermott of Washington; and the 
House's lone independent, Rep. Bernard Sanders of Vermont. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
