<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Courts Female Voters for 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Al Gore is making a special appeal to  
female voters, building a list of thousands of women for a mass 
endorsement the vice president plans to announce next week. 
</P>
<P>
	The pitch came in the form of a letter sent to women across the  
country in recent days that was signed by Democratic Reps. Juanita 
Millender-McDonald of California and Carolyn Maloney of New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``Women will play a pivotal role in the upcoming elections,''  
they write. ``Together, we will elect a president who will place 
the concerns of women at the top of our national agenda.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In outlining what they say are Gore's accomplishments on women's  
issues, the congresswomen cite his support for abortion rights, 
equal pay for women, child care credits for the poor and the Family 
and Medical Leave Act. 
</P>
<P>
	Recipients, who included Democratic Party activists and members  
of abortion rights groups, also got a sheet on which they could log 
their names as supporters of Gore for the Democratic presidential 
nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	The pledge sheet and a similar appeal are also posted on the  
Gore 2000 Web site, next to a photograph of Gore greeting a woman 
holding a child. 
</P>
<P>
	``On issues of importance to American women,'' the Web site  
declares, ``Al Gore has been and continues to be a leader -- a 
champion for women's issues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore plans to announce a ``national women's endorsement'' June 1  
in Washington, D.C., said campaign spokesman Roger Salazar. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's really going to be a broad range of names, from officials  
to grassroots supporters to regular people,'' he said. ``What we're 
hoping to do is have a show of support from women across the 
country for his candidacy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The effort has also given rise to a new group within the  
campaign, Women for Al Gore, to be headed by former Democratic 
National Committee Treasurer Carol Pensky. 
</P>
<P>
	The group will tailor appeals to female voters by highlighting  
Gore's accomplishments on women's issues. 
</P>
<P>
	Stan Moore, president of the Southern California Political  
Scientists' Association, said Gore is seeking to repeat the support 
President Clinton has enjoyed among women voters. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, who campaigned on a range of family issues, won the  
women's vote in a landslide -- 54 percent to 38 percent -- in 1996. 
Gore's letter does not mention Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore faces a primary challenge from former Sen. Bill Bradley,  
but Moore said it appeared Gore was trying to shore up the women's 
vote ``for the longer haul.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The women's vote may be the critical constituency of the  
Democratic Party,'' Moore said. ``If Gore can get as much as 
Clinton got, it certainly gives him a tremendous boost toward the 
presidency.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
