<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ga. Southern Baseball Coach Retires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STATESBORO, Ga. (AP) -- Georgia Southern baseball coach Jack  
Stallings retired Monday after 39 seasons and 1,258 victories. 
</P>
<P>
	He had been the winningest active coach in Division I, and ranks  
fourth overall in career coaching victories. His record of 
1,258-796-5 includes an 858-581-5 record in 24 seasons at Georgia 
Southern. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the decision is in the best interest for me, my wife,  
and the program,'' Stallings said. ``I feel the program needs a 
change in direction. Although, no one at the age of 68 should ever 
have to explain a retirement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Eagles concluded play last weekend with a loss in the  
Southern Conference tournament. Stallings took them to five NCAA 
tournaments, including the College World Series in 1990, and won 
seven conference titles. 
</P>
<P>
	Stallings also coached at Wake Forest and Florida State. A  
player at Wake Forest, Stallings' minor league career in the Boston 
Red Sox organization was cut short by a bout with polio and he 
returned to Wake Forest to complete his studies in 1955 while 
serving as a student coach. 
</P>
<P>
	Inducted into the American Baseball Coaches Association Hall of  
Fame six years ago, Stallings has been active globally for decades 
in baseball instruction. He has coached or advised U.S. teams in 
several international series, including acting as a hitting coach 
for the 1984 U.S. Olympic team. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
