<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> MLS Season Tickets Up 12 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Major League Soccer's season-ticket sales are up  
12 percent this year, but that has only slightly helped its 
attendance numbers so far. 
</P>
<P>
	MLS commissioner Doug Logan said Tuesday the number of season  
tickets for the 12 teams in the 4-year-old American league 
increased from 38,860 to 43,423. The Columbus Crew was responsible 
for the majority -- a record 9,083 tickets, or a 60 percent jump, 
for its new stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	However, through 56 games, average attendance has only climbed  
half a percent to 14,456, which also is ahead of last season's 
final average of 14,312. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides Columbus, the teams showing the biggest increase in  
season ticket sales have been D.C. United (up 31 percent), Colorado 
(up 30 percent) and Miami (up 42 percent). 
</P>
<P>
	``These numbers are very important to us,'' Logan said during  
his weekly conference call. ``Our ultimate success will be 
predicated on how well we do. ... The year 2000 season ticket drive 
starts this week, since it is the way we treat our customers and 
the way we treat our patrons is how we will be remembered when it 
comes time to renew.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Logan said 70 percent of last year's season-ticket holders  
renewed this season. 
</P>
<P>
	This season's attendance leaders are Columbus, Chicago and D.C.  
United, all of which have drawn more than 21,900 per game. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the biggest reasons for the league average not increasing  
more has been the drop of the Los Angeles Galaxy. Last year's 
league leader has seen an average of 7,500 fewer fans through its 
first six games, and is drawing only 14,144 to the Rose Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we've lost in Los Angeles is not season tickets,'' said  
Logan, who noted the team was 1 percent ahead of last year. ``But 
what their attendance problems accent is the importance of season 
tickets. 
</P>
<P>
	``A major market like L.A. with only 2,000 season tickets is not  
enough. ... If you are going to let your business be determined by 
the spontaneous decision-making of your fan on Friday night through 
Sunday morning, then you run the risk of having groups decide not 
to patronize you on a given Sunday evening.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
