<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lemieux Sweetens Deal for Penguins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Mario Lemieux said Tuesday night he has a new  
plan to rescue the financially troubled Pittsburgh Penguins. 
</P>
<P>
	The former star center for the Penguins and NHL Hall of Famer  
said he will file a revised plan before Friday to reorganize the 
team and accept a bigger ownership stake and less cash for what he 
is owed. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux said his deal will convert $20 million of the salary he  
is owed into a larger ownership stake in the team. He said he will 
forgive the remaining $7.5 million he is owed. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is Mario's way of saying, `You want a body-and-soul  
commitment -- here it is,''' said his agent, Tom Reich. ``Those of 
us in the service of Mario Lemieux are planning to play this hand 
until the last breath.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Counting debt and equity, Lemieux's package is worth $100  
million and should be attractive to Penguins' creditors, Reich 
said. The amount of ``fresh money,'' new investment in the team, 
will be $50 million to $60 million, Reich said. The previous 
commitment was $50 million. 
</P>
<P>
	He said talks continue with potential partner Mark Cuban, a  
native of suburban Pittsburgh and founder of the Dallas-based 
Broadcast.com Internet company. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux had previously offered to convert $10 million of what he  
is owed into a stake in the team and take annual payments for the 
rest. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux also said Tuesday night that he offered to buy out the  
remaining $15 million of the Penguins' $24 million lease with SMG, 
which was described in bankruptcy court as the worst in the NHL. 
Steve Halvonik, a spokesman for SMG, did not return a telephone 
call about Lemieux's offer. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux's plan is competing with two others.  
</P>
<P>
	SMG and broadcaster Fox Sports Net Pittsburgh want to own the  
team, make Lemieux chairman of the management committee, pay him $3 
million for a 5 percent stake in the team and give him the the 
possibility of another 5 percent in three years. Fox has a stake in 
the New York Rangers and would have to give that up, NHL attorney 
Jeffrey Levitan said. 
</P>
<P>
	The NHL, which has stated its public endorsement of Lemieux's  
bid, nonetheless has filed a plan that calls for selling the team 
for $85 million to someone the league would not name who would move 
the franchise. Published reports have said the buyer is Seattle 
billionaire Paul Allen, who wants to move the team to Portland, 
Ore. 
</P>
<P>
	Fox spokesman Larry Eldridge said the Fox-SMG group will take a  
look at what Lemieux has offered. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been meeting to try and come up with a workable plan.  
We're evaluating what we've seen today,'' Eldridge said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
