<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Takes on Base Closing Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration's request to close  
more military bases as a cost-saving measure is headed for a 
crucial Senate test. But the plan remains unpopular in the 
Republican-led Senate, even among some Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	The move to close more bases was being led by Sens. John McCain,  
R-Ariz., and Carl Levin, D-Mich., both senior members of the Senate 
Armed Services Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	``I appeal to the better angels of our nature,'' said McCain.  
``Every expert inside government and without says we need to close 
more bases.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Defense Secretary William Cohen contends that closing antiquated  
bases -- many of them Cold War relics -- could save the Pentagon 
nearly $4 billion a year that would be better spent on aircraft 
carriers, jet fighters and other crucial hardware. 
</P>
<P>
	But Congress has always been reluctant to close bases.  
Republicans contend that President Clinton meddled in the process 
to save jobs at bases in vote-rich California and Texas during his 
1996 re-election campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration's proposal for two new rounds of base  
closings -- one in 2001 and another in 2005 -- was rejected earlier 
this month by the Armed Services panel. McCain and Levin are 
seeking to win approval for just one round, in 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	Armed Services Committee Chairman John Warner, R-Va., contended  
it was impossible to create a truly nonpartisan process for 
base-closings, particularly while Clinton remains in office. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it's a new president you want, there will be a new  
president,'' said McCain, a GOP 2000 presidential hopeful himself. 
He noted that, under his and Levin's proposal, an impartial 
commission for deciding which bases to close would not even be 
named until May 2001, well after the 2000 presidential election. 
</P>
<P>
	The debate occurred as the Senate worked on a $288.8 billion  
defense spending bill for the fiscal year that begins next Oct. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, the Senate voted 52-47 to exonerate two American  
military commanders accused of dereliction of duty in the bombing 
of Pearl Harbor. That vote approved an effort by Sen. William Roth, 
R-Del., to restore the reputations of Adm. Husband Kimmel and Gen. 
Walter Short, the two senior commanders of U.S. military forces in 
the Pacific at the time of the December 1941 attack. 
</P>
<P>
	The move would also give them posthumous promotions.  
</P>
<P>
	Roth said Kimmel and Short became the Pentagon's scapegoats for  
the surprise attack. ``They were held responsible for what happened 
in Pearl Harbor. And that is not fair. And that is not just,'' Roth 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Warner, Navy secretary during the Nixon administration,  
strongly opposed the move, suggesting ``both commanders made errors 
in judgment'' and the reprimands should stand. 
</P>
<P>
	On another measure, the Senate rejected, 52-48, an amendment by  
Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., to require the president to obtain 
congressional consent before expanding the conflict in Kosovo with 
ground forces. ``We have seen the erosion of congressional 
authority,'' Specter said. 
</P>
<P>
	Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and other members of  
Clinton's national security team assured senators during a private 
briefing Tuesday that Clinton would not commit to any NATO ground 
offensive without first seeking congressional approval, 
participants said. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, the administration officials told the  
gathering that any attempt by Congress to force him to obtain such 
consent was a likely veto candidate, said Warner. A defense bill to 
be taken up later this week by the House does contain such a 
provision, similar to the Specter proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	On base closings, the existing process calls for Congress to  
authorize a round of closings, then for the independent Base 
Realignment and Closure Commission to select the bases. 
</P>
<P>
	But Republicans contend Clinton poisoned the process to save  
jobs at McClellan Air Force Base in Sacramento, Calif., and Kelly 
Air Force Base in San Antonio, both targets of a 1995 round. The 
administration denies doing anything illegal as it tried to find 
private-sector jobs for base workers. 
</P>
<P>
	Three rounds -- in 1991, 1993 and 1995 -- closed 70 bases and  
depots, causing economic losses to local communities. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., and Minority Leader  
Tom Daschle, D-S.D., oppose the administration's request for new 
base-closing authority 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is S. 1059.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
