<HEADLINE> Allen, Arnault Invest in Datek </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELLEVUE, Wash. (AP) -- Microsoft co-founder Paul Allen and  
French businessman Bernard Arnault are investing $300 million in 
the privately held Internet brokerage firm Datek Online Holdings 
Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Datek Online said Tuesday that Allen's Bellevue-based Vulcan  
Ventures will lead the cash investment, with participation by 
Arnault's private holding company, Group Arnault, and TA 
Associates, a Boston-based venture capital company. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are excited about working closely with Vulcan and having  
access to some of the best and brightest minds in the world,'' said 
Edward Nicoll, president and chief operating officer of Datek 
Online. ``The fact that they have made such a large investment in 
us speaks for itself in terms of our business model.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nicoll said Vulcan, Group Arnault and TA Associates would  
together hold a minority stake in his company, but other terms of 
the investment were not disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
	Founded in 1996, Datek Online is one of the fastest-growing  
online brokers. Customer accounts grew 35 percent in the first 
quarter to 205,109. 
</P>
<P>
	The company recently ran into trouble with the Securities and  
Exchange Commission, which fined Datek $50,000 for falsifying 
financial documents and using customer money to cover corporate 
expenses. 
</P>
<P>
	Allen, a multibillionaire from his Microsoft holdings, has  
invested in dozens of high-tech and Internet companies. Group 
Arnault controls LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton, a luxury 
products company whose brands include Dom Perignon champagne, 
Hennessy cognac, Louis Vuitton luggage and Christian Dior, Givenchy 
and Kenzo perfumes, cosmetics and clothing. 

</P>
</TEXT>
