<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clintons Hit Texas En Route to Fla. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EDINBURG, Texas (AP) -- Escorting Al Gore onto George W. Bush's  
turf, President Clinton today praised the vice president as an 
advocate for poor communities and credited him with helping spark 
an economic rebirth in urban America. ``I am profoundly grateful to 
him,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	The president joined Gore here for an empowerment-zones  
conference at the University of Texas-Pan American. Afterward, 
Clinton and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton departed for Yulee, 
Fla., for a few days of vacation at the White Oak Plantation, where 
reticulated giraffes, cheetahs and rhinos roam. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton and Gore toured the Rio Grande Valley empowerment zone  
and listened to anecdotes about how such zones, launched during 
Clinton's first term, are bringing new jobs and investment to 
neglected urban and rural communities. 
</P>
<P>
	They also launched the Southwest Border Economic Development  
Initiative, which will pump federal resources into poor, rapidly 
expanding border communities. Clinton announced a task force to 
coordinate economic development along the border. The panel will 
report to the vice president. 
</P>
<P>
	The president said Gore has worked tirelessly to cultivate the  
empowerment zones, and his labor has helped turn blighted, 
abandoned areas into hopeful communities ``now flowing with the 
lifeblood of commerce.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a challenge he embraced passionately,'' Clinton said.  
``I am profoundly grateful to him for proving that this is an idea 
whose time had come.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He then yielded the stage to Gore, who Gore announced $32  
million in grants to help 70 communities redevelop brownfields, or 
abandoned, urban industrial sites contaminated by waste. 
</P>
<P>
	The conference is an annual event held by the vice president,  
who is seeking the Democratic presidential nomination. This year's 
gathering allows Gore to test the political temperature in Texas, a 
Republican stronghold where Bush is the popular governor, and he 
wasted no time in cozying up to the voters. 
</P>
<P>
	``I may be from Tennessee, but I feel right at home here  
today,'' Gore said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clintons are going to Florida as guests of the Howard Gilman  
Foundation, which lets groups and individuals use its facilities 
for free, said White House spokesman Joe Lockhart. He said the 
Clintons were invited to the facility, but he did not say why. 
</P>
<P>
	White Oak, located just across the St. Mary's River from the  
Georgia border, sits on a 7,500-acre conservation area. In addition 
to the giraffes, cheetahs and rhinos, it is home to Big Guy, an 
endangered Florida panther injured in an auto accident. 
</P>
<P>
	Those animals stand a better chance of seeing the Clintons than  
any of the reporters tagging along with them. Lockhart said Monday 
that the president and first lady -- traveling without daughter 
Chelsea, who is still in school at Stanford University -- have no 
plans to venture off White Oak's grounds. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clintons plan to linger in Yulee until late Sunday, so they  
can participate in a conference being held at White Oak by the 
Democratic Leadership Council and its think tank, the Progressive 
Policy Institute. 
</P>
<P>
	Lockhart would not say whether that conference -- or for that  
matter, the entire vacation -- would allow the Clintons to discuss 
the first lady's possible Senate bid. 
</P>
<P>
	``You'll have to ask the first couple that,'' Lockhart said  
Monday, prompting one frustrated reporter to reply, ``When will we 
have that opportunity?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton's spokeswoman, Marsha Berry, said the first lady  
plans to rest and relax and that's all. As for whether she would 
cull issues from the Democratic conference for her potential Senate 
campaign, Berry said, ``She did say that she planned to spend some 
time thinking about this. I think she's thinking about that stuff 
all the time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Clintons were to stay at Roseland, a two-story,  
cedar-paneled, five-bedroom house near the St. Mary's River. There, 
they'd have a view of a white rhino who nests nearby with her 
4-month-old calf. And Clinton can either relax beside the pool with 
a good book or play a few rounds on the nine-hole golf course. 
</P>
<P>
	White Oak was created by the late Howard Gilman, chairman and  
chief executive officer of Gilman Paper Co. in nearby St. Mary's, 
Ga., the largest privately held paper and building products company 
in the country. Gilman's father, Charles Gilman, established the 
plantation in 1938 as a family residence. 
</P>
<P>
	now flowing with the lifeblood of commerce. ... the return on  
this investment is more than financial ... we restored the ameican 
dream for many who thot it was out of reach. 
</P>
</TEXT>
