<HEADLINE> Telecom Board Quits After Takeover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- The board of Telecom Italia SpA resigned Tuesday as  
had been expected in the wake of Olivetti SpA's successful hostile 
acquisition of control of Italy's biggest telephone company. 
</P>
<P>
	It was not immediately clear whether Telecom's chief executive,  
Franco Bernabe, had also stepped down. Bernabe was a board member. 
</P>
<P>
	Olivetti prevailed Saturday in its uninvited takeover of the  
huge telecommunications company. Olivetti, which is a fifth the 
size of Telecom, won a 52 percent stake in the company. 
</P>
<P>
	Italy's Industry Minister Pierluigi Bersani said he would meet  
with Roberto Colaninno, Olivetti's chief executive, to ``exchange 
opinions'' on how to proceed. Colaninno also plans to meet with 
union leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	The new management is already under pressure to produce fast  
results in terms of development and job creation. 
</P>
<P>
	Olivetti is still waiting for word from the Italian government  
that it will stick to its pledge not to use its so-called golden 
share -- a 3.4 percent stake in Telecom -- to veto the takeover. 
</P>
</TEXT>
