<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Missouri Dairy Recalls Cheese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A small Missouri dairy is recalling 135 pounds  
of specialty cheese that may be contaminated with dangerous 
listeria. 
</P>
<P>
	Morningland Dairy Farms Inc., based in Mountain View, Mo., said  
the U.S. Food and Drug Administration has temporarily closed its 
cheese-making operations. 
</P>
<P>
	In Raleigh, N.C., state officials reported a recall of a  
quantity of imported cheese after tests found evidence of the same 
bacteria in it. Routine testing at a grocery store revealed the 
Listeria monocytogenes pathogen in Pinna Ricotta Salata Cheese, 
made with 100% sheep's milk. 
</P>
<P>
	The Missouri recall involved Morningland Dairy Chives Colby  
Cheese, which authorities said should be returned for refunds to 
retailers who sold it. The cheese is made from raw milk, and 
contamination showed up in tests by federal health officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Calls to the company went unanswered Tuesday. A recorded message  
said: ``The FDA has temporarily shut down the cheese-making 
facility. We will not be shipping for a couple weeks for sure. Call 
us back after that to find out how we are doing. Sorry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Listeria can cause serious, potentially fatal, infections in  
young children, the elderly and people with weak immune systems. It 
also can cause miscarriages. Healthy people, however, usually 
suffer short-term symptoms, including diarrhea, nausea, abdominal 
pain and fever. 
</P>
<P>
	The recalled Colby cheese, sold in vacuum-packed plastic bags,  
carries the code A259 on the label. It was sold by mail and in 
retail stores in Missouri, Colorado, Utah, Illinois, Arizona, 
Tennessee, New York, California, Georgia, Maryland, Pennsylvania 
and South Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	No illnesses have been reported from the cheese recalled in  
North Carolina, which was imported from Italy distributed by Anco 
Foods of Fairfield, N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	The Food and Drug Protection Division of the North Carolina  
Department of Agriculture and Consumer Services advised consumers 
not to use the product in packaging bearing the code ``Sell by Sep 
18, 99.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The cheese also may have been distributed in South Carolina,  
Georgia, Florida, Alabama, Mississippi, Louisiana and Tennessee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
