<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GAO: Forest Serv. Lobbied Illegally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Forest Service lobbied illegally to try to  
boost road funds and change the way it distributes county aid, 
according to congressional investigators. 
</P>
<P>
	A regional forester in Michigan told interest groups last year  
to ``let Congress know'' of the need to boost funds for roads in 
national forests, the General Accounting Office said in a report 
released Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Forest Service also asked regional foresters to contact  
Congress, state officials, interest groups and the news media last 
year to build support for a proposal to freeze payments to counties 
and no longer link the payments to timber harvests, the GAO said. 
</P>
<P>
	The actions violated the 1998 Interior Appropriations Act, which  
bars federal officials from using taxpayer dollars to lobby for or 
against legislation, according to the GAO, Congress' investigative 
arm. 
</P>
<P>
	The lobbying prohibition has been included in every interior  
appropriations bill since 1977. 
</P>
<P>
	But the GAO found ``no evidence that Forest Service employees  
were aware that they were violating the law.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The GAO recommended that Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman, who  
oversees the Forest Service, develop guidelines on lobbying and 
educate agency employees about the guidelines. 
</P>
<P>
	Glickman said in a statement Monday his agency is developing  
guidelines that ``will provide employees with better information 
about prohibited activities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alaska's two Republican senators, Frank Murkowski and Don Young,  
requested the GAO investigation. They said the report raises 
serious concerns, but praised Glickman's response. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has our support for making the changes necessary,'' the  
lawmakers said. 
</P>
<P>
	Murkowski chairs the Senate Energy and Natural Resources  
Committee and Young chairs the House Resources Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawmakers requested and received about 1,500 Forest Service  
documents after some Republicans complained that a leaked 
communication plan suggested the agency was mixing politics with 
professional duties. 
</P>
<P>
	Murkowski and Young, in contacting the GAO last November, said  
the documents contained evidence of lobbying. 
</P>
<P>
	Forest Service officials initially predicted the Republican  
investigation would turn into ``quite an expensive fishing 
expedition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Capitol Hill Republicans and Forest Service officials have  
clashed before. Republicans have faulted the agency's for a 
troubled accounting system, a lack of detailed legislative 
proposals and sharp cutbacks in logging on federal land. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
