<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Federated-WeddingChannel.Com Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Federated Department Stores Inc. is linking  
its bridal registries with online wedding planner 
WeddingChannel.com. 
</P>
<P>
	In the deal announced Tuesday, Federated also will buy a 20  
percent stake in WeddingChannel.com, a Los Angeles-based company. 
Terms were not announced. 
</P>
<P>
	The arrangement will link bridal registries from Federated's 403  
department stores and online sites with WeddingChannel.com's 
offerings, which include personalized Web pages, travel planning, 
local business directories and a database of bridal fashions. 
</P>
<P>
	Couples will be able to register with Federated stores and  
guests will be able to purchase gifts through WeddingChannel.com. 
Federated will continue to offer bridal registries in its stores. 
</P>
<P>
	WeddingChannel.com has also formed a sales and marketing  
partnership with Conde Nast's Bride's Magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	Federated, based in Cincinnati, has annual sales of more than  
$17.3 billion. The company operates stores in 33 states under the 
names of Bloomingdale's, The Bon Marche, Burdines, Goldsmith's, 
Lazarus, Macy's, Rich's and Stern's. Federated also operates the 
Fingerhut, Bloomingdale's By Mail, Macy's By Mail and Macys.com 
catalog and electronic commerce subsidiaries. 
</P>
<P>
	Competitors are also after more of the bridal registry business.  
Last month, an online business called theknot.com announced that it 
was receiving a $15 million investment from the television retailer 
QVC. 
</P>
<P>
	While thousands of couples use the Internet for wedding  
research, the online market is still only a fraction of the $35 
billion spent on weddings each year in the United States. But 
analysts expect sales to jump sharply in the next few years, with 
much of the gain expected from guests buying wedding gifts online. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
