<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sen. Won't Block Summers Nomination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A senator who wants the Clinton administration  
to do more to protect the U.S. steel industry won't try to block 
the nomination of Lawrence Summers to be treasury secretary, a 
spokesman for the senator said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio, ``has no plans to do this and has  
ruled out this option,'' said his spokesman, Charlie Boesel. 
</P>
<P>
	Boesel said he had misstated his boss' position earlier in the  
day when he told The Associated Press and other news organizations 
that DeWine was considering putting a ``hold'' on the nomination, 
which would have blocked the Senate from voting on it. 
</P>
<P>
	Summers' nomination to replace outgoing Secretary Robert Rubin  
is subject Senate confirmation. 
</P>
<P>
	DeWine and other senators want the administration to do more to  
help U.S. steel companies, which contend that they've had to close 
plants and cut jobs because of a flood of steel imports coming into 
the United States from Russia, Japan, South Korea and other 
countries. 
</P>
<P>
	A Treasury Department spokeswoman declined to comment on  
Summers' nomination and issues related to it. 
</P>
<P>
	DeWine and other steel-state senators, including John  
Rockefeller, D-W.Va., have offered legislation that would use 
different approaches to address the matter, their aides said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rockefeller, a member of the Senate Finance Committee, which  
will consider Summers' nomination, ``intends to ask Summers very 
tough questions about steel in confirmation hearings,'' said 
Rockefeller's spokesman, Don Marshall. 
</P>
<P>
	But Rockefeller has no plans to try to hold up or block Summers'  
nomination, Marshall said. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., has said he saw no  
problems with the nomination. And, the Finance Committee chairman, 
Sen. William Roth, R-Del., has said his panel had had a ``good 
working relationship'' with him. 
</P>
<P>
	The Finance Committee has not yet scheduled hearings on the  
nomination, since President Clinton has not formally submitted it 
to the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Summers, 44, joined Treasury in 1993 as undersecretary for  
international affairs. He has served since 1995 as deputy to Rubin, 
who announced his resignation earlier this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
