<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Complaints Against Customs Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- While allegations of wrongdoing against U.S.  
Customs Service employees were increasing threefold since 1996, the 
agency wasn't even tracking the outcome of the cases, a Senate 
analysis says. 
</P>
<P>
	And, at the same time the number of cases was zooming, the  
percentage referred to prosecutors dropped significantly, according 
to the study by the Senate Finance Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	William A. Keefer, assistant commissioner in charge of internal  
affairs, told the committee that while instances of corruption in 
customs are few, ``We may not have always done a good job in 
responding to allegations of misconduct. That has changed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In testimony prepared for the hearing, Keefer said that under a  
prior system, offices within Customs reported misconduct in ways 
that were ``diverse and often confusing.'' He said the agency now 
has a uniform system for reporting alleged wrongdoing and a new 
computerized operation to track cases moving through the 
disciplinary process. 
</P>
<P>
	He added that the word has gone out to all Customs investigators  
that ``failure to exhaust viable leads or to interview 
knowledgeable witnesses is inexcusable'' in misconduct cases. 
</P>
<P>
	The analysis was obtained by The Associated Press on Monday,  
prior to today's committee hearing on the agency's internal affairs 
operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Only last week, the Treasury Department inspector general  
released a stinging audit of the Customs internal affairs unit, 
contending the agents mismanaged investigations and created a fear 
of reprisal among employees filing complaints. The Customs Service 
is a Treasury Department agency. 
</P>
<P>
	On the eve of the hearing, leaders of two groups claiming to  
represent 2,000 customs employees announced plans to pursue a class 
action lawsuit alleging retaliation against workers who complained 
of sexual harassment, racial discrimination and other wrongdoing. 
At a news conference in Riverside, Calif., Customs agent Sandy Nunn 
said internal investigations and job transfers are used to punish 
employees who complain. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate committee found that bribery was the most frequent  
allegation to the internal affairs unit and that Miami employees 
were the subjects of the most complaints. 
</P>
<P>
	Customs Commissioner Raymond Kelly contended Monday that ``no  
systemic corruption'' exists within the agency. 
</P>
<P>
	But in his six-page letter to the Senate Finance Committee  
chairman, Sen. William Roth, R-Del., Kelly also said he has 
initiated ``greatly strengthened internal affairs procedures ... 
which demand accountability and provide us with the tools to 
monitor all cases from their inception to final disposition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kelly's spokesman, Dennis Murphy, added, ``He appointed a career  
Justice Department official to run the (internal affairs) 
organization and a nationwide disciplinary review board to ensure 
fairness and protection for people to come forward.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Based on information provided by the 19,500-employee Customs  
Service, the committee analysis showed that from fiscal 1996 
through fiscal 1998: 
</P>
<P>
	--Allegations of criminal wrongdoing and serious, noncriminal  
misconduct against Customs employees increased from 209 to 677, or 
223 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--Of 696 cases of potential wrongdoing referred by internal  
affairs investigators to agency management, 69 percent had no 
information on the disposition of the cases. Of those that had such 
information, the highest percentage category was ``no action'' (29 
percent) followed by suspensions (22 percent). 
</P>
<P>
	--The percentage of allegations referred for prosecution declined  
from 78 percent to 17 percent for the most serious category of 
accusations, including potentially major crimes; and from 29 
percent to 8 percent for less serious actions. 
</P>
<P>
	--The most common allegation was bribery (114 cases) followed by  
various forms of harassment (95 cases) and disclosure of 
confidential information (77). 
</P>
<P>
	--Allegations most frequently involved inspectors (29 percent of  
the total), criminal investigators (12 percent) and supervisory 
criminal investigators (7 percent). One percent, or 18 allegations, 
involved assistant commissioners. 
</P>
<P>
	--Miami had the most allegations, (11 percent of the total),  
followed by El Paso and McAllen, Texas, (9 percent each), Tucson, 
Ariz., (6 percent), Los Angeles and San Francisco (5 percent each) 
and San Diego (4 percent). 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, the inspector general's report said the Customs  
Service created ``a fear of reprisal'' among employees who reported 
wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	The internal affairs unit mishandled investigations so that  
wayward agents were neither disciplined nor prosecuted, the 
Treasury inspector general said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
