<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Groups Continue LA Expansion Debate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Al Davis, who moved his Raiders back to Oakland  
in 1995 after 13 seasons in Los Angeles, is an onlooker during the 
NFL's discussions on bringing a team back to the nation's second 
largest market. 
</P>
<P>
	But the league's maverick seemed to catch the essence of the  
latest debate. 
</P>
<P>
	``They spent four years, and all their talking about is  
garages,'' Davis said Tuesday after two groups competing for the 
expansion franchise that will begin play in 2002 presented their 
plans to the owners. 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, garages are at the heart of how the NFL will refurbish  
the Los Angeles Coliseum to bring an expansion team there by 2002. 
And the one that seems to be preferred by the NFL leadership could 
cost more than $200 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The group headed by Hollywood agent Michael Ovitz presented a  
plan for a parking garage with a park on top. The project features 
a garage covered with trees, grass in front of luxury suites and a 
cooling system that would spray mist on sweltering fans. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's exactly the kind of vision necessary to transform the  
venue in the interests of the city of Los Angeles,'' commissioner 
Paul Tagliabue said. 
</P>
<P>
	The other major action Tuesday was the unanimous approval of the  
sale of the Washington Redskins to 34-year-old Daniel Snyder for 
$800 million, the highest for a franchise in sports history. 
</P>
<P>
	``Wow!'' exulted Snyder, a lifelong Redskins fan. ``It's been an  
unbelievable journey.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Snyder was a junior partner to Howard Milstein in a previous bid  
to buy the team from the trustees of the late Jack Kent Cooke. 
</P>
<P>
	When Milstein pulled out after it became clear he couldn't win  
support from other owners, Snyder went his own way. He brought in 
Fred Drasner and Mort Zuckerman, co-owners of the Daily News in New 
York. 
</P>
<P>
	Snyder's bid was the same as Milstein's. But he backed it with a  
$300 million down payment that sold the rest of the owners. 
</P>
<P>
	The previous high price for a franchise was the $550 million Al  
Lerner paid for the new Cleveland Browns, who will begin playing in 
September as the NFL's 31st team. 
</P>
<P>
	The Redskins sale has been a long-running soap opera since the  
team was put up for sale by the trustees of the estate of Jack Kent 
Cooke, who died in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Cooke's son, John, was one of the bidders when Milstein got the  
franchise. When Milstein dropped out, he sued John Cooke and 
general manager Charley Casserly. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has been a long goodbye,'' Cooke said. ``As disappointing  
as it has been, it has also been very gratifying to hear how much 
my family has meant to the National Football League and Redskins 
fans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Snyder has said that for this season he will retain Casserly and  
coach Norv Turner. He also expects to hire a team president soon, 
but not necessarily someone from football, although one of those 
mentioned is former Miami coach Don Shula. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's agenda includes a demonstration of instant replay,  
further discussion of the Los Angeles situation and stadium 
situations in New England, Philadelphia and Denver. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
