<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Says EU Tax May Hurt Bonds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- Britain fought a rearguard action  
Tuesday against plans for European Union nations to impose a 20 
percent tax on savings and investments which London claims could 
harm international bond dealing worth billions of dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	At a meeting of EU finance ministers Britain's Chancellor of the  
Exchequer Gordon Brown restated his opposition to the plan, which 
could jeopardize the lucrative ``Eurobond'' market, which is 
primarily based in London. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown said he would present proposals next month to exempt  
Eurobonds from the new tax, and said he was confident the other 14 
EU nations would agreed. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe that we are making progress,'' Brown told reporters.  
``People are beginning to understand what Britain has been saying 
all along.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The EU has been trying for years to plug tax loopholes that  
enable investors to skip national taxes by moving money around the 
bloc to centers offering low tax incentives to foreign investors -- 
particularly London and Luxembourg. 
</P>
<P>
	Germany in particular says Luxembourg's refusal to introduce  
taxes on interest earned from savings costs it billions of marks in 
lost revenue every year. 
</P>
<P>
	German Finance Minister Hans Eichel, who chaired Monday's  
meeting, was cautiously optimistic a deal could be wrapped up by 
the end of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Although most EU nations support the call for a common 20  
percent tax, all tax issues need unanimous agreement from the 15 
nations and Britain and Luxembourg are resisting the move, fearing 
it will simply lead to a flight to low-tax centers outside the EU, 
such as Switzerland. 
</P>
<P>
	Luxembourg is also seeking exemptions from the tax for  
investment funds and similar instruments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
