<DOCNO> APW19990525.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 16:22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stars' Desperate Play Evens Series </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Playing with desperation and a street-fighter  
mentality, the Dallas Stars delivered a message to the Colorado 
Avalanche: This will be a long, tough playoff series. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stars squared the Western Conference final with Monday  
night's 4-2 victory in Dallas. The best-of-7 series shifts to 
Denver for Games 3 and 4 on Wednesday and Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were a desperate team and they had to be,'' Avalanche  
forward Theo Fleury said, referring to the Stars losing Game 1 at 
home. ``They threw everything at us in the third period.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The bottom line is, this is the semifinals,'' Dallas center  
Guy Carbonneau said Tuesday. ``You play each shift as if it were 
your last.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Joe Nieuwendyk and Mike Modano scored in the Stars' dominating  
third period, when they outshot Colorado 15-1. For the game, Dallas 
outshot Colorado 45-19. 
</P>
<P>
	``We finally found some seams and cracks through the defense to  
get to the net,'' Modano said. ``The second and third shots were 
finally there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said his team's more aggressive  
approach on Monday night was by design. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think for us to play well, we have to press the pace,'' he  
said. ``It doesn't matter who we're playing. We've played two 
pretty good hockey games. Unfortunately, we lost the first one. I 
thought the difference was we played with desperation, knowing our 
status. We took some chances and we didn't get hurt by it. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you're playing a team as good and as skilled as Colorado,  
you can take one of two attitudes -- either stand back and wait and 
hope that's going to work out, or press the issue. Obviously, by 
the way we played, we've made the decision to press the issue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of a suffocating defensive game, Modano felt as if he  
had been turned loose Monday night. That observation drew a chuckle 
from Hitchcock. 
</P>
<P>
	``He might think he's been turned loose, but he's not,''  
Hitchcock said. ``This is just a different series. There just is no 
play in the neutral zone. It's in one end or the other. The games 
are very similar to the way we play against Phoenix. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the series against St. Louis, there was a tremendous amount  
of counter-attacking and neutral zone play. In this series, there 
is none. So the feeling is that there's a lot of room because 
you're coming through that area between the two blue lines with a 
lot of speed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked to explain Colorado's somewhat lackluster play in Game 2,  
Hitchcock said, ``They got what they wanted. They got the split in 
our building.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Now, we have to come in here and do that, too. And if our  
attitude is we're going to weather the storm, then that's the wrong 
attitude because we're going to be on our heels all night. We have 
to go and attack,'' he said. ``It's going to make for some 
high-risk hockey, and I think their team probably has the same 
attitude.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dallas lost forward Benoit Hogue for the remainder of the  
playoffs after he tore knee ligaments in the first period. 
</P>
<P>
	The Avalanche, meanwhile, were hopeful of getting back center  
Stephane Yelle, their best penalty-killer. Yelle has been sidelined 
since May 3 with a sprained left knee. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's probably going to be a game-time decision,'' Colorado  
coach Bob Hartley said. 
</P>
<P>
	Yelle, who skated for the fifth straight day on Tuesday, said  
his injury ``has been improving and I've been feeling more and more 
comfortable. I want to get back. It's been tough to sit and watch 
the guys play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Besides cutting down on the number of shots faced by goalie  
Patrick Roy, the Avalanche were eager to get more production from 
Fleury and Joe Sakic, normally two of their most prolific scorers. 
</P>
<P>
	Fleury's assist Monday night was his first point since Game 3 of  
the Detroit series. Sakic has just one goal and one assist in 
Colorado's last eight playoff games. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've had some great chances as a line,'' Fleury said. ``The  
puck is just not going in, for some reason. We're too good of 
players not to get on the scoreboard. We're doing all the right 
things. It's just a matter of time. But Milan is playing great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Milan Hejduk, a rookie and Fleury's linemate, scored his sixth  
goal of the playoffs Monday night. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
