<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Serbs Demand End to Army Protests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- The Yugoslav army today banned  
anti-war demonstrations and threatened to court-martial deserters 
if they don't return immediately, local media reported. In Kosovo, 
fierce fighting was reported today between the army and ethnic 
Albanian rebels. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO's bombing campaign entered its third month today with  
missiles striking the abandoned Serb police headquarters in 
Belgrade and other targets across Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	For days, citizens of several central Serbian cities have been  
demonstrating against the war and protesting the conscription of 
male relatives to fight in Kosovo. Several hundred reservists who 
deserted and returned home joined some of the protests. 
</P>
<P>
	The army was previously conciliatory, saying deserters would not  
be punished. But the comments today in the daily Vijesti were 
harsher, warning that those failing to return by noon today would 
be court-martialed by a war court. 
</P>
<P>
	The statement also warned against illegal public gatherings,  
saying reaction will be ``robust and the violators will be 
punished.'' As many as 2,000 people rallied Monday in two central 
Serbian towns to protest the draft. Police also detained three 
leaders of an anti-war movement. 
</P>
<P>
	The English-language V.I.P. newsletter reported fierce fighting  
in much of Kosovo, especially in the west, where Yugoslav forces 
were trying to regain positions lost to the rebel Kosovo Liberation 
Army. 
</P>
<P>
	Kosovo is a province in Serbia, the main republic in Yugoslavia.  
The NATO bombing campaign aims to force President Slobodan 
Milosevic to accept a peace deal for the troubled province that 
would include withdrawing his forces and allowing NATO-led 
peacekeepers to police the accord. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Yugoslav capital of Belgrade, water reserves dropped to  
the only 8 percent today because of damaged pumping stations and a 
power outage, Serbian media reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Poor weather hampered NATO's military operation today, but jets  
still struck several artillery emplacements, military vehicles, a 
radar site and a logistics support base. 
</P>
<P>
	Many strikes focused on command and control facilities,  
including Milosevic's villa at Dobanovci, 12 miles west of 
Belgrade, NATO said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jets also fired at Mount Cer, 60 miles west of Belgrade, where a  
key communication transmitter is located; at the Batajnica military 
airport northwest of Belgrade; and in the suburb of Rakovica, the 
site of a large underground military complex, state media reported. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO troops also began relocating 30,000 Kosovo refugees today  
from Albania's northern border to safer camps deeper inside the 
country, fearing attacks from nearby Serb forces. 
</P>
<P>
	In one of several recent incidents, U.N. spokesman Rupert  
Colville noted that two bullets fired from inside Kosovo struck the 
refugee reception center Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're trying to empty these camps as soon as possible for a  
whole variety of reasons. The most important is danger,'' Colville 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 830,000 ethnic Albanian refugees have fled Kosovo to  
neighboring Albania and Macedonia -- with 20,000 arriving in 
Macedonia in the last four days alone. 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslav leaders have remained defiant, with the country's U.N.  
envoy rejecting a key NATO demand that NATO troops police any peace 
deal for Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be really unthinkable for one sovereign country to  
allow its own destroyers to play the role of peacemakers or 
peacekeepers,'' envoy Vladislav Jovanovic said. 
</P>
<P>
	If NATO troops enter Yugoslavia, he warned that ``nobody could  
guarantee the safety of those people because of the outrage of the 
population.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While British officials have recommended that NATO prepare to  
send ground troops into Kosovo -- whether a diplomatic solution has 
been reached or not -- NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana said 
today the air campaign is working. But Solana did not dismiss the 
possibility of deploying ground troops. 
</P>
<P>
	``All options are open,'' Solana said in an interview with  
Europe 1 radio. And the option of ground troops is ``on the 
table,'' he added. 
</P>
<P>
	A U.N. fact-finding mission returned from Kosovo and reported  
that conditions in the province were ``a lot worse than we 
feared.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Everything indicates that there is an attempt to displace,  
ethnically cleanse Kosovo,'' said Sergio de Mello, head of the U.N. 
mission, calling the scale of the crisis ``gigantic.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
