<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> La. Candidate's Grandson Missing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CASCADE LOCKS, Ore. (AP) -- Just days before a tight runoff  
election for Congress, former Louisiana Gov. Dave Treen canceled 
all campaign appearances Tuesday to join a search in the Oregon 
wilderness for his grandson. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 30 searchers and divers fanned out over the steep,  
wooded trails and waterfalls in the Columbia Gorge for 20-year-old 
Jason Neville, who failed to return Saturday from a two-day hiking 
trip. 
</P>
<P>
	``The campaign is not on my mind at this point,'' Treen, 70,  
said Tuesday afternoon, after arriving at the trailhead where his 
grandson began his trip. ``There's nothing I would not do or give 
up to find Jason.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Treen faces a runoff Saturday back in Louisiana against fellow  
Republican David Vitter to succeed former Rep. Bob Livingston. They 
were the top two vote-getters in a May 1 primary in which former Ku 
Klux Klan leader David Duke finished third. 
</P>
<P>
	Treen arrived in Portland by private jet with his daughter,  
Jennifer Neville, the missing hiker's mother. They were driven to 
the search area accompanied by a state trooper and, after meeting 
with search and rescue officials, spoke to reporters arm in arm. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to stay here until we find him,'' said Treen,  
optimistic that his grandson would be found. ``Jason is not foolish 
in any way. That gives me the most confidence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The search was suspended Tuesday evening and was to resume  
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Neville is from Mandeville, La., but lives in Portland and works  
for AmeriCorps, the domestic equivalent of the Peace Corps. He had 
taken time off from college to teach poor children in Portland to 
read. 
</P>
<P>
	He set out alone Thursday evening on the Eagle Creek trail, one  
of Oregon's most popular hiking routes, near the river town of 
Cascade Locks, about 40 miles east of Portland. Officials said he 
wanted to be by himself in the wilderness when he turned 20 at 
midnight Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	His friends were supposed to pick him up Saturday. When he  
didn't show up, they assumed he had decided to hike another day. 
Crews began searching for him on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The trails he planned to take have some steep sections with  
drops of hundreds of feet. Friends said he had food and a sleeping 
bag with him but authorities described Neville as a novice 
outdoorsman. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday, searchers began focusing on off-trail areas after  
receiving two sighting reports of someone believed to be Neville. 
Earlier in the day, they brought in equipment to search pools below 
several waterfalls. 
</P>
<P>
	``The worst-case scenario is that he took a fall,'' said Stan  
Hinatsu, a U.S. Forest Service spokesman. ``The best-case scenario 
is that he's sitting on a trail somewhere, disoriented and not sure 
which way to go.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
