<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IBM Program To Be Sold With Linux </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A popular IBM program for network databases will  
be sold with a Linux operating system in a deal giving the upstart 
software added legitimacy in a market dominated by Microsoft's 
Windows NT. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement to bundle TurboLinux and IBM's best-selling DB2  
Universal Database program was announced today by Pacific HiTech, 
one of many small companies selling a version of Linux. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies also agreed to collaborate on making future  
editions of IBM server software, often referred to as 
``middleware,'' and TurboLinux work together more smoothly. 
</P>
<P>
	For now, Linux poses only a marginal threat to Windows NT as the  
No. 1 software platform for the servers that run computer networks. 
</P>
<P>
	But an affiliation with DB2, which recently eclipsed Oracle8 as  
the top database application for those machines, marks a new level 
of legitimacy for Linux, which is a fan favorite among software 
developers, but relatively new to the business world. 
</P>
<P>
	``It takes more than just an operating system to run a computing  
environment effectively,'' said John B. Jones Jr., an industry 
analyst for Salomon Smith Barney, noting surveys showing that data 
processing is a top priority among server operators. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the Linux space, the No. 1 prerequisite is database  
software, and IBM has the No. 1 position in the database market,'' 
he said, referring to Tuesday's deal as ``one more incremental 
benefit to the people who are considering using Linux.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Linux code, developed by Linus Torvalds in the early 1990s  
when he was a student in Finland, is best known for being a system 
that rarely crashes. 
</P>
<P>
	But it was relatively unknown until recently, when big names  
such as Intel, IBM, Netscape, and Oracle began investing in Red 
Hat, a leading vendor of Linux software, based in Durham, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1998, the Linux server market grew by 212 percent with more  
than 500,000 copies shipped, according to International Data 
Corporation, an industry research firm. 
</P>
<P>
	The basic code, continually updated in consultation with an  
enthusiastic community of programmers, is still given away for free 
over the Internet or can be bought at stores for as little as $30. 
</P>
<P>
	Enhanced versions such as TurboLinux can sell for about $200.  
</P>
<P>
	No pricing for the DB2-TurboLinux was disclosed. DB2 typically  
sells for about $8,000 per copy. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have customers in every geography asking for Linux  
solutions,'' said Dick Sullivan, a vice president for IBM Software. 
``Collaborations like our agreement with Pacific HiTech will help 
IBM bring enterprise solutions to our customers faster and with the 
same high level of support for Linux as we provide for other 
operating systems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pacific HiTech, based in san Francisco, shipped about 1 million  
units of TurboLinux last year, but mostly in Asia. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990525.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 13:52:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Consumer Confidence Up for 7th Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Consumer confidence rose in May for a  
record-setting seventh consecutive month, suggesting that the 
economy will remain robust, the Conference Board said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Low inflation and a strong job market are providing a durable  
foundation for historically high levels of consumer confidence,'' 
said Lynn Franco, associate director of the business group's 
Consumer Research Center. ``Consumers continue to project healthy 
economic growth, and their hefty batting average over the last 
three decades suggests it would be unwise to challenge them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate report released Tuesday, an organization of  
industrial executives forecast the manufacturing economy will be 
even stronger in the second half of this year than in the first six 
months, with little significant pickup in inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Association of Purchasing Management said 55  
percent of the members polled in its semiannual survey said they 
believe business in the final half of 1999 will be better than in 
the first half, up from 46 percent in a survey six months ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly two-thirds believe revenues will be higher this year than  
last, but they predict a net increase of just 4.3 percent -- the 
lowest forecast since May 1996, it said. The organization said 
there are minimal expectations for increased prices of supplies 
this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, the National Association of Realtors released a  
report that showed the spring rise in mortgage rates took a toll on 
home sales, but that activity remained strong. 
</P>
<P>
	The real estate group said sales of existing single-family homes  
fell 3.3 percent in April to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 
5.24 million units from March's 5.42 million record level. Still, 
the April figure was 6.3 percent above the pace of April 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest reports had a brief, calming effect on financial  
markets, which were buffeted by investor concerns over Internet 
stocks. The Dow Jones industrial average, at one point up almost 
100 points, not only surrendered all of its gains but closed down 
123.58, a drop of 1.2 percent, at 10,531.09. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumer sentiment is an important economic indicator because  
consumer spending accounts for about two-thirds of the nation's 
overall economic activity. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan, speaking Monday night  
to the National Retail Federation, said the strength in consumer 
spending, depends not just on the wealth effect generated by rising 
stock prices but from strong home sales. 
</P>
<P>
	``On the sale of a home, you tend to realize very large capital  
gains -- on average, that has been something in excess of $35,000,'' 
Greenspan said. ``When you are talking about 4 million (home) 
sales, that's a very large number.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Conference Board said its consumer confidence index rose to  
135.8 in May from a revised 135.5 in April, reaching the highest 
level since July 1998 when it stood at 137.2. Most Wall Street 
analysts had expected the index to be unchanged in May. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the crisis in Kosovo and increases in gas prices,  
confidence rose for a seventh consecutive month, a performance that 
the business-financed study group said was ``the longest uptrend in 
the 32-year history of the survey.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gary Thayer, chief economist at A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons Inc.  
investment company in St. Louis, said ``consumers are feeling 
good'' and that was showing up in the index. 
</P>
<P>
	``The job situation is the primary factor,'' he said.  
``Unemployment is low, those who want to work can. Wages are rising 
faster than inflation, so consumers are getting ahead.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he did not believe this was a sign of overheating that  
some fear could prompt the Fed to raise interest rates -- a move the 
Fed recently said it might consider to keep inflationary pressures 
in check. 
</P>
<P>
	``Productivity gains have been offsetting wage gains -- and  
that's the ultimate thing that the Fed is watching,'' Thayer said. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest report showed 44 percent of those surveyed in May say  
current business conditions are ``good,'' while only 8.4 percent 
characterized them as ``bad.'' That was slightly more optimistic 
than in April. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 12.8 percent of respondents in May said jobs would be hard  
to get, about the same as the 12.7 percent of the preceding month. 
</P>
<P>
	Expectations for upcoming months continued to rise. A separate  
index designed to measure consumer expectations for the next six to 
nine months increased to 109.3 in May from a revised 108.8 in 
April, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	The consumer confidence index, started in 1967, is compiled from  
responses to questions sent to 5,000 households nationwide. The 
survey polls consumers on matters ranging from job prospects to 
buying plans. 
</P>
<P>
	The index compares results to its base year, 1985, when it stood  
at 100. 
</P>
</TEXT>
