<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Smoke Ban Won't Hurt Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Contrary to what the tobacco industry says,  
smoking bans in restaurants do not hurt tourism and may even help, 
a study says. 
</P>
<P>
	``This will only further the trend to clean indoor air,'' said  
Elva Yanez, associate director of Americans for Non Smokers' 
Rights. 
</P>
<P>
	Yanez called the study being published in Wednesday's Journal of  
the American Medical Association the first of its kind. 
</P>
<P>
	Stanton A. Glantz, a tobacco industry critic and professor of  
medicine at University of California, San Francisco, and Annemarie 
Charlesworth also of UC, studied hotel revenues as a measure of 
tourism in three states and six cities. 
</P>
<P>
	In each location, opponents of smoking bans claimed tourism  
would suffer once restaurants and bars went smoke-free. 
</P>
<P>
	Glantz and Charlesworth looked at hotel revenues before and  
after the smoking bans took effect. They found the rate of revenue 
increased in four spots, stayed the same in four others and 
increased more slowly in one -- Flagstaff, Ariz. 
</P>
<P>
	``It won't stop these front groups from making the claims but  
people can now say there's actual data out there collected by a 
third party,'' Glantz said of his findings. 
</P>
<P>
	Tom Humber, president of the Arlington, Va.-based group the  
National Smokers Alliance, called the study ``an advocacy piece 
masquerading as research.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said it used ``too broad an ax, too broad a methodology to  
understand what is going on in very specific circumstances.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Humber cited San Francisco as an example. There, sidewalk and  
outdoor dining -- which is exempt from the nonsmoking law -- has 
flourished since the ban, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Glantz said the research ``is not a detailed study of the  
dynamics of the hotel or tourism industry. ... This is a paper 
designed to test the veracity of claims that if these things 
passed, the tourism industry would be negatively impacted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The study looked at California, Utah and Vermont; all three  
passed smoke-free ordinances in 1995. It also looked at New York 
City, Los Angeles, San Francisco, Mesa and Flagstaff, Ariz., and 
Boulder, Colo. 
</P>
<P>
	Los Angeles and Flagstaff passed smoking bans in 1983, while the  
other cities passed theirs in 1995 and 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Hotel revenue rates stayed the same in California, Vermont,  
Boulder and San Francisco. They increased in Utah, Los Angeles, New 
York City and Mesa. 
</P>
<P>
	Kathleen Harrington, who owns a third-generation restaurant and  
bar, said she saw her bottom line drop 10 percent after San 
Francisco's ban was passed in 1995. Since she opened an outdoor 
patio where people can smoke, she said her profits are back up. 
</P>
<P>
	Harrington said bar and restaurant owners end up paying the  
price in the battle over smoking rights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
