<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Consumer Confidence Rises in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Consumer confidence, a key indicator of future  
economic activity, rose in May for a record-setting seventh 
consecutive month, the Conference Board reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	``Neither the crisis in Kosovo nor recent price surges at the  
gas pump have cooled consumer optimism,'' said Lynn Franco, 
associate director of the board's Consumer Research Center. ``Low 
inflation and a strong job market are providing a durable 
foundation for historically high levels of consumer confidence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The increase came despite recent reports that the Federal  
Reserve, concerned that rapid economic growth could reignite 
inflation, may consider raising interest rates in the future. 
</P>
<P>
	Also today, the National Association of Realtors reported that  
sales of existing single-family homes fell 3.3 percent in April to 
a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 5.24 million units from 
March's 5.42 million record level. Still, the April figure was 6.3 
percent above the pace of April 1998, the Realtors said. 
</P>
<P>
	The reports helped calm financial markets, providing evidence  
the economy can continue to grow comfortably, analysts said. In 
early afternoon trading, the Dow Jones industrial average was up 
more than 50 points after tumbling 174.61 points on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The consumer confidence index rose to 135.8 in May from a  
revised 135.5 in April, reaching the highest level since July 1998 
when it stood at 137.2, according to the Conference Board. Most 
Wall Street analysts had expected the index to be unchanged in May. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the seventh consecutive month of increase for the index,  
which the business-financed study group said was ``the longest 
uptrend in the 32-year history of the survey.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Consumer sentiment is an important economic indicator because  
consumer spending accounts for about two-thirds of the nation's 
overall economic activity. 
</P>
<P>
	Gary Thayer, chief economist at A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons Inc.  
investment company in St. Louis, said ``consumers are feeling 
good'' and that was showing up in the index. 
</P>
<P>
	``The job situation is the primary factor,'' he said.  
``Unemployment is low, those who want to work can. Wages are rising 
faster than inflation, so consumers are getting ahead.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On housing sales, James F. Smith, chief economist for the  
National Association of Realtors, blamed the April drop to a rise 
in interest rates earlier in the spring. 
</P>
<P>
	``We expect mortgage rates to decline in the near future and  
trend downward during the second half of the year,'' stimulating 
sales, he added. This year's total resales, he said, could be very 
close to last year's record. 
</P>
<P>
	The main consumer index has been strengthening since the rebound  
of the stock market from last fall's downturn and now stands 16.5 
points higher than in October. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest report showed 44 percent of those surveyed in May say  
current business conditions are ``good,'' while only 8.4 percent 
characterized them as ``bad.'' That was slightly more optimistic 
than in April. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 12.8 percent of respondents in May said jobs would be hard  
to get, about the same as the 12.7 percent of the preceding month. 
</P>
<P>
	Expectations for upcoming months continued to rise.  
</P>
<P>
	A separate index designed to measure consumer expectations for  
the next six to nine months increased to 109.3 in May from a 
revised 108.8 in April, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the longer-term outlook, 16.9 percent said in May they  
expected business conditions to improve and 5.5 percent expected 
them to worsen. And 24.7 percent of respondents in May, nearly one 
in four, said they expected incomes to rise, up from 23.5 percent 
in April. 
</P>
<P>
	The consumer confidence index, started in 1967, is compiled from  
responses to questions sent to 5,000 households nationwide. The 
survey polls consumers on matters ranging from job prospects to 
buying plans. 
</P>
<P>
	The index compares results to its base year, 1985, when it stood  
at 100. 
</P>
</TEXT>
