<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Starr Won't Retry McDougal, Steele </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- After fighting legal battles all the way to  
the Supreme Court, Kenneth Starr is invoking pragmatism in 
declining to retry two witnesses he accused of hindering his 
investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr decided Tuesday he won't prosecute anew Whitewater figure  
Susan McDougal and Julie Hiatt Steele, a witness in the Monica 
Lewinsky investigation, after both their trials this spring ended 
with hung juries. 
</P>
<P>
	``Retrials raise important questions of resource allocation....  
The jury's inability to reach a unanimous verdict is a reality that 
we have taken seriously,'' Starr said, signaling that his 
five-year, $40 million investigation may be one step closer to 
wrapping up. 
</P>
<P>
	Three of Starr's key deputies left for the private sector this  
spring. 
</P>
<P>
	The independent counsel's decision came after juries handed him  
consecutive setbacks in his effort to punish witnesses he contended 
were uncooperative or gave false testimony that delayed his 
investigation. Mistrials were declared in both cases. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement was welcomed by some of Starr's harshest  
critics. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't believe he would have gotten a conviction and he would  
only have put my family through the misery of a retrial,'' said 
William Henley, one of Mrs. McDougal's brothers. ``I think he did 
the right thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Starr's decision ends five years of legal warfare with Mrs.  
McDougal, who along with her late ex-husband started the Whitewater 
land venture with President Clinton and his wife, Hillary. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal was sent to prison after being convicted in the  
first Whitewater trial in 1996, was also jailed for refusing a 
judge's order to answer Starr's questions before a grand jury and 
then was tried this year for obstruction. From her jail cell to 
television interviews, she repeatedly attacked Starr's motives and 
tactics. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Steele's lawyer, who also made Starr's tactics an issue in  
her client's trial, said the decision reflected an assessment that 
``this was a case that could not be won.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Whatever his motivation, we are pleased and relieved,'' said  
attorney Nancy Luque. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr still has two more trials involving another witness he has  
accused of being uncooperative, presidential friend and former 
Justice Department official Webster Hubbell. Hubbell, who has 
already served prison time on charges brought by Starr, faces 
separate indictments alleging tax evasion and false testimony. The 
first of those trials is set to begin in August. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr had accused Mrs. McDougal of obstructing his investigation  
and defying a federal judge's order by refusing to testify before 
the grand jury that investigated the Clintons' Arkansas business 
dealings. 
</P>
<P>
	A jury in April acquitted Mrs. McDougal of the obstruction  
charge and deadlocked on the contempt of court charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal testified in her own defense. She said she refused  
to talk to the grand jury because she feared that Starr would 
punish her if she did not give testimony that matched his theory of 
the case. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr's office charged Ms. Steele of Richmond, Va., with lying  
to federal investigators in testimony that undercut the claims of 
presidential accuser Kathleen Willey. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Willey alleged Clinton made an unwanted sexual advance  
toward her inside the White House in 1993 and that she told Ms. 
Steele immediately about the episode. Ms. Steele testified that 
Mrs. Willey had not told her about the alleged incident and later 
asked her to lie about it. 
</P>
<P>
	Though Starr provided testimony from friends that Ms. Steele had  
indeed told them about Mrs. Willey's allegation shortly after the 
alleged incident occurred, a jury in northern Virginia deadlocked 
and a mistrial was declared. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Steele's lawyers surprised many by resting their case  
without calling any witnesses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
