<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Pacers Are Trying To Stay Sharp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- It's rust, not rest, that worries the  
Indiana Pacers, the only team without a loss through the first two 
rounds of the NBA playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	A three-game sweep of Milwaukee in the first round and a  
four-game sweep of Philadelphia in the Eastern Conference 
semifinals took minimal toll on the Pacers physically. But it also 
meant a full week will have passed before they open the conference 
finals against New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if it hurts or helps. All I know is that it is  
for all the marbles to go to the championship, to have the 
opportunity to go to the finals and win this whole thing,'' Mark 
Jackson said after a brief shoot-around Tuesday. ``There's no time 
for any excuses now. We're excited about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Knicks wrapped up a four-game sweep of Atlanta on Monday  
night, so they'll have almost as much time between games as the 
Pacers. 
</P>
<P>
	``You get a little rusty,'' Indiana coach Larry Bird said. ``I  
had that happen to us in Boston before. We had eight or nine days 
and came out a little rusty. But New York's got a lot of time, too, 
so we'll get back to work tomorrow and try to practice as hard as 
we possibly can to prepare these guys and hopefully go into the 
first game on Sunday ready to play. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it will be mental. I think it'll be physical,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pacers' last game was on Sunday, when they finished off the  
76ers in Philadelphia. They'll break up the practice routine this 
week with a scrimmage, open to the public, at Market Square Arena 
on Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Reggie Miller called the week between games ``a double-edged  
sword.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It goes both ways,'' Miller said. ``It's great because we're  
going to be well prepared for New York, and vice versa, but on the 
other hand it's kind of good to be playing basketball games and 
getting banged and moved around. 
</P>
<P>
	``You don't want some of the rust to settle into your game at  
all, but I'm sure both teams will be ready come Sunday,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The first two games in the best-of-7 series will be at Indiana  
Sunday afternoon and Tuesday night. Games 3 and 4 will be in New 
York the following Saturday and Monday. If necessary, the remaining 
games will be in Indianapolis on June 9, in New York June 11 and 
back to Indy on June 13 for a Game 7. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pacers are working on a 12-game playoff winning streak at  
home, but in three previous trips to the conference finals -- 1994, 
1995 and 1998 -- they never had homecourt advantage and lost on the 
road each time in the seventh game. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, Indiana earned the homecourt edge in the East after  
both Miami and Orlando lost in the first round. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't rely on homecourt advantage that much, but we feel  
very fortunate to have it so we want to take advantage of it,'' 
Bird said. ``We played a lot better at home, and we're playing 
awful well on the road. We lucked into homecourt advantage, and 
we're playing against a team that's played a lot better, but we've 
got to worry about ourselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Knicks were seeded eighth in the East but took out Miami in  
five games and Atlanta in four. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're playing much better, with a lot more confidence thanks  
to an Atlanta team that looked like they could care less,'' Jackson 
said. ``But give the Knicks credit. They're playing better 
basketball, and it'll be a war of a series.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indiana won two of three regular-season games against New York  
this year. The two teams have met in four previous playoff series, 
each winning twice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
