<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S.-Canada Reach Magazine Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OTTAWA (AP) -- Canada and the United States have reached a  
tentative agreement to end their eight-month dispute over Canada's 
proposed magazine legislation, sources close to the negotiations 
told Canadian Press on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	A deal would avert the threat of American trade sanctions in  
areas such as lumber, steel and textiles. 
</P>
<P>
	The breakthrough came over the weekend, when negotiators managed  
to get through the impasse on access to Canadian advertising 
dollars, the heart of the dispute. A bill in the Canadian 
Parliament calls for fines on foreign publishers who carried 
Canadian advertising in special Canadian editions of their 
magazines. 
</P>
<P>
	The compromise would allow American publishers who produce  
Canadian magazines -- also known as split-runs -- to print up to 18 
percent of Canadian advertising per issue. The levels would be 
phased in over three years, with 12 percent in the first year and 
15 percent in the second. 
</P>
<P>
	Magazines printing more than that would have to produce a  
majority of Canadian content or face the original system of fines 
proposed in the bill. Split-runs cost little to publish and 
therefore can afford to charge advertisers much less than Canadian 
magazines. 
</P>
<P>
	The Canadian Magazine Publishers Association has said that  
granting anything more than 10 percent would cause serious damage 
to the industry. Meanwhile, their U.S. counterparts steadfastly 
demanded 25 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	A source close to the negotiations, who spoke on condition of  
anonymity, told Canadian Press that some form of federal funding to 
the industry would be made available to ease the pressure that 
American publications would exert on the market. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, conditions would be placed on American publishers  
that run more than the specified amount of Canadian ads to set up 
some sort of presence in Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal comes days after the two countries teetered on the  
brink of a full-scale trade war when negotiators came to an 
impasse. 
</P>
<P>
	A formal announcement of the tenative agreement is expected  
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Trade Minister Sergio Marchi beamed as he addressed a Senate  
committee meeting Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``While you will no doubt appreciate that I cannot go into the  
details ... I will say that we have made substantial progress and I 
expect that we will come to a meeting of the minds very soon,'' 
Marchi said. 
</P>
<P>
	Marchi has tried to take a conciliatory tone to the magazine  
issue, supporting the need for cultural protection on one hand 
while expressing concern for the industries that were likely to be 
affected by a trade war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
