<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> MSN To Post CareerBuilder Listings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Microsoft Corp. is taking a stake in the  
Web-based job listing service CareerBuilder Inc. in a move that 
will put listings from more than 650 companies on Microsoft's MSN 
Network. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft made an initial investment of $17.8 million in the  
Reston, Va.-based company with the right to acquire more shares, 
The Washington Post reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	In exchange, Microsoft can post CareerBuilder's job-search  
database on the Web under its own name. 
</P>
<P>
	``Users are really wanting to find as many of the things they  
are wanting online in one location with the same look and feel,'' 
Michael Goff, director of programming for the Microsoft Network, 
told The Washington Post. 
</P>
<P>
	CareerBuilder already operates its own Web site and offers its  
services through 22 others, including sites owned by USA Today and 
Business Week. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft, based in Redmond, Wash., has made a push in recent  
months to add additional features to its MSN portal, including 
travel, financial and auto information, with content from outside 
companies. Last week, Microsoft announced an alliance with 
Homeseekers.com to boost its real estate listings. 

</P>
</TEXT>
