<DOCNO> APW19990525.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 17:01:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hasek Sidelined for Game 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Buffalo Sabres goaltender Dominik Hasek missed  
his second straight playoff game Tuesday night with a groin injury, 
and Dwayne Roloson started against the Toronto Maple Leafs. 
</P>
<P>
	Roloson made 28 saves in Buffalo's 5-4 win in Sunday's opener in  
the best-of-7 Eastern Conference finals as Hasek was unable to play 
because of the injury that first bothered him back in February. 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek said the injury probably wouldn't keep him out of the  
entire series. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel much better than I did two days ago,'' Hasek said  
before Tuesday's game. ``I feel pretty optimistic. I feel much more 
strength in my leg and that's good. I hope I'll be back in the 
series. It's day-to-day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek has been taking anti-inflammatory drugs to ease the pain.  
Buffalo coach Lindy Ruff said the team was considering using 
cortisone injections. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to try anything,'' Ruff said. ``We'll explore  
every avenue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek first injured the groin in a 3-2 overtime loss to Toronto  
in Buffalo on Feb. 17. The two-time defending league MVP, who led 
the NHL in save percentage (.937) for the sixth straight year, 
missed the next 12 games and did not return until March 19. He flew 
to Germany on March 24 for treatment after twisting his back in a 
game against the New Jersey Devils. 
</P>
<P>
	The groin injury flared in a Game 4 victory over Boston in the  
second round and continued hampering the acrobatic goaltender in a 
5-3 loss to the Bruins in Game 5. Hasek started and won Game 6 
against Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has got to get to a level where he feels comfortable and  
can perform his acrobatics,'' Ruff said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek, whose butterfly style relies on mobility and quickness  
and a capacity to rebound from a prone position, said he didn't 
know when he would return. The teams play Thursday and Saturday in 
Buffalo. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of course I'm thinking about Thursday,'' said Hasek, who added  
he would try to skate Wednesday. ``Who knows? I cannot answer 
because I don't know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek said he would be cheating his teammates if he were to try  
to come back too soon. 
</P>
<P>
	``I cannot go up and down, and if I cannot go up and down I  
cannot do my job,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	An MRI in Buffalo on Monday confirmed that Hasek had a strained  
groin, but a bone scan revealed no other damage, the team said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ruff said the Sabres were still a good team without Hasek.  
</P>
<P>
	``We can beat anybody, and we don't need every star player in  
the lineup,'' said Ruff, also missing leading scorer Miroslav Satan 
since the first round when Satan sustained an ankle bruise. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres have recalled Martin Biron from Rochester, the team's  
AHL affiliate, to back up Roloson. Biron, named the AHL's 
outstanding goaltender this season, made three starts and was 1-2-1 
with the Sabres. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
