<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sales of Existing Homes Off 3.3 Pct </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- After hitting an all-time high in March, sales  
of existing homes slipped back a bit last month, with the setback 
blamed on rising mortgage rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Association of Realtors said that sales of existing  
single-family homes dropped 3.3 percent in April to a seasonally 
adjusted annual rate of 5.24 million units. 
</P>
<P>
	It marked the first decline after five consecutive monthly  
increases as the strong economy pushed sales of new and existing 
homes into record territory. 
</P>
<P>
	James Smith, chief economist for the Realtors, predicted that  
1999 still would be a good year for home sales, given the strong 
economy, high consumer confidence levels and unemployment rates 
that have dropped to the lowest levels in three decades. 
</P>
<P>
	``The rise in interest rates earlier this spring caused a  
temporary postponement of purchase decisions. We expect mortgage 
rates to decline in the near future and trend downward during the 
second half of the year,'' Smith said. ``Existing home sales in 
1999 should be very close to last year's record.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A weekly national survey of rates by Freddie Mac, the mortgage  
company, showed that 30-year rates climbed last week to 7.10 
percent, the highest level in 18 months. 
</P>
<P>
	The strength in the housing sector has been a key factor  
supporting U.S. economic growth in the midst of severe recessions 
in many parts of the world stemming from the Asian currency crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan, speaking Monday night  
to the National Retail Federation, said the strength in consumer 
spending, which accounts for two-thirds of economic activity, 
depends not just on the wealth effect generated by rising stock 
prices but from strong home sales. 
</P>
<P>
	``On the sale of a home, you tend to realize very large capital  
gains -- on average, that has been something in excess of $35,000,'' 
Greenspan said. ``When you are talking about 4 million (home) 
sales, that's a very large number.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many economists attribute the strong consumer spending to the  
wealth effect that occurs when people start spending more of their 
disposable income because their investment portfolios are rising. 
But Greenspan said ``by far the largest portion of the extent to 
which capital gains are being translated into purchases occurs in 
the process'' of selling a home. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumer confidence has also helped to bolster strong spending,  
reflecting the fact that unemployment rates have fallen to the 
lowest level in three decades. The Conference Board reported today 
that consumer confidence rose for a record-setting seventh straight 
month, climbing in May to 135.8, compared to April's index number 
of 135.5. 
</P>
<P>
	The Realtors report on sales of existing homes showed the  
biggest drop in April occurred in the Northeast, where sales fell 
by 8.3 percent to an annual rate of 660,000 units. Sales were down 
4.2 percent in the Midwest and 3.8 percent in the South. The only 
region of the country that saw an increase last month was the West, 
where sales rose 1.4 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The median price of an existing home sold last month rose by 1.4  
percent to $131,400. The median price is the point where half the 
homes sold for more and half for less. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
