<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Staffer Accused in Prison Escape </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JESSUP, Md. (AP) -- A former prison psychologist was arrested  
Tuesday on charges she helped two inmates in their prison getaway 
by driving them to a hotel and paying for their room. 
</P>
<P>
	Elizabeth L. Feil, 43, was held on charges of being an accessory  
after the fact, harboring a prison escapee and obstructing and 
hindering. She posted a $5,225 bond and left without commenting to 
reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	She allegedly helped convicted murderer Gregory Lawrence and  
armed robber Byron Smoot, with whom her husband said she had an 
affair, escape from the Maryland Correctional Institute on May 18. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Feil denied the charges.  
</P>
<P>
	``We feel that they're false and we plan on mounting a vigorous  
defense,'' her lawyer, Isaiah Dixon III, said. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators said Ms. Feil and Smoot planned the escape  
together. 
</P>
<P>
	Prison logs showed she had made numerous visits to see Smoot,  
and Ms. Feil's husband released letters that Smoot wrote to Ms. 
Feil in February, which alluded to escape plans. 
</P>
<P>
	``It won't be until spring, this is the real thing honey, there  
won't be any more delays,'' Smoot allegedly wrote. ``All I know is 
that if the nest is ready by then, the eagle will land.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After the escape, police said the two men dialed Ms. Feil's  
pager. She picked them up in her car, drove them to a hotel and 
paid for the room, then tried to bandage the cuts the men had 
suffered scaling a razor-wire fence. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the escape, they were recaptured two days later in  
Baltimore. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawrence, 39, was serving a life sentence for murder after  
shooting a man and stealing his shoes in 1978. Smoot, 38, was 
imprisoned for a rash of armed robberies and was sentenced to 29 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	State police also said that Ms. Feil was under investigation for  
allegedly cooking up mail-order schemes with Smoot. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Feil was fired from the Patuxent Institution, a  
maximum-security prison, for setting up a post office box in May 
1998 to exchange intimate correspondence with prisoners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
