<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Truck Safety Measures Unveiled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration said Tuesday it  
would aim to cut truck-related deaths in half, but critics said the 
proposals were unlikely to produce quick results. 
</P>
<P>
	Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater said his department would  
ask for $56 million more from Congress this year to increase the 
number of inspectors for commercial vehicles -- which includes 
trucks and motorcoaches -- and to boost state and federal safety 
programs. 
</P>
<P>
	He also said the federal Office of Motor Carriers, which  
regulates commercial vehicles, would increase the fines for 
violations, move more swiftly to shut down unfit motor carriers, 
limit negotiated settlements in enforcement cases and aggressively 
pursue criminal or civil penalties when someone is killed in a 
commercial vehicle crash. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the secretary said he would push to reduce driving  
time for operators and seek to monitor compliance with rules 
through the expanded use of technology similar to airline 
flight-data recorders. 
</P>
<P>
	All told, Slater said he hoped to reduce the number of  
truck-related deaths from about 5,000 annually to about 2,500 
annually. In 1997, 5,355 people were killed; preliminary figures 
show the number fell to about 5,200 last year. 
</P>
<P>
	On average, six people are killed each year in bus accidents,  
although the figure has spiked in the past six months after a 
Christmas Eve crash that killed eight in New Jersey and a charter 
bus accident earlier this month in New Orleans that killed 22. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today we face up to a time for action, and the plan that I  
have outlined deals with action,'' Slater declared at a news 
conference. He was flanked by Federal Highway Administrator Kenneth 
Wykle, who oversees the Office of Motor Carriers. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposals triggered swift and critical reaction from safety  
advocates and truckers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most of the things the secretary talked about are longterm.  
Most are proposals and actions they should have been taking,'' said 
Jacqueline Gillan, vice president of Advocates for Highway and Auto 
Safety, a group with insurance industry support. ``The safety 
community wants action.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Joan Claybrook, president of the advocacy group Public Citizen,  
said: ``While we welcome DOT's statement on improved enforcement, 
they're still talking about useless safety education programs and 
`collaborative' government-industry research, for which they have 
been harshly criticized by the inspector general of the DOT.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, truckers said they wished Slater had already reformed  
hour-of-service rules which regulate the amount of time truckers 
are on the road and created a separate agency to oversee motor 
carrier safety, much like the Federal Aviation Administration does 
with airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	``Only in this format, with a Senate-confirmed presidential  
appointee reporting to the secretary of transportation, will truck 
safety get its proper respect,'' said Walter McCormick Jr., 
president of the American Trucking Associations. 
</P>
<P>
	In his announcement, Slater ducked one demand of safety  
advocates: moving the Office of Motor Carriers out of the Federal 
Highway Administration and into the National Highway Traffic Safety 
Administration. 
</P>
<P>
	Both are under the Transportation Department, but the highway  
administration largely oversees the interstate system, while the 
safety administration deals with issues such as drunken driving, 
air bags and seat belt use. 
</P>
<P>
	Slater didn't rule out the change, but he said he would prefer  
to be accountable for results and ``not just rearranging boxes on 
an organizational chart.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gillan, of Advocates for Highway and Auto Safety, said there was  
merit to such a move. 
</P>
<P>
	``NHTSA is a regulatory agency with a safety culture,'' she  
said. ``OMC is like a really sick patient that is on life support. 
This proposal was the equivalent of `Take two aspirin and call me 
in the morning.' The real solution is to treat the problem.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
