<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Whitbread Buys Allied Domecq Pubs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Whitbread PLC has agreed to buy the British pub  
operations of Allied Domecq PLC for about $3.7 billion in stock and 
will shed its own brewing operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the deal announced Tuesday, Whitbread will acquire 3,500  
pubs and restaurants, Allied's 50 percent stake in the First Quench 
retail shops, in which Whitbread already had a 50 percent share, 
and Allied's 25 percent stake in Britannia soft drinks. 
</P>
<P>
	Allied will receive 230 million new shares in Whitbread.  
</P>
<P>
	To comply with British competition law, Whitbread will dispose  
of its brewing operations, which command 15.7 percent of the 
British market. Whitbread said it had not decided how it will 
divest those operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Whitbread said it expects the acquisition to lead to annual cost  
savings of around $160 million by the third year after the deal is 
complete. 
</P>
<P>
	Whitbread, founded as a brewery in 1742, has expanded  
aggressively in the retail field, owning 3,400 pubs, the Cafe Rouge 
restaurant chain and Marriott hotels and Travel Inns in Britain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
