Gold(final) -    $270.70    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Tue.
Silver(final) -   UNCH    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Mon.

</P>
<P>
	Consumer Confidence Up for 7th Month  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Consumer confidence rose in May for a  
record-setting seventh consecutive month, suggesting that the 
economy will remain robust, the Conference Board said today. Low 
inflation and a strong job market are being given much of the 
credit. In a separate report released today, the National 
Association of Purchasing Management said 55 percent of the members 
polled in its semiannual survey predicted the manufacturing economy 
will be even better in the second half of this year than it was in 
the first half. 

</P>
<P>
	Barnesandnoble.com IPO Lags Others  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Barnesandnoble.com's much-anticipated initial  
public offering of stock received a subdued welcome on Wall Street 
today, the latest sign that the dot.com craze in the stock market 
may be waning. Although shares of the online bookseller rose 27 
percent above their offering price, they failed to triple or 
quadruple in value as many Internet peers have done in their first 
days of trading. Barnesandnoble.com shares went public at $18 per 
share and were at $22.93 3/4 in late trading on the Nasdaq Stock 
Market. 

</P>
<P>
	Judge Rules for Sun Over Microsoft  
</P>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Several Microsoft Corp. products,  
including Windows 98, infringed Sun Microsystems Inc.' copyrights, 
a federal judge said in a nonbinding, tentative ruling today. 
However, the ruling -- issued by U.S. District Court in San Jose -- 
said that Microsoft can develop and distribute ``independently 
developed'' tools that do not comply with a contract with Sun, so 
long as such products do not infringe any Sun copyright, patent or 
other intellectual property right. The three-part ruling will be 
finalized -- and possibly changed -- after oral arguments scheduled 
in June. Sun stock was down 3 7/8 at 35 1/16 today; Microsoft was down 
1 at 76 1/4. 

</P>
<P>
	Impact of 'Digital Divide' Debated  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- At this embryonic stage of the Internet's  
development, no one disputes figures showing minorities trailing 
whites in computer ownership, cyberaccess and Internet know-how. 
But the impact of ``the digital divide'' is a matter of dispute 
between some Internet experts and civil rights advocates. Keith 
Fulton of the National Urban League sees the gap as a sign that 
minorities might find themselves relegated to second-class 
citizenship in cyberspace due to a lack of computer aptitude. But 
E. David Ellington, a founder and president of one of the 
Internet's most popular black-directed sites, believes it's too 
early to fret over the paucity of blacks and Hispanics on the 
Internet. 

</P>
<P>
	IBM Program To Be Sold With Linux  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A popular IBM program for network databases will  
be sold with a Linux operating system in a deal giving the upstart 
software added legitimacy in a market dominated by Microsoft's 
Windows NT. The agreement to bundle TurboLinux and IBM's 
best-selling DB2 Universal Database program was announced today by 
Pacific HiTech, one of many small companies selling a version of 
Linux. The companies also agreed to collaborate on making future 
editions of IBM server software, often referred to as 
``middleware,'' and TurboLinux work together more smoothly. 

</P>
<P>
	Allen, Arnault Invest in Datek  
</P>
<P>
	BELLEVUE, Wash. (AP) -- Microsoft co-founder Paul Allen and  
French businessman Bernard Arnault are investing $300 million in 
the privately held Internet brokerage firm Datek Online Holdings 
Corp. Datek Online said today that Allen's Bellevue-based Vulcan 
Ventures will lead the cash investment, with participation by 
Arnault's private holding company, Group Arnault, and TA 
Associates, a Boston-based venture capital company. Edward Nicoll, 
president of Datek Online. said Vulcan, Group Arnault and TA 
Associates would together hold a minority stake in his company, but 
other terms of the investment were not disclosed. 

</P>
<P>
	Toys R Us Settles Antitrust Suit  
</P>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- Toys R Us Inc. and two toy manufacturers  
will pay $50 million in toys and cash to settle state claims that 
the nation's No. 2 toy retailer kept toy makers from selling Barbie 
dolls, Mr. Potato Head and other popular toys to discount stores. 
Toys R Us will pay $40.5 million, while Mattel Inc. and Little 
Tikes Co. -- who were accused of acceding to the demands of the 
Paramus, N.J.-based retailer -- will pay $9.5 million to settle a 
lawsuit joined by attorneys general in 44 states, the District of 
Columbia and Puerto Rico. All 50 states will share in the 
settlement. Toys R Us shares were down 3/16 at 23 9/16. 

</P>
<P>
	McKesson To Restate Earnings Again  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Medical supplies distributor McKesson HBOC  
Inc. says it will revise downward its fiscal 1999 earnings for a 
second time in two months after finding more accounting problems in 
its recently acquired health information company HBO. The news sent 
its stock sharply lower. The restatement may also include previous 
years' earnings reports, McKesson disclosed today. The company 
blamed ``improper revenue recognition matters'' involving software 
sales at HBO, which provides computer solutions to help health care 
providers manage their businesses. McKesson shares were at 33 1/2, 
down 4 11/16 

</P>
<P>
	First Union Profit Outlook Dims  
</P>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE (AP) -- First Union Corp. has warned that its  
second-quarter and annual profits will be below expectations, 
largely because of merger-related costs. For the second quarter, 
the Charlotte-based bank said it expects to post earnings in the 
range of $770 million to $800 million, or 80 cents to 83 cents a 
share. The results exclude a non-recurring 8-cent gain. Analysts 
polled by the research firm First Call Corp. had expected the bank 
to earn 97 cents per share in the second quarter. 

</P>
<P>
	Americans Give $175B to Charity  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Americans opened their pocketbooks wider in  
1998, donating nearly $17 billion more to charities than the 
previous year, according to a new report on charitable giving. The 
strong economy, low inflation, a growth in personal wealth and more 
sophisticated fund raising helped fuel the 10.7 percent increase 
and raise overall charitable giving to $174.52 billion, said Ann E. 
Kaplan, research director for the American Association of 
Fund-Raising Counsel's Trust for Philanthropy. When adjusted for 
inflation, the increase was 9 percent, she said today. 

</P>
<P>
	Federated-WeddingChannel.Com Plan  
</P>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Federated Department Stores Inc. is linking  
its bridal registries with online wedding planner 
WeddingChannel.com. In the deal announced today, Federated also 
will buy a 20 percent stake in WeddingChannel.com, a Los 
Angeles-based company. Terms were not announced. The arrangement 
will link bridal registries from Federated's 403 department stores 
and online sites with WeddingChannel.com's offerings, which include 
personalized Web pages, travel planning, local business directories 
and a database of bridal fashions. 

</P>
