<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NH House Votes To Add King Holiday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- The New Hampshire House voted Tuesday to  
create a permanent Martin Luther King Jr. holiday, all but ensuring 
the state will finally join the rest of the nation in honoring the 
slain civil rights leader. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the past 20 years, repeated attempts to create such a  
holiday have failed. 
</P>
<P>
	The House voted 212-148 to add King's name to the state's Civil  
Rights Day holiday, held the day every other state honors King. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill now goes to the Senate, where passage is all but  
assured. The Senate passed an identical bill earlier this month. 
</P>
<P>
	The House also was expected to vote Tuesday on the Senate bill,  
which would go directly to Gov. Jeanne Shaheen if passed. 
</P>
<P>
	Shaheen, who like her predecessor added King's name to the  
holiday by proclamation each year, said she will sign either bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Democratic Rep. Jane Kelley urged lawmakers to support the bill  
so ``the ugly stain of racism and bigotry can be cleansed from the 
beautiful face of our state.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents argued that singling out King would detract from other  
American heroes such as George Washington and Abraham Lincoln. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican Rep. Donald White said he opposed the bill ``for the  
simple reason that the history of this great nation reflects the 
pride and energy of all our people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers created Civil Rights Day as a compromise in 1991 to  
honor ``the many people from a variety of cultural backgrounds who 
fought and died in the struggle to gain freedom and equality for 
all individuals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A King holiday bill first came before the Legislature in 1979  
and has been introduced nearly every two-year session since. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990525.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 15:02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wrestler's Costume Blamed for Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Professional wrestler Owen Hart's fatal  
fall while being lowered into the ring may have been caused by his 
elaborate, feathered costume catching on his release cord, 
authorities said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is believed at this point in time that the quick release  
was activated. Either it was snagged on his clothes or he pulled it 
too soon,'' police spokesman Floyd Mitchell said. 
</P>
<P>
	The 34-year-old wrestling bad boy known as the Blue Blazer fell  
70 feet to his death Sunday night while making his entrance for a 
match at Kemper Arena. 
</P>
<P>
	Hart planned to descend 90 feet into the ring from the rafters  
in a stunt he had done before and had practiced at the arena hours 
earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Strapped into a harness, Hart was suspended from a rope as three  
rigging handlers above him waited for the cue to begin lowering 
him. 
</P>
<P>
	His harness was attached to the rope with a metal ring. He had a  
release mechanism similar to a parachute release. Hart was supposed 
to pull on it when he was just above the mat and drop into the 
ring. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities said the feathers of his costume may have become  
caught in the pull-string, or he may have yanked the string 
accidentally. 
</P>
<P>
	Somehow, that quick-release was activated early, and Hart fell,  
hitting his head on the turnbuckle, the padded metal coupling that 
holds the ring's ropes together. 
</P>
<P>
	Hart had done the stunt before, and his widow, Martha Hart, told  
NBC's ``Today'' show on Tuesday that she was never comfortable with 
it. 
</P>
<P>
	``This particular one we did discuss,'' Mrs. Hart said. ``I had  
told him that I didn't think he should do it.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
