<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Up on Heat Worry / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures moved higher Tuesday on  
the Chicago Board of Trade as investors eyed the potential for heat 
damage to newly planted crops. 
</P>
<P>
	Forecasters were calling for a high-pressure ridge to begin  
forming in Midwest growing regions next week, which could choke off 
rainfall and provide heat stress to young crops. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans also found support on ideas farmers in western growing  
regions remain far behind the normal planting pace and may not be 
able to catch up. That could reduce what is expected to be record 
acreage. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat's gains were limited as farmers found above-average yields  
in early harvesting of winter wheat crops. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery rose 1 1/2 cents to $2.48 3/4 a bushel; July  
corn rose 3 cents to $2.14 3/4 a bushel; July oats rose 1 3/4 cents to 
$1.19 1/2 a bushel; July soybeans rose 4 3/4 cents to $4.59 3/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Lean hogs futures fell sharply a second day on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange amid expectations meatpacker supplies will be 
ample going into the busy summer period, reducing the need to 
slaughter fresh supplies. Pork bellies were mostly higher, while 
beef futures retreated. 
</P>
<P>
	June live cattle fell .65 cent to 62.70 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle fell .75 cent to 74.57 cents a pound; June lean hogs 
fell 1.30 cents to 53.60 cents a pound; July pork bellies rose 1.17 
cents to 53.37 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
