<DOCNO> APW19990525.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 05:42:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hastert Is Assertive but Softspoken </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Unhappy with the votes that three Republicans  
cast in midnight negotiations with the Senate, House Speaker Dennis 
Hastert invited the lawmakers to his office to discuss the 
legislation financing the air campaign in Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't yell and scream. It's not my style,'' Hastert, a  
former wrestling coach, said afterward. Even so, two of the three 
swiftly agreed to reverse course, and a provision that the speaker 
feared would derail the entire measure was sidetracked. 
</P>
<P>
	It was one of several instances recently in which the  
57-year-old Illinois Republican has asserted himself -- more quietly 
than his predecessor Newt Gingrich might have. And it came as he 
struggled to hold his narrow majority together as well as overcome 
the Democratic-fed perception that GOP Whip Tom DeLay is the real 
power in the House. 
</P>
<P>
	``My job is the speaker. I do what I have to do as speaker. He  
is the whip,'' Hastert said of DeLay in an interview in his office, 
with its broad sweeping view down Washington's Mall. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, that perception was enhanced late last month when Hastert  
cast a vote on the floor in support of the ongoing bombing 
campaign. He had told fellow Republicans he viewed the issue as a 
``vote of conscience.'' But DeLay opposed it, visibly lobbied some 
lawmakers to do likewise, and the provision failed on a tie vote. 
</P>
<P>
	``I like Dennis Hastert,'' Democratic Leader Dick Gephardt said  
the following day. ``He is a nice man and he's a good man and I 
like talking to him and working with him. But unfortunately ... the 
reality, I'm afraid (is) that the extreme right wing of the 
Republican Party remains in control.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the days since, Hastert has become noticeably more assertive.  
For example: 
</P>
<P>
	-- He intervened to increase the amount of money for the Pentagon  
well beyond what the administration asked for. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Even before he called Reps. Ralph Regula, Joe Skeen and Sonny  
Callahan, into his office, his frustration with add-ons to the 
spending bill led him to talk about quitting the post he's held for 
less than six months. Several GOP sources, who spoke on condition 
of anonymity, said Hastert said in private meetings it wasn't worth 
holding the job if he had to watch while Democratic-crafted 
amendments that were extraneous to the war effort were attached to 
the measure. 
</P>
<P>
	-- He also caused a stir last week when he signaled support for  
gun control legislation after the high school shootings in 
Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	-- And he angered some GOP moderates when he told them he didn't  
intend to bow to their demand to bring campaign finance legislation 
to a vote before September. 
</P>
<P>
	``If that's not soon enough for them they have a right to do  
something else,'' he said. Some moderates later said they took that 
as a virtual dare to join Democrats in trying to force the measure 
to the floor in July. 
</P>
<P>
	In another part of the job, Hastert has raised roughly $5  
million for candidates and GOP causes since becoming speaker, aides 
say. With the House campaign committee facing a substantial debt, 
he asked GOP chairman Jim Nicholson for help. Nicholson agreed to 
swap $800,000 in ``hard money'' to help the House committee pay off 
the debt, for a larger amount of soft money. 
</P>
<P>
	The job, Hastert points out, is not something he sought.  
</P>
<P>
	But Gingrich abdicated after Republicans lost seats in last  
fall's elections. Rep. Bob Livingston, in line to replace him, quit 
after admitting to marital infidelities. 
</P>
<P>
	At that point, Gingrich, DeLay and others turned to Hastert, the  
genial deputy whip. But it was his wife who cast the deciding vote. 
</P>
<P>
	He called her in Illinois, where she has taught elementary  
school for 33 years. ``And I thought she'd say no. She didn't. She 
undercut me,'' Hastert said with a smile. 
</P>
<P>
	Hastert found himself at the helm of a slender majority in a  
House where Republicans had just impeached a Democratic president 
in an atmosphere of distrust and partisanship. 
</P>
<P>
	He set a quieter tone. ``One of the things you try to do is keep  
the trains running on time and not have any train wrecks,'' he 
says. 
</P>
<P>
	He brought Republicans together around a budget plan, and it  
passed on time. He also helped position Republicans as the party 
committed to setting aside the entire Social Security surplus until 
a plan can be passed to overhaul the system. 
</P>
<P>
	He's pledged that the House will pass a tax cut before lawmakers  
go home for August. 
</P>
<P>
	And he's moved to defuse a census dispute that once, under  
Gingrich, delayed disaster aid to Midwestern farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	``His not being fancy plays to what we need now, which is  
solid,'' says Don Fierce, a former top Republican National 
Committee official, now a lobbyist loyal to the GOP cause. 
</P>
<P>
	With Republicans eager to achieve legislative accomplishments,  
the challenges are coming faster. 
</P>
<P>
	Given the limits contained in the 1997 balanced budget deal,  
passage of some annual spending measures seems impossible. Among 
the options, according to several Republicans, is to seek a 
negotiation with the White House to overhaul Medicare, cut taxes, 
and provide more money for domestic spending. 
</P>
<P>
	A more immediate challenge is gun control. Hastert and Gephardt  
met last week and discussed bringing the issue to the floor in 
mid-June. A few hours later, after meeting with fellow Democrats, 
Gephardt rejected the offer as too late. 
</P>
<P>
	And even the issues that ultimately come off smoothly in public  
are filled with difficulties. 
</P>
<P>
	At one point last winter, according to some Republicans,  
hard-liners were tugging one way on the budget and members of the 
Appropriations Committee tugging in another. 
</P>
<P>
	Hastert summed up his own predicament.  
</P>
<P>
	``Now I know why Newt left,'' he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
