<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> WWII Survivors Sue German Drug Cos. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- A half-century later, twin sisters who  
survived the Auschwitz concentration camp say they clearly remember 
Dr. Joseph Mengele scrutinizing their naked bodies that he had 
subjected to gruesome and unscientific medical ``experiments.'' 
</P>
<P>
	They have only recently learned, however, that German  
pharmaceutical companies participated in the tests with the 
notorious ``Angel of Death'' and profited from their pain, 
according to two class-action lawsuits they and others filed this 
month. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuits filed May 13 against Bayer AG, Hoechst AG and  
Schering AG are among the first in the nation linking German 
companies to Nazi medical experiments. The Associated Press learned 
of the lawsuits Tuesday. A similar class-action lawsuit against 
Bayer was filed in Indiana in February. 
</P>
<P>
	The three lawsuits are the latest filings in a recent wave of  
litigation by survivors of Nazi death camps or slave labor 
factories aimed at European banks, insurance companies and 
industrial firms. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the Newark suits, one is filed on behalf of U.S. citizens,  
the other for citizens of other nations. Each seeks unspecified 
damages for survivors it estimates number in the hundreds. 
</P>
<P>
	They accuse the companies of providing toxic chemicals to the  
Nazis for the ``experiments.'' Company personnel supervised the 
work and used information from those experiments to market products 
sold during and after the war, the lawsuits said. 
</P>
<P>
	Schering also participated in these experiments, but also  
supported experimental sterilization procedures on camp inmates, 
the lawsuit said. 
</P>
<P>
	The allegations stem from ``various documents that have become  
available for researching that were not available before,'' said 
Joseph D. Ament, a Chicago lawyer representing plaintiffs in the 
Newark cases. 
</P>
<P>
	All of the survivor lawsuits, many filed in U.S. District Court  
here, have been made possible by a 1991 international agreement 
settling German reparations to other nations, and thus allowing 
individuals to sue, said Burt Neuborne, a professor at New York 
University Law School who is among the lawyers pressing the Newark 
lawsuits. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoechst issued a statement that did not address the medical  
experimentation claims, but cited the company's support of 
``various organizations and projects dedicated to preserving the 
memory of the atrocities of the Nazi regime.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bayer spokesman Thomas Reinert in Leverkusen, Germany, said the  
company would not comment on the lawsuits at this time. 
</P>
<P>
	Schering spokesman Gert Wlasich said the company would examine  
the claims before commenting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990525.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 14:12:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> First Union Again Warns on Profits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- For the second time in five months, First  
Union Corp. on Tuesday was forced to scale back sharply its 
projected earnings for the quarter and year. Its stock fell nearly 
9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	First Union chairman Ed Crutchfield remained cool to speculation  
about a merger with a comparable-size bank. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been here 34 years, and we've missed this (earnings  
forecast) only once,'' he said during a 90-minute conference call 
with analysts who cover First Union's stock. ``Maybe it will happen 
again in another 34 years. We'll tighten up what we need to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Analyst David Berry of Keefe Bruyette &AMP; Woods was sharply  
critical of the bank's actions, however. ``This is a bank that 
seems to have trouble budgeting,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not the result of some external event beyond their  
control. It's not like they made some loans to Russia and they 
defaulted,'' Berry said. ``The pattern of events shows they don't 
have a grip on the finances of this company.'' 
</P>
<P>
	First Union shares fell $4.25 to $45.68 3/4 on the New York Stock  
Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	The Charlotte-based bank said its second-quarter earnings would  
be in the range of $770 million to $800 million, or 80 cents to 83 
cents a share. The results exclude a non-recurring 8-cent gain. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts polled by the research firm First Call Corp. had  
expected the bank to earn about 97 cents per share in the second 
quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's sixth-largest bank also said Tuesday it expects its  
1999 operating earnings to be between $3.3 billion and $3.4 
billion, or $3.40 to $3.50 a share, excluding a 20-cent 
non-recurring gain. 
</P>
<P>
	That's far short of the company's earnings goal of around $4 a  
share. In January, it had been revised downward to that figure from 
$4.29. First Call's estimate was $3.98 a share. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1998, the bank earned $3.7 billion, or $3.77 per share, which  
did not include merger-related and restructuring charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Crutchfield said one reason for the company's struggles has been  
its growth over the past few years. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have had a lot of acquisitions, as you know, over the last  
two or three years,'' he said. ``The company has roughly tripled in 
size.'' 
</P>
<P>
	First Union's largest acquisition, Philadelphia's CoreStates  
Financial Corp., turned out to be its most problematic, Crutchfield 
said. The 1998 merger partner has not produced the revenues that 
First Union had anticipated. 
</P>
<P>
	``CoreStates has not lived up to our expectations,'' he said,  
adding that neither has another acquisition, The Money Store. ``I'd 
still do it over again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In February, First Union unveiled plans to trim its work force 7  
percent to cut annual costs by $400 million. The moves were 
prompted by forecasts that bank profits would be slowing after 
several years of strong growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990525.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 17:11:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Petrie Named NBA Exec of the Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Geoff Petrie, Sacramento's vice  
president of basketball operations, was selected NBA Executive of 
the Year on Tuesday, capping a spectacular comeback year for him 
and the Kings. 
</P>
<P>
	The award, announced in New York by The Sporting News,  
recognized Petrie's key role in rebuilding a team which had not had 
a winning season since moving from Kansas City to Sacramento in 
1985. 
</P>
<P>
	Starting his fifth year with the Kings, Petrie made a series of  
trades and signings, some of them controversial, that resulted in 
four new starters playing for a new coach, Rick Adelman. 
</P>
<P>
	The NBA lockout meant an abbreviated training camp and season  
for the young team, and the start was rocky. The Kings' 
inconsistency and lapses often made them look like the 27-55 team 
of the previous season. 
</P>
<P>
	But Sacramento closed the regular season with 10 wins in their  
final 11 games for a 27-23 record. Then they came within one missed 
shot on the final buzzer of upsetting the Utah Jazz, the defending 
two-time Western Conference champion, in the fifth and final game 
of the opening round of the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Petrie received eight of a possible 33 votes from his fellow NBA  
executives and league representatives. Orlando's John Gabriel 
received seven votes, followed by Toronto's Glen Grunwald with five 
and Portland's Bob Whitsitt with four. 
</P>
<P>
	Petrie said the award was especially gratifying ``coming with  
the type of year we had ... the way it came together under such 
great uncertainty and much doubt. I'm really proud of everybody 
associated with the team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A lot of that doubt and uncertainty involved Petrie's own job.  
Earlier this year, as Petrie faced a scheduled mid-year change in 
team ownership and the expiration of his contract. At one point he 
reportedly was just hours away from resigning. 
</P>
<P>
	But Petrie signed a multiyear contract extension in January, and  
his team of strangers -- nine new players on the 12-man roster -- won 
national attention with a sometimes erratic but always exciting 
style. 
</P>
<P>
	Petrie's major accomplishments were trading for power forward  
Chris Webber, signing free agent center Vlade Divac and drafting 
point guard Jason Williams. 
</P>
<P>
	Almost as important were the free agent signings of guards  
Vernon Maxwell and Jon Barry and forward Scot Pollard and the 
recruitment and signing of guard Peja Stojakovic, a 1996 
first-round draft choice from Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	Only forwards Corliss Williamson and Lawrence Funderburke and  
guard Tariq Abdul-Wahad -- all draft choices during Petrie's 
five-year tenure -- returned from the 1997-98 squad. 
</P>
<P>
	``Geoff has done a terrific job in rebuilding the Sacramento  
Kings. A lot of hard work has started to pay off for the 
organization,'' said Kings chief executive officer Jim Thomas, who 
hired Petrie in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Gavin Maloof, whose family will assume control of the franchise  
from Thomas on July 1, said the honor was well deserved. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't say I was surprised,'' Maloof said from Las Vegas. ``I  
do know it's an honor for him individually and for the Kings 
organization to have a person of his quality. It's certainly a very 
prestigious award, and I'm happy for him because he works very hard 
and deserves it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Petrie, 51, shared the NBA Rookie of the Year award in 1971,  
when he played for the Portland Trail Blazers. His latest award 
makes him the first person to win both the NBA's rookie and 
executive honors. 
</P>
<P>
	Petrie played six years for the Trail Blazers. After his playing  
career was curtailed by injuries, he spent five years as a members 
of the Trail Blazers broadcast team and another four years in the 
team's front office before joining the Kings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990525.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 17:11:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
