<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  NATO Bombings Enter Third Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO's bombing campaign entered its  
third month today with missiles striking the abandoned Serb police 
headquarters in Belgrade and a villa said to be one of the 
residences of President Slobodan Milosevic. A new wave of refugees 
were bound for Macedonia. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO approved an updated operations plan with higher numbers for  
its Kosovo ground force today, a peacekeeping unit about 
50,000-strong that would be sent into the province from Macedonia 
as soon Serb troops depart. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States would probably furnish 7,000-8,000 troops as  
part of the plan, which now goes back to NATO generals to decide 
this month exactly how many troops with what specialties will be 
needed. 
</P>
<P>
	The operations plan was drawn up last year, creating a NATO-led  
international force of about 28,000 to implement an eventual peace 
agreement between the Yugoslav government and the ethnic Albanians, 
but that accord never materialized as the Kosovo conflict broke 
out. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of today's airstrikes focused on command and control  
facilities, including Milosevic's villa at Dobanovci, 12 miles west 
of Belgrade, NATO said. It was the third time the villa that NATO 
says also houses a major command center had been struck. 
</P>
<P>
	Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital, was down to its last 8 percent  
of water reserves because of damaged pumping stations and a power 
outage, Serb media reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The English-language V.I.P. newsletter reported fighting in much  
of Kosovo and said the most intense clashes were in the west, where 
Serbian forces were trying to regain positions lost to the rebel 
Kosovo Liberation Army in the past few weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	The allied campaign aims to force Milosevic to accept a peace  
deal for the southern Serb province that would include withdrawing 
Yugoslav forces from Kosovo, allowing NATO-led peacekeepers to 
police the accord and all refugees to return. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past three days, 22,000 ethnic Albanian refugees have  
poured out of Kosovo and into Macedonia, the most U.N. workers had 
seen since the first week of May. 
</P>
<P>
	Sources inside Yugoslavia have alerted Macedonia that 150,000  
more refugees are on the way, a Macedonian Foreign Ministry 
official said, speaking on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Since March, more than 830,000 ethnic Albanians have fled  
Kosovo, which had a prewar population of 2.1 million. A 13-month 
crackdown by Yugoslav forces that killed at least 2,000 people 
preceded the NATO air campaign that started March 24. 
</P>
<P>
	Ron Redmond, a spokesman for the U.N. High Commissioner for  
Refugees, speculated that Milosevic's forces had begun a final push 
to oust ethnic Albanians from Pristina and Urosevac -- deportation 
hubs where refugees from all over Kosovo gather to board buses and 
trains for the border. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the new arrivals Monday were from Pristina, Kosovo's  
capital. They described a broken city, where paramilitary police 
wearing black masks ruled streets emptied of the ethnic Albanian 
residents. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yugoslav army, meanwhile, banned anti-war demonstrations in  
a central Serbian town during air raid alerts and warned deserters 
to return to their units or face courts-martial, the daily Vijesti 
reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	For days, citizens of Krusevac and several central Serbian towns  
have been demonstrating against the war and protesting service of 
their male relatives in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	In Krusevac, several hundred reservists who deserted and  
returned home joined the protests. A local official who asked for 
anonymity said about 2,000 people demonstrated Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The army was previously conciliatory, urging deserters to return  
and even offering to treat their unauthorized leave of absence as 
formal leave. But the comments reported from Krusevac by Vijesti 
were harsher, saying those failing to return would be 
court-martialed by a ``war court.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The statement, issued by the local army command, also warned  
against illegal public gatherings during air raid alerts, saying 
reaction will be ``robust and the violators will be punished.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Poor weather hampered NATO's military operation today, but jets  
still struck several artillery emplacements, military vehicles and 
a logistics support base. 
</P>
<P>
	Jets also fired at Mount Cer, 60 miles west of Belgrade, site of  
a key communication transmitter; at the Batajnica military airport 
northwest of Belgrade; and in the suburb of Rakovica, the site of a 
large underground military complex, state media reported. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO troops also began relocating 30,000 Kosovo refugees today  
from Albania's northern border to safer camps deeper inside the 
country, fearing attacks from nearby Serb forces. Most of the 
refugees are in Albania and, increasingly, Macedonia. 
</P>
<P>
	In one of several recent incidents, U.N. spokesman Rupert  
Colville noted that two bullets fired from inside Kosovo struck the 
refugee reception center Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's foreign minister, meanwhile, said no progress has been  
made so far on finding a political solution to the Kosovo crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Deputy of Secretary of State Strobe Talbott returned to  
Moscow today for another round of talks. 
</P>
<P>
	Talks between Talbott, Russia's special envoy on Kosovo, Viktor  
Chernomyrdin, and Finnish President President Martti Ahtisaari were 
to resume Wednesday. The three men are spearheading efforts to find 
a political solution. 
</P>
<P>
	Chernomyrdin was to fly to Belgrade on Thursday with Ahtisaari  
to meet with Milosevic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990525.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 10:59:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  NATO Bombings Enter Third Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO's bombing campaign entered its  
third month today with missiles striking the abandoned Serb police 
headquarters in Belgrade and a villa said to be one of the 
residences of President Slobodan Milosevic. A new wave of refugees 
were bound for Macedonia. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO approved an updated operations plan with higher numbers for  
its Kosovo ground force today, a peacekeeping unit about 
50,000-strong that would be sent into the province from Macedonia 
as soon Serb troops depart. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States would probably furnish 7,000-8,000 troops as  
part of the plan, which now goes back to NATO generals to decide 
this month exactly how many troops with what specialties will be 
needed. 
</P>
<P>
	The operations plan was drawn up last year, creating a NATO-led  
international force of about 28,000 to implement an eventual peace 
agreement between the Yugoslav government and the ethnic Albanians, 
but that accord never materialized as the Kosovo conflict broke 
out. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of today's airstrikes focused on command and control  
facilities, including Milosevic's villa at Dobanovci, 12 miles west 
of Belgrade, NATO said. It was the third time the villa that NATO 
says also houses a major command center had been struck. 
</P>
<P>
	Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital, was down to its last 8 percent  
of water reserves because of damaged pumping stations and a power 
outage, Serb media reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The English-language V.I.P. newsletter reported fighting in much  
of Kosovo and said the most intense clashes were in the west, where 
Serbian forces were trying to regain positions lost to the rebel 
Kosovo Liberation Army in the past few weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	The allied campaign aims to force Milosevic to accept a peace  
deal for the southern Serb province that would include withdrawing 
Yugoslav forces from Kosovo, allowing NATO-led peacekeepers to 
police the accord and all refugees to return. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past three days, 22,000 ethnic Albanian refugees have  
poured out of Kosovo and into Macedonia, the most U.N. workers had 
seen since the first week of May. 
</P>
<P>
	Sources inside Yugoslavia have alerted Macedonia that 150,000  
more refugees are on the way, a Macedonian Foreign Ministry 
official said, speaking on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
