<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nevada Won't Block Tyson's Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- Mike Tyson doesn't figure to waste any time  
getting back into the ring. And Nevada boxing officials apparently 
won't get in his way. 
</P>
<P>
	With Tyson out of jail once again, his advisers and handlers are  
looking for him to fight as early as Aug. 21, and possibly once 
more before the end of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Aug. 21 is certainly a date we're looking at,'' said Jay  
Larkin, who runs boxing for the Showtime network. ``Hopefully in 
the next couple of days, we'll have something concrete.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A top Nevada boxing official, meanwhile, said Tuesday that  
Tyson's no contest plea that landed him in a Maryland jail will not 
be held against him. Dr. James Nave, vice chairman of the Nevada 
Athletic Commission, said Tyson likely won't face additional 
questions from state regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson won a license in October after extensive hearings to  
replace the one taken from him for biting Evander Holyfield's ears. 
It does not expire until the end of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	``My feeling is that he has a license,'' Nave said. ``I don't  
see the need for a hearing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson's advisers, caught off guard by his sudden release from  
jail Monday, were scrambling to make arrangements to get the 
fighter back in the ring as quickly as possible, possibly against 
Axel Schulz or Brian Nielsen. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson, whose last fight was a fifth round knockout of Francois  
Botha on Jan. 16, had his comeback interrupted when he was jailed 
in Maryland for assaulting two motorists following a traffic 
accident. 
</P>
<P>
	He served 3 1/2 months of a year-long sentence before being  
released on parole. 
</P>
<P>
	``We all agreed that while Mike Tyson was in jail, we wouldn't  
make any plans for his fights,'' Larkin said. ``Now, he's been out 
only 24 hours and we just haven't gotten to that point yet. But 
we're going to start right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Adding to the sense of urgency to get Tyson back into the ring  
is the fact that his advisers want him to fight twice this year. 
And, because prime pay-per-view dates in September and November are 
already blocked out because of two big fights, the options for 
fight dates are limited. 
</P>
<P>
	Oscar De La Hoya and Felix Trinidad are expected to fight on  
pay-per-view on Sept. 18, while Holyfield and Lennox Lewis meet on 
Nov. 13 in their rematch on pay-per-view. 
</P>
<P>
	That leaves Tyson with the option of fighting in August and  
again in December. An alternative, though, could be for Tyson's 
fight to be a network show and not a pay-per-view, something his 
handlers are also reportedly considering. 
</P>
<P>
	The thinking behind putting a Tyson fight on Showtime itself or  
even selling it to a major network is that it would be tough to 
sell Tyson again in a fight against someone similar to Botha. 
</P>
<P>
	The 32-year-old Tyson looked rusty and confused in the ring  
against Botha in what was his first fight in 19 months since the 
Holyfield biting incident. Plans before he was sent to jail were 
for him to fight at least four times this year, and there is 
concern about what kind of boxing shape and condition he will be 
in. 
</P>
<P>
	Larkin, whose network has a contract with Tyson and televises  
his pay-per-view fights, said discussions about an opponent will 
likely wait until Tyson gets in a gym and has a few workouts so his 
trainers can see what he looks like. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson remains one of the biggest pay-per-view attractions,  
although the number of homes that bought his fight with Botha 
slipped to about 750,000 from more than 1 million for several of 
his other fights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
