<DOCNO> APW19990525.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 15:39:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Steel Producers Want More Tariffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Leading U.S. steel producers said Tuesday they  
remain hurt by imports despite recent reductions and will soon ask 
the Clinton administration to consider more tariffs. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. government already has imposed punitive tariffs on some  
stainless steel, and a key ruling from the U.S. International Trade 
Commission in early June could lead to tariffs against Japan on 
hot-rolled carbon steel, the industry's most common product. 
</P>
<P>
	Tariffs would effectively make foreign steel too expensive to  
sell in U.S. markets, offering relief to a U.S. steel industry 
beleaguered by low-priced imports. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year's surge in imports, coming in the wake of the Asian  
economic crisis, which reduced demand for steel abroad, has been 
blamed for thousands of layoffs and bankruptcies at three U.S. 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Bethlehem Steel Corp., U.S. Steel Group and Steel Dynamics Inc.  
were among the companies planning to file trade complaints 
targeting cold-rolled steel, a thinner, stronger and more valuable 
product than the hot-rolled variety. 
</P>
<P>
	``Regretfully, imports are still too high,'' said Curtis H.  
Barnette, chairman and chief executive of Bethlehem Steel. ``While 
volume has been reduced, ... fair value in the marketplace has not 
been restored.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a conference call with reporters from the American Iron and  
Steel Institute's general meeting in New York, Barnette said the 
cold-rolled cases will be brought ``in the near future.'' He did 
not name the countries that will be targeted. 
</P>
<P>
	Because trade cases take several months to resolve, the decision  
to file additional complaints is a sign the industry does not 
believe its woes will go away anytime soon. 
</P>
<P>
	Imports have dropped by roughly 40 percent since November, and  
the industry credits past trade complaints for those reductions. 
</P>
<P>
	The industry also has sought quotas from Congress. Unlike trade  
complaints, which target specific products and specific countries, 
quotas would restrict steel globally. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990525.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 15:01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Down Against Most Currencies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar fell against the yen Tuesday as news  
surfaced about possible Senatorial opposition to Lawrence Summers' 
nomination to be Treasury secretary. 
</P>
<P>
	In listless, low-volume trading, the dollar's fall against the  
yen sparked the dollar's slide against other major currencies. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar fell to 122.70 yen from 123.21 Monday. The euro was  
quoted at $1.0601, rising from $1.0594. The dollar also was quoted 
at 1.5038 Swiss francs, down from 1.5122; and 1.4657 Canadian 
dollars, up from 1.4546. The British pound rose to $1.6028 from 
$1.5964. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders sent the dollar lower during Asian trading after a  
report that senators from steel states were thinking about blocking 
Summers' nomination to get the attention of the Clinton 
administration about protecting the U.S. steel industry. President 
Clinton nominated Summers to replace the well-respected Robert 
Rubin. 
</P>
<P>
	The industry suffered considerable job losses and plant closings  
last year as Japan and other nations allegedly dumped steel in the 
United States at lower than market prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The Washington Post said the bipartisan steel caucus is seeking  
passage of a bill that's before the Senate, and already approved by 
the House, that would roll back steel imports. The president has 
threatened to veto the bill as a violation of international trade 
laws. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite claims Tuesday by Sen. Mike DeWine, D-Ohio that his  
comments were misinterpreted and that he has no plans to do 
challenge Summers, the dollar was unable to recover in New York 
trading. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dollar/yen seems to be more of a political currency. The trade  
deficit against Japan is a lot bigger. It attracts a lot more 
attention than Europe's,'' said Jay Bryson, an international 
economist at First Union Capital Markets in Charlotte, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	Therefore, the yen ``took the hit last night,'' Bryson said. ``I  
think it's carried over today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The currencies of the 11 countries that have switched to the  
euro are no longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a 
fixed rate. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on the euro's latest exchange rate, the dollar was worth:  
1.8450 German marks, down from 1.8460; 6.1881 French francs, down 
from 6.1920; and 1,828.15 Italian lire, unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990525.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 19:41:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baseball Players in Anti-Smoking Ad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- New York Yankees outfielder Paul O'Neill  
says winning the World Series was his greatest accomplishment. 
Boston Red Sox shortstop Nomar Garciaparra says his was hitting two 
grand slams in one game. New York Mets third baseman Robin Ventura 
is most proud of ``quitting tobacco.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The three players star in a new public service campaign along  
with Travis Lee of the Arizona Diamondbacks and Eric Karros of the 
Los Angeles Dodgers to draw attention to World No Tobacco Day on 
May 31 as well as the global tobacco epidemic. 
</P>
<P>
	The coalition behind the global event turned to the baseball  
players as role models for young people in an attempt to counter 
the glamorous image of smoking the tobacco industry has created. 
</P>
<P>
	``These ballplayers can do much to reach our nation's youth and  
convince them of the dangers of tobacco use,'' baseball announcer 
and former major league all-star Tim McCarver told a news 
conference Tuesday, launching the campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	The public service broadcast, which will air in several  
ballparks over the Memorial Day weekend and throughout the baseball 
season, delivers the following message from O'Neill: 
</P>
<P>
	``May 31, World No Tobacco Day, could be the day YOU quit.  
Wouldn't it be great to spend the baseball season tobacco free?'' 
</P>
<P>
	World No Tobacco Day, first observed in 1988 and backed by the  
Pan American Health Organization, is the only international event 
established to raise awareness of the global impact of tobacco. A 
coalition of non-profit organizations and corporate sponsors is 
launching widespread initiatives this year to promote the day. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. David Kessler, the coalition's co-chair and dean of the Yale  
University School of Medicine, said the baseball campaign is one of 
many aimed at getting the estimated 1.1 billion smokers in the 
world to quit. 
</P>
<P>
	With tobacco use and tobacco-related illness skyrocketing in the  
developing world, countering the tobacco industry isn't going to be 
easy, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The United States tobacco industry is responsible for  
perpetuating the so-called glamorous appeal of tobacco use,'' 
Kessler said. ``It is up to U.S. health leaders and organizations 
like the coalition to tear down a century of brand and image 
building.'' 
</P>
<P>
	David Brandling-Bennett, deputy director of the Pan American  
Health Organization, said the coalition is hoping tobacco users 
will view May 31 as an opportunity to follow the day's theme -- 
``Leave The Pack Behind.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday in Geneva, the U.N. health chief said the start of work  
on a global tobacco-control treaty is an important first step 
toward tougher policies. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposed treaty, designed to accelerate the work of member  
states with weaker tobacco control programs, won't be ``just 
another way of raising awareness,'' said Gro Harlem Brundtland, 
director-general of the World Health Organization. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of course we are going to make it clear this product should  
not be advertised, subsidized or glamorized, but we are also going 
to'' help countries decide how to regulate or even make tobacco use 
illegal, Brundtland said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
