<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Saturn Moves Ahead With SUV Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Saturn Corp. is moving ahead with plans  
to make a sport utility vehicle, but company president Cynthia 
Trudell won't give a sneak preview. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not even a hint. Let me put it this way, we love the element  
of surprise,'' Trudell said Tuesday with a grin, shortly before 
speaking at a conference for automotive industry leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	GM's board of directors approved funding this month to design  
the SUV, create its manufacturing process and develop a supplier 
network. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now, the program can stop any time. So unless that thing is  
coming down the assembly line I never believe it,'' Trudell said. 
``But yes, they gave concurrence to advance funding for us to 
continue developing the product.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The SUV is considered key to the future success of Saturn, which  
last year posted its first loss since 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Trudell is focused on the new larger Saturns that go  
on sale this July. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturn is struggling to regain the strong reputation it enjoyed  
for much of the 1990s, when its ad campaign touted Saturn as a 
``different kind of car company,'' a reference to its no-haggle 
sales approach and strong labor-management relationship. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturn's 8,000 workers are not covered by the United Auto  
Workers contract in place at every other U.S. automaker. Their 
contract rewards productivity and gives workers input on management 
decisions. 
</P>
<P>
	As sales -- and worker bonuses -- declined, some Saturn employees  
called for scrapping the contract. Last summer, they threatened to 
strike but backed off when Saturn officials said GM planned to 
build the SUV in Spring Hill. 
</P>
<P>
	Trudell said Saturn has ``emerged stronger today as a result''  
of the unrest last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Trudell said that to succeed and grow, Saturn must continue to  
emphasize teamwork and customer service. 
</P>
<P>
	``This means we must continue to work toward a supportive  
environment in which everyone feels comfortable to contribute.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
