<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Money Withdrawn From Okla. Bomb Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- Local prosecutors plan to go ahead with the  
trial of Oklahoma City bombing conspirator Terry Nichols, despite a 
vote by the state Legislature to withdraw financial support for the 
case. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're disappointed that the Legislature is not going to help  
us,'' First Assistant District Attorney Robert Mitchell said 
Tuesday after the state House passed a bill to reallocate $1.2 
million for the trial. 
</P>
<P>
	``The office is committed to the prosecution. We'll see how this  
affects that, if at all,'' Mitchell said. 
</P>
<P>
	Nichols faces 160 murder charges for the April 19, 1995, bombing  
of the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building. He already is serving a 
life sentence after being convicted of federal charges in the 
attack. 
</P>
<P>
	The money would have gone to both the prosecution and the team  
retained to defend Nichols at taxpayer expense. The legislation 
would redistribute the money to help victims of the tornadoes that 
killed 44 people and damaged or destroyed nearly 7,000 homes 
earlier this month. 
</P>
<P>
	The House and Senate approved the measure, but a spokesman for  
Gov. Frank Keating said it is unclear whether the governor will 
sign it 
</P>
<P>
	``He feels it puts him in a difficult position,'' said John Cox.  
</P>
<P>
	Keating plans to meet with prosecutors and members of Nichols'  
defense team in the next week ``and find some middle ground on the 
issue,'' Cox said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers said their action reflected misgivings about the  
state's tight budget and the fact that Nichols is already serving a 
life sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	Nichols would be subject to the death penalty if convicted of  
the state murder charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Bednar, executive director of the state Indigent Defense  
System, said the legislation ends any hope of providing an adequate 
defense for Nichols, 44. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1995 bombing of the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building killed  
168 people and injured hundreds more. Prosecutors filed 160 murder 
charges against Nichols -- one count for each victim whose death was 
not part of Nichols' federal prosecution. 
</P>
<P>
	No state charges were filed against co-conspirator Timothy  
McVeigh, who was convicted in federal court and sentenced to death 
for the bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers have said a trial would be too expensive, with some  
estimating the cost at $20 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
