<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 16:22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Clinton Vows To Block Spying  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton, confronted by a bipartisan  
congressional conclusion that Chinese espionage has led to the 
theft of top-secret information about every U.S. nuclear weapon, 
said today he will put into place more than two dozen 
recommendations to safeguard America's nuclear secrets. A House 
committee catalogued 20 years of Chinese espionage and the panel's 
chairman, Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif., said China's spying 
campaign is still going on. The report concluded that by stealing 
nuclear secrets, China's weapon designs soon will be on par with 
those of the United States. 

</P>
<P>
	NYC Cop Guilty in Torture Case  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A white police officer accused of torturing a  
Haitian immigrant with a wooden stick in a stationhouse bathroom 
pleaded guilty today after the vaunted ``blue wall of silence'' 
came tumbling down around him. Justin Volpe, the central figure in 
an explosive brutality case that shocked the city and heightened 
racial tensions, pleaded guilty to civil rights charges three weeks 
into his trial. Volpe, 27, could be sent to prison for life. 

</P>
<P>
	House GOP Supports Gun-Control Plan  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House Republican leadership announced  
today its support for gun control measures included in a juvenile 
crime bill passed by the Senate last week. Judiciary Committee 
Chairman Henry Hyde said he hoped to get the bill to the House 
floor by mid-June. House Speaker Dennis Hastert said the final 
product would require gun sellers to provide safety devices, 
background checks at gun shows and other gun control measures. Rep. 
Bill McCollum, R-Fla., said the bill would require states to punish 
juvenile offenders as a condition for receiving federal grants. 

</P>
<P>
	Peace-Keeping Force Might Increase  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO warplanes attacked Slobodan  
Milosevic's villa and other targets across Yugoslavia today, and 
the military alliance approved a revised plan for an enlarged 
peacekeeping ground force of up to 50,000 in Kosovo as soon as Serb 
troops depart. A new wave of refugees -- as many as 150,000 -- were 
reported bound for Macedonia, and a U.N. report detailed in graphic 
fashion ``a significant upsurge'' in sexual violence against ethnic 
Albanian women in Kosovo since NATO airstrikes began two months 
ago. 

</P>
<P>
	Starr Won't Retry McDougal, Steele  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Kenneth Starr won't retry Whitewater figure  
Susan McDougal or Julie Hiatt Steele, both of whom were accused of 
hindering his investigation of President Clinton, The Associated 
Press has learned. Both cases ended in mistrials this spring. The 
independent counsel's decision came after juries handed him 
consecutive setbacks in his effort to punish witnesses he contended 
were uncooperative or gave false testimony that delayed his 
investigation. Jurors deadlocked in both cases. 

</P>
<P>
	Fires Burn at Both Ends of Florida  
</P>
<P>
	WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- One person was killed and 20 others  
injured when five tractor-trailers crashed into an overturned truck 
today on a smoke-shrouded highway where firefighters battled 
fast-spreading wildfires. About 20,000 acres of flaming sawgrass, 
brush and muck in the Rotenberger Wildlife Management Area sent 
heavy smoke into South Florida skies for the fifth day. Authorities 
said the smoke likely contributed to the fatal crash on U.S. 27. 

</P>
<P>
	Justice Dept. OKs Software Merger  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department approved Computer  
Associates International Inc.'s $3.5 billion purchase of smaller 
software rival, Platinum technology International, Inc., today 
after Computer Associates agreed to sell six Platinum products and 
related assets. Without the divestiture of the Platinum mainframe 
systems management software products, the government said, Computer 
Associates' dominance in a number of already concentrated software 
markets would have been significantly increased. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends 123.58 Lower  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks ended sharply lower today after continued  
concerns about interest rates and Internet stocks outweighed 
continued consumer optimism about the U.S. economy. At the close, 
the Dow industrials was down 123.58 at 10,531.09. Declining issues 
on the NYSE led advancers 1,909-1,082. The Nasdaq was down 72.77 to 
2,380.89. 

</P>
<P>
	Baseball Fires Curve at ESPN  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The feud continues between ESPN and Major League  
Baseball, with MLB countersuing the cable network over three 
late-season games that conflict with NFL telecasts. ESPN sued MLB 
earlier this month after the sport terminated a regular-season 
contract with the cable network that was supposed to run through 
2002. MLB is claiming it should be paid damages because the cable 
television network broke its contract when it decided three 
football games would draw much higher ratings than three baseball 
games. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by JEROME MINERVA  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
