<DOCNO> APW19990525.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 17:51:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> WWII Survivors Sue German Drug Cos. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- Survivors of hideous Holocaust medical  
``experiments,'' some conducted by the infamous Dr. Joseph Mengele, 
are charging in lawsuits that German pharmaceutical companies 
participated in the tests and profited from their pain. 
</P>
<P>
	The survivors include twins who say that, a half-century later,  
they clearly remember Mengele, Auschwitz's ``Angel of Death,'' 
scrutinizing their naked, tortured bodies. 
</P>
<P>
	The two federal class-action lawsuits filed here this month  
against Bayer AG, Hoechst AG and Schering AG are among the first in 
the nation linking German companies to Nazi medical experiments. A 
similar class-action lawsuit against Bayer was filed in Indiana in 
February. 
</P>
<P>
	The three class-action lawsuits filed May 13 are the latest  
filings in a recent wave of litigation by survivors of Nazi death 
camps or slave labor factories aimed at European banks, insurance 
companies and industrial firms. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the Newark suits, one is filed on behalf of U.S. citizens,  
the other for citizens of other nations. Each seeks unspecified 
damages for survivors it estimates number in the hundreds. 
</P>
<P>
	They accuse the companies of providing toxic chemicals to the  
Nazis for the ``experiments.'' Company personnel supervised the 
work and used information from those experiments to market products 
sold during and after the war, the lawsuits said. 
</P>
<P>
	Schering also participated in these experiments, but also  
supported experimental sterilization procedures on camp inmates, 
the lawsuit said. 
</P>
<P>
	The allegations stem from ``various documents that have become  
available for researching that were not available before,'' said 
Joseph D. Ament, a Chicago lawyer representing plaintiffs in the 
Newark cases. 
</P>
<P>
	All of the survivor lawsuits, many filed in U.S. District Court  
here, have been made possible by a 1991 international agreement 
settling German reparations to other nations, and thus allowing 
individuals to sue, said Burt Neuborne, a professor at New York 
University Law School who is among the lawyers pressing the Newark 
lawsuits. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoechst issued a statement that did not address the medical  
experimentation claims, but cited the company's support of 
``various organizations and projects dedicated to preserving the 
memory of the atrocities of the Nazi regime.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bayer spokesman Thomas Reinert in Leverkusen, Germany, said the  
company would not comment on the lawsuits at this time. 
</P>
<P>
	Schering spokesman Gert Wlasich said the company would examine  
the claims before commenting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990525.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 14:31:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S.-China Relations Likely To Sour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Already under heavy strain, U.S.-Chinese  
relations are likely to slide further after charges that Beijing 
stole America's nuclear-weapons secrets. There also could be 
substantial political fallout, with accusations of blame 
reverberating into next year's presidential campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	A 700-page report from a congressional committee Tuesday  
documented what even its top Democrat, Rep. Norm Dicks of 
Washington, acknowledged was ``one of the worst counterintelligence 
failures in the nation's history.'' The espionage stretched over 20 
years across Republican and Democratic administrations and probably 
continues today, the chairman of the panel, Rep. Christopher Cox, 
R-Calif., said. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the another blow to a relationship already shaken by the  
U.S. bombing of China's embassy in Belgrade and allegations of 
illegal campaign contributions for President Clinton from Beijing. 
Each side has its own list of grievances. China bristles at 
pressure from the United States on human rights and trade and 
planning for a missile defense system. 
</P>
<P>
	The gulf has widened dramatically since Clinton toured China a  
year ago -- the first visit by an American president since the 1989 
Tiananmen Square crackdown -- and raised expectations for positive 
change. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was a perfect example where personal diplomacy got out  
ahead of reality,'' said Richard Haass, director of foreign policy 
studies at the Brookings Institution. ``This is another setback. It 
is a relationship that is deteriorating, and we've yet to come up 
with a formula that both sides can embrace for a relationship that 
is non adversarial and maybe even productive. This is a 
relationship that is yet to find a post Cold War footing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the frontrunner for the Republican  
presidential nomination, put aside his usual reluctance to speak on 
foreign policy matters and seized on the congressional report. He 
attacked the administration's ``failed policies toward China'' and 
urged a congressional investigation into ``what went wrong and 
why.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gary Bauer, another GOP presidential hopeful, said the report  
confirms ``that the Clinton-Gore administration cares more for 
their political security than America's national security.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The China issue and the ways to deal with China are going to  
be the top foreign policy issues in the presidential campaign,'' 
said David Shambaugh, a China military expert at George Washington 
University. ``It's likely to be highly politicized.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The spying charge threatens prospects for congressional approval  
of China's membership in the World Trade Organization. Another 
casualty is U.S.-Chinese military relations, already frozen after 
the Belgrade bombing. Defense Secretary William Cohen dropped plans 
to visit China next month, in part because of heightened tensions. 
</P>
<P>
	The accusations also will cloud the debate next month over  
renewing normalized trade benefits for China -- although analysts 
expect the benefits will be approved, anyway. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the last few years there has been sharp rhetoric but in  
fact, every time Congress has had to vote, it has voted by bigger 
margins to continue normal trade relations,'' said David Lampton, 
director of China studies at the Nixon Center and the Johns Hopkins 
School of Advanced International Studies. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not only the American business community but the hundreds of  
thousands of Americans who owe their jobs to trade will leaven 
their anger with recognition we still have positive interests,'' 
Lampton said. 
</P>
<P>
	It should come as no surprise that China spied on the United  
States. Practically everybody does it, even our friends. 
</P>
<P>
	Israel, one of America's closest partners, stole enough national  
security documents and photographs from Washington in the 1980s via 
former Navy intelligence officer Jonathan Pollard to fill a room 10 
feet by 6 feet by 6 feet. For its part, the United States spies on 
allies and adversaries alike. 
</P>
<P>
	What is alarming about China's espionage is how successful it  
was in obtaining some of America's most closely guarded nuclear 
warhead secrets. 
</P>
<P>
	``A great deal of the excitement politically will be on who did  
what in either political party, in what regime or administration in 
our country,'' said Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind. 
</P>
<P>
	But Democrats reject criticism that the Clinton administration  
failed to be alert to signs of trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	``This matter goes back to 1982,'' said Senate Minority Leader  
Tom Daschle, D-S.D. ``The Reagan administration did nothing. The 
Bush administration did nothing. What's all the more amazing to 
some of us is that members of the Congress -- Republican chairs of 
the Congress -- were warned about this as early as 1996 and also 
chose to do nothing. This administration is the first to do 
something.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *EDITORS NOTE -- Terence Hunt has covered the Reagan, Bush and  
Clinton presidencies 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
