<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 20:51:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boatman Convicted in Haitian Deaths one conviction in two deaths. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
No pickup.  
<P>
	FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) -- A boat captain was convicted  
Tuesday of his role in a smuggling operation in which 19 Haitians 
were forced to swim to shore, leading to the deaths of two by 
drowning. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal jury found Addison Joseph Hepburn, 45, guilty of one  
count of smuggling for profit resulting in the death of an alien 
and eight counts each of smuggling and smuggling for profit. 
</P>
<P>
	Sentencing guidelines call for a minimum mandatory three years  
in prison, and he could face up to life in prison. Sentencing was 
scheduled for Aug. 13. 
</P>
<P>
	At least 33 Haitians who paid $350 each to reach the United  
States via the Bahamas were abandoned in August 1998 on a sandbar 
100 yards offshore near Jupiter Inlet. 
</P>
<P>
	Nineteen swam to shore, but two died struggling to make it.  
</P>
<P>
	Searchers pulled from the water the bodies of Anne Benette  
Dorsonne, 25, of Port-au-Prince, and Richard Presendieu. 
</P>
<P>
	Jurors acquitted Hepburn in the death of Presendieu, whose body  
came ashore a day later and a mile north of the landing point. 
Prosecutors were unable to prove Presendieu was on the smuggling 
trip, said Randee Golder, Hepburn's attorney. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
