<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brazilian Markets React to Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- The optimism over Brazil's economic  
recovery was dampened Tuesday by allegations that President 
Fernando Henrique Cardoso tried to influence the outcome of the $19 
billion privatization of the national phone company last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The charges, published in the Folha de Sao Paulo newspaper,  
added to a spate of economic worries that sent the Sao Paulo Stock 
Exchange down nearly 5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Folha published the transcripts of 46 illegally taped phone  
conversations. In one, Cardoso authorizes the use of his name to 
persuade a balky pension fund to take part in the bidding for 
federal telecommunications giant Telebras. 
</P>
<P>
	The actual tapes were played on radio and TV broadcasts.  
</P>
<P>
	Charges of government tampering with the bidding first emerged  
late last year and led to the resignation of former Communications 
Minister Luiz Carlos Mendonca de Barros and Andre Lara Resende, 
then president of Brazil's National Development Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	Secretly recorded conversations apparently showed the two trying  
to benefit a consortium, although the group lost the bidding. The 
group Cardoso allegedly supported also lost. 
</P>
<P>
	The Presidential Palace issued a statement late in the afternoon  
calling the charges ``sensationalist and riddled with insinuations 
that don't correspond to the transcriptions of the illegally 
obtained information.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Senate president Antonio Carlos Magalhaes, a Cardoso ally and  
one of the country's most powerful politicians, said: ``There's no 
involvement of the president whatsoever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Arthur Virgilio, the government leader in the Chamber of  
Deputies, said Cardoso's attitude was not ethically wrong because 
it was the government's job to encourage competition and raise the 
bids. Telebras was sold for 63 percent above the minimum bid, a 
price analysts considered surprisingly good. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexandre Barros, a political analyst in Brasilia, the capital,  
said the scandal adds to a list of irregularities that have come 
dangerously close to Cardoso and his top aides. He cited recent 
cases of government officials flying to vacation resorts on Air 
Force planes, and congressional inquiries into irregularities in 
Brazilian banks and courts. 
</P>
<P>
	``This could further undermine his authority and popularity,  
which recession and unemployment have already weakened,'' said 
Barros. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
