<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyers To Drop Race Profiling Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW BRUNSWICK, N.J. (AP) -- Prosecutors are seeking to drop  
charges against 21 people arrested by two state troopers accused of 
singling out minority drivers for traffic stops and then lying 
about it. 
</P>
<P>
	Middlesex County prosecutor Lawrence West filed a motion Friday  
to dismiss charges against the black and Hispanic defendants. 
</P>
<P>
	The cases involve arrests by State Police Troopers John Hogan  
and James Kenna on the New Jersey Turnpike. They were indicted last 
month on charges that they falsified records to hide their alleged 
practice of targeting minorities. 
</P>
<P>
	A few days after misconduct charges against the troopers were  
made public, a state report concluded that the State Police target 
minorities. 
</P>
<P>
	The 21 cases involve charges ranging from minor traffic and drug  
possession violations to attempted murder. The two troopers would 
have likely testified in the cases. 
</P>
<P>
	``They would have no credibility to testify,'' said Chuck Davis,  
a spokesman for the attorney general's office. 
</P>
<P>
	Superior Court Judge Robert Longhi scheduled a hearing on the  
motion for Wednesday. Defense attorneys said they expect the 
charges to be dismissed. 
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't want our clients' rights to a speedy trial  
jeopardized,'' said public defender Dale Jones, who is tracking the 
cases. ``This comes as welcome news to us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Justice Department also has investigated racial  
profiling allegations against New Jersey's state police. Similar 
accusations have been made in Florida, Maryland, Connecticut and 
elsewhere. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
