<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bank Robber's Conviction Overturned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EASTON, Pa. (AP) -- A federal judge has overturned the  
13-year-old conviction of a man sentenced to death row for killing 
three people during a bank robbery. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge William Yohn Jr. ruled Friday that  
court-appointed attorneys for Martin Appel were ineffective because 
they didn't aggressively try to prove him incompetent to represent 
himself. 
</P>
<P>
	Yohn ordered the state to act within 180 days or Appel could go  
free. 
</P>
<P>
	Northampton County District Attorney John Morganelli called the  
decision an ``outrage,'' saying it ``underscores all that is wrong 
with the criminal justice system.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Relatives of the victims also were angered by the judge's  
decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's not right,'' said Shad Confer, 18, whose grandmother  
was slain in the robbery. ``He killed people and he's getting away 
with it. What good is the justice system? He admitted to it and 
then he laughed about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Appel, 40, pleaded guilty to robbing the First National Bank of  
Bath in East Allen Township of less than $3,000 on June 6, 1986, 
killing three and wounding two others. 
</P>
<P>
	He argued that he had a delusional disorder in which he believed  
he worked for the CIA and had to eliminate ``moles'' or ``clones'' 
at the bank. 
</P>
<P>
	After Appel, a former cab driver and prison guard, rejected  
legal help and asked to be executed, he was sentenced to death in 
August 1986. Co-defendant Stanley Hertzog was sentenced to life in 
prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Yohn ruled that Appel's court-appointed attorneys at his  
competency hearing, Ellen Kraft and Lorenzo Crowe Jr., could have 
interviewed Appel's friends and gathered records to help determine 
his mental fitness. 
</P>
<P>
	``The record is undisputed that they failed to do so,'' the  
judge said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kraft was unaware of the ruling when contacted for comment  
Monday. Crowe did not return a call seeking comment. 
</P>
<P>
	But Morganelli described the judge's decision a ``stretching of  
the right to counsel.'' He pointed out that Appel had refused 
counsel, and two psychiatrists and a psychologist had determined he 
was competent to make the decision to defend himself. 
</P>
<P>
	John Spirk Jr., who prosecuted the case in the 1980s, was  
surprised by the ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	``My first thought when I heard it was for the victims and the  
families,'' said Spirk, now the solicitor for Northampton County. 
``After all these years, it has to be devastating for them. It's 
still a very open wound.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
