<DOCNO> APW19990525.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 06:36:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Gandhi Withdraws Party Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- Hundreds of Congress party delegates  
filled a sports stadium in New Delhi today to hear a speech by 
Sonia Gandhi, who has withdrawn her resignation as the party's 
leader. 
</P>
<P>
	The Italian-born Mrs. Gandhi, the widow of a former prime  
minister and heiress to India's strongest political dynasty, 
answered internal criticism that a foreign-born politician should 
not lead India's oldest political party in fall general elections. 
</P>
<P>
	``India accepted me 31 years ago, the day I came here as Indira  
Gandhi's daughter-in-law,'' she told the 1,400 delegates to the 
party's decision making body, referring to the former prime 
minister. ``I got married here, became mother here and became a 
widow here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Gandhi said she is not seeking power and that her party  
will decide if she should become prime minister. The delegates 
later adopted a resolution saying Mrs. Gandhi's Italian background 
was a non-issue in the elections. 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands of party workers jammed the streets surrounding the  
stadium, prompting police to delay her arrival by several hours 
because of security risks. ``Hail Sonia Gandhi!'' the crowd chanted 
in Hindi. 
</P>
<P>
	The rally comes the same day as local newspapers reported that  
the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, a Sri Lankan rebel group, 
were plotting to assassinate her. In 1991, the group killed her 
husband, former Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi, and they still fear 
she will crack down on their supporters in southern India. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hindu, a respected English-language daily, reported today  
that Tiger guerilla have rehearsed a car bomb attack in northern 
India. The guerrillas reportedly want to stage the attack in a 
northern state to deflect suspicion away from the Tigers. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal government recently alerted state police chiefs  
about a secret meeting the Tigers held in South Africa in April 
during which they discussed assassinating Mrs. Gandhi with a car 
bomb, the paper quoted unnamed sources as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	Indian intelligence agencies reportedly learned of the threats a  
few weeks ago and immediately asked Mrs. Gandhi to take extra 
precautions. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Gandhi is among the most protected persons in India. She is  
surrounded by 48 commandoes at all times and 250 policemen set up 
three cordons around her wherever she goes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every drop of my blood belongs to this country,'' Mrs. Gandhi  
said, reading out her speech today in halting Hindi and English. 
</P>
<P>
	The Congress party was thrown into controversy last week when  
three of the party's leaders questioned Mrs. Gandhi's Italian 
ancestry and lack of political experience. A week ago, she resigned 
from the party's leadership in protest. 
</P>
<P>
	The dissenters were later expelled and pledged to set up their  
own party to run in the September elections called after the 
collapse of India's minority government last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of workers besieged her fortress-like house in New  
Delhi to urge her to withdraw her resignation letter. Opposition 
parties called the resignation a sham, aimed at drumming up 
support. 
</P>
<P>
	The elections are mainly a battle between the Congress and the  
Hindu-nationalist Bharatiya Janata Party, which lost power in 
April. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990525.0200 </DOCNO>
