<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> `East Is East' Short on Substance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The greasy aroma of fish and chips greets  
theatergoers at Manhattan Theater Club these days, getting them in 
the right mood for ``East Is East,'' Ayub Khan-Din's obvious yet 
atmospheric generational comedy. 
</P>
<P>
	``East Is East,'' a joint venture between two off-Broadway  
companies (MTC and the New Group), is heavy on atmosphere, 
especially in the way it portrays its tale of immigrant life in a 
working-class English town in the early 1970s. 
</P>
<P>
	Substance is another thing. Khan-Din's plot tends to mimic the  
sitcoms that forever seem to be on the family's telly, although the 
story delivers a few twists that would never get by the TV censors 
of nearly 30 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Patriarch George Khan, born in Pakistan, runs a small  
fish-and-chip shop. Six of his seven children help out, doing their 
jobs with varying degrees of resentment. His harassed, hardworking 
wife, Ella, is English. 
</P>
<P>
	Their Anglo-Pakistani children are caught between the two worlds  
-- and always trying to figure out where and how they belong. This 
clash of cultures forms the heart of ``East Is East,'' most of the 
battles centering on arranged marriages made by the father for two 
of his sons. 
</P>
<P>
	Khan-Din takes a while to sort out these youngsters, and even  
then, they are given only the sketchiest of character development. 
A lot of attention is paid to 12-year-old Sajit, who, his father 
discovers, has never been circumcised. 
</P>
<P>
	Sajit is a strange boy, given to hiding in the coal shed and  
refusing to take off a favorite hooded coat, a garment in serious 
need of a good washing. His eccentricities are mined for a lot of 
jokes, most of them quite funny. 
</P>
<P>
	The other children are not as lovingly developed -- or  
particularly well acted. They are plot devices rather than people. 
The playwright has more luck with the mother, played with 
considerable spirit by Jenny Sterlin. She is the play's weary 
heroine, battling not only the obtuseness of her husband but the 
prejudices of English society. 
</P>
<P>
	As the tyrannical father, Edward A. Hajj blusters effectively.  
He has a harder time managing the play's quieter moments. One would 
have liked to see more of the couple's relationship. 
</P>
<P>
	Director Scott Elliott, who runs the New Group, displays a sure  
hand with the play's frequent histrionics. The fights are staged at 
full throttle. 
</P>
<P>
	In terms of atmosphere, he gets considerable help from a strong  
production team. Designer Derek McLane's settings -- including the 
family's fish-and-chip shop -- are models of realism. He manages to 
transform the family's flat into an homage to 1970s bad taste. It 
exudes a lived-in feeling that manages to be theatrical as well. 
</P>
<P>
	If ``East Is East'' sometimes borders on the cartoonish, it  
still pulsates with life. The play, a hit in England, has been made 
into a movie. Its broad strokes should work better on the big 
screen, or maybe, come to think of it, as a television series, 
where all those siblings would have a chance to shine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990525.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 16:02:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  MSG Chief Apologizes to Van Gundy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Jeff Van Gundy will remain in limbo for the  
foreseeable future. 
</P>
<P>
	The coach of the New York Knicks met with the president of  
Madison Square Garden on Monday and received an apology for being 
lied to about the team's meeting with former Bulls coach Phil 
Jackson. 
</P>
<P>
	But rather than put the issue completely to rest by assuring  
everyone that Van Gundy would remain as coach next season, team 
president Dave Checketts said no decisions will be made until the 
season ends. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not fair to make an evaluation on somebody or a judgment  
on what should happen in the organization based on one series, one 
shot or one win,'' Checketts said. ``He (Van Gundy) has agreed to 
that and he's comfortable with that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Van Gundy, however, was clearly uncomfortable with discussing  
the subject after the Knicks defeated the Atlanta Hawks 79-66 for a 
4-0 sweep of their second-round series. 
</P>
<P>
	It's not every day, after all, that one's boss comes into an  
underling's office and says he's sorry for lying to your face. 
</P>
<P>
	``He explained himself to me and I listened,'' Van Gundy said.  
``It's a non-issue to me. The only thing I was worried about was 
getting one more win, and now all I'm concerned with is trying to 
get back to the finals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For the better part of the day Sunday, Checketts denied having  
any contact with Jackson despite two newspaper reports saying they 
sat down together to gauge Jackson's interest in the job. 
</P>
<P>
	But late in the afternoon, while Game 3 was still being played,  
Checketts confessed the truth. He was lambasted in Monday's papers 
as a shiftless corporate snake in a building of backstabbers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I regret that I lied about it,'' Checketts said. ``We met for  
a couple of hours, and there were no offers exchanged. There was 
nothing that came out of the meeting other than getting acquainted 
with a guy who I felt was a tremendous option for us if we had not 
made the playoffs and needed a new direction. 
</P>
<P>
	``If anything, what I did is err on the side of protecting  
everyone. I had to do the job of finding out if I had an option 
like that,'' Checketts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Checketts, the president of Madison Square Garden, has been  
running the Knicks on a day-to-day basis since general manager 
Ernie Grunfeld was demoted in mid-April because of a rift between 
him and Van Gundy. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the unanswered questions surrounding the  
Checketts-Jackson meeting is who set it up. Checketts said he 
contacted Jackson through an intermediary, but he refused to say 
who it was. 
</P>
<P>
	Tony Wyche, a spokesman for presidential candidate Bill Bradley,  
said the former Knicks forward was not the emissary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990525.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 16:02:26 </DATE_TIME>
