<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) -- The Honduran government is  
investigating whether military officers conspired to take control 
of the country and repeal constitutional reforms that weakened the 
power of the armed forces, officials said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	National Defense Minister Edgardo Dumas told reporters ``the  
investigation will establish whether military personnel intended to 
recover the power they once held.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Honduras returned to civilian rule in 1981, ending nearly two  
decades of military regimes that had been born from a series of 
coups against the presidency. 
</P>
<P>
	In January, Congress eliminated the military's autonomy and the  
constitutional immunity enjoyed by commanders since 1957. Dumas, a 
lawyer, also became the third civilian in Honduras' 178-year 
history to lead the defense ministry. 
</P>
<P>
	The investigation was sparked by media reports that high-ranking  
officers, allegedly led by Joint Chief of Staff Col. Eugenio 
Romero, were conspiring against Dumas. 
</P>
<P>
	Romero admitted meeting last week with opposition and governing  
party politicians to discuss the constitutional reforms but said 
``these conferences were not to recover ground lost by the armed 
forces to civilian rule.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	GUATEMALA CITY (AP) -- A British man has been ordered to stand  
trial in Guatemala on charges of defaming and slandering a 
Guatemalan lawyer he accused of organizing illegal adoptions for 
foreigners, a court said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Bruce Harris, director of the child aid group Casa Alianza, will  
be called to testify on his statements about Susana de Umana, the 
10th Court of Appeals said. 
</P>
<P>
	In news reports last year, Harris accused Umana of trafficking  
in children. Umana says Harris harmed her professional and personal 
reputation and challenged him to present evidence of his claims. 
</P>
<P>
	Harris was traveling in Costa Rica on Tuesday and could not be  
reached for comment, according to Arturo Echeverria, the national 
director of the U.S.-based Casa Alianza. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) -- The headquarters of an Army battalion  
that fought in World War II and Vietnam was closed Tuesday as the 
United States continues its withdrawal from the Panama Canal Zone. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today is a moment of closure, a moment of sadness, the time of  
a new beginning,'' said Lt. Col. Randall E. Tindall, commander of 
Battalion 245, headquartered at the Clayton Base. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States is slowly transferring its facilities in the  
Canal Zone as it prepares for the Dec. 31 handover under treaties 
signed in 1977. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. military's presence in Panama dates back to the canal's  
construction around the turn of the century. 
</P>
<P>
	Battalion 245 was created under a different name in 1940, and  
its soldiers fought in World War II and Vietnam. It also has helped 
drug-fighting and humanitarian efforts throughout Latin America. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	JALAPA, Mexico (AP) -- Mexico is advancing in the fight against  
drugs, the U.S. ambassador said Tuesday, a day after the outgoing 
head of the Drug Enforcement Administration said the country isn't 
doing enough. 
</P>
<P>
	``We all have to be very clear. The work of the Mexican  
government has improved in recent years,'' Ambassador Jeffrey 
Davidow told reporters in the eastern state Veracruz, where he was 
meeting with Gov. Miguel Aleman. 
</P>
<P>
	DEA head Thomas Constantine, an outspoken critic of Mexico's  
anti-drug efforts, announced Monday he is resigning. He said that 
after 39 years in law enforcement and five years heading the DEA, 
it was time to pursue other options. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview with The Associated Press, Constantine said  
Monday that ``traffickers have become infinitely more powerful in 
the last five years, and they are a major threat to citizens of the 
United States and the institutions of Mexico.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Washington Post quoted him as saying that U.S. officials  
know who the top 20 or 25 Mexican drug dealers are ``but the 
Mexican law enforcement is so weak it seems unable even to find 
them, never mind arrest them or extradite him.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990525.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 18:31:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clintons To Begin Fla. Vacation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	YULEE, Fla. (AP) -- President Clinton arrived in Florida on  
Tuesday for a five-day vacation with the first lady at a 7,500-acre 
conservation area inhabited by giraffes, cheetahs and white rhinos. 
</P>
<P>
	The president and Hillary Rodham Clinton were invited to White  
Oak Plantation in the backwoods of northern Florida as guests of 
the Howard Gilman Foundation, said White House spokesman Joe 
Lockhart. 
</P>
<P>
	White Oak, located just across the St. Marys River from Georgia,  
is home to several rare species, including white rhinos and Florida 
panthers. The 14 houses spread across the property include log 
cabins, lodges and modern stucco dwellings. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton and his wife were traveling without daughter Chelsea,  
who is still in school at Stanford University. The president's 
Labrador, Buddy, did make the journey aboard Air Force One. 
</P>
<P>
	Turning up a dirt road leading to the plantation, the president,  
still dressed in a suit, halted the bronze presidential Suburban he 
was riding in to greet a dozen local residents in shorts and 
T-shirts waiting in front of a small house. 
</P>
<P>
	As he turned to leave, he noted an important member of his party  
was missing. ``Hey, where's Buddy?'' Clinton asked. Buddy, after a 
tense standoff with the well-wishers' fence-hopping bulldog, was 
sniffing out the new acquaintance. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clintons had no plans to venture off White Oak's grounds.  
But that wasn't a sign that the golfer in chief was giving up his 
favorite pastime for animal watching: White Oak has a nine-hole 
course and a swimming pool. 
</P>
<P>
	The quiet time also gave Mrs. Clinton an opportunity to ponder  
her potential bid for the Senate seat being vacated by New York 
Democrat Patrick Moynihan. 
</P>
<P>
	``She did say that she planned to spend some time thinking about  
this,'' said spokeswoman Marsha Berry. ``I think she's thinking 
about that stuff all the time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton was to fly to Jacksonville, Fla., and make the short  
drive to Yulee after joining Vice President Al Gore in Edinburg, 
Texas, for Gore's annual empowerment zone conference. 
</P>
<P>
	At the conference, the president touted his work to steer  
investment toward distressed communities and announced formation of 
the Southwest Border Economic Development Initiative, an effort to 
better coordinate federal assistance to poor communities along the 
Mexican border. 
</P>
<P>
	With Gore by his side on the turf of Gov. George W. Bush,  
considered the front-runner for the GOP nomination in 2000, Clinton 
urged state leaders to join him in combatting youth violence by 
placing more controls on guns. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every state and every community must be involved in this  
effort,'' the president said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clintons planned to stay in Yulee until late Sunday, so they  
can participate in a conference at White Oak by the Democratic 
Leadership Council and its think tank, the Progressive Policy 
Institute. 
</P>
<P>
	The secluded White Oak is located off an unmarked dirt road  
about 20 miles north of Jacksonville. The Clintons were staying at 
Roseland, a two-story, cedar paneled, five-bedroom house. 
</P>
<P>
	Roseland offered a view of a white rhino's lair, part of a  
wildlife preserve and breeding center established by Gilman in 1982 
on the site of his family home. More than 400 animals representing 
60 different species live on the plantation, which is staffed by 
more than 40 zoologists. 
</P>
<P>
	Previous guests have included Gore, Colin Powell, Mikhail  
Baryshnikov, John F. Kennedy Jr., Julia Roberts and Jessica Lange. 
</P>
<P>
	Gilman, who died last year at 73, was chairman and chief  
executive officer of Gilman Paper Co. in nearby St. Marys, Ga. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990525.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 16:02:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Pacers Are Trying To Stay Sharp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- It's rust, not rest, that worries the  
Indiana Pacers, the only team without a loss through the first two 
rounds of the NBA playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	A three-game sweep of Milwaukee in the first round and a  
four-game sweep of Philadelphia in the Eastern Conference 
semifinals took minimal toll on the Pacers physically. But it also 
meant a full week will have passed before they open the conference 
finals against New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if it hurts or helps. All I know is that it is  
for all the marbles to go to the championship, to have the 
opportunity to go to the finals and win this whole thing,'' Mark 
Jackson said after a brief shoot-around Tuesday. ``There's no time 
for any excuses now. We're excited about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Knicks wrapped up a four-game sweep of Atlanta on Monday  
night, so they'll have almost as much time between games as the 
Pacers. 
</P>
<P>
	``You get a little rusty,'' Indiana coach Larry Bird said. ``I  
had that happen to us in Boston before. We had eight or nine days 
and came out a little rusty. But New York's got a lot of time, too, 
so we'll get back to work tomorrow and try to practice as hard as 
we possibly can to prepare these guys and hopefully go into the 
first game on Sunday ready to play. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it will be mental. I think it'll be physical,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pacers' last game was on Sunday, when they finished off the  
76ers in Philadelphia. They'll break up the practice routine this 
week with a scrimmage, open to the public, at Market Square Arena 
on Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Reggie Miller called the week between games ``a double-edged  
sword.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It goes both ways,'' Miller said. ``It's great because we're  
going to be well prepared for New York, and vice versa, but on the 
other hand it's kind of good to be playing basketball games and 
getting banged and moved around. 
</P>
<P>
	``You don't want some of the rust to settle into your game at  
all, but I'm sure both teams will be ready come Sunday,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The first two games in the best-of-7 series will be at Indiana  
Sunday afternoon and Tuesday night. Games 3 and 4 will be in New 
York the following Saturday and Monday. If necessary, the remaining 
games will be in Indianapolis on June 9, in New York June 11 and 
back to Indy on June 13 for a Game 7. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pacers are working on a 12-game playoff winning streak at  
home, but in three previous trips to the conference finals -- 1994, 
1995 and 1998 -- they never had homecourt advantage and lost on the 
road each time in the seventh game. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, Indiana earned the homecourt edge in the East after  
both Miami and Orlando lost in the first round. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't rely on homecourt advantage that much, but we feel  
very fortunate to have it so we want to take advantage of it,'' 
Bird said. ``We played a lot better at home, and we're playing 
awful well on the road. We lucked into homecourt advantage, and 
we're playing against a team that's played a lot better, but we've 
got to worry about ourselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Knicks were seeded eighth in the East but took out Miami in  
five games and Atlanta in four. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're playing much better, with a lot more confidence thanks  
to an Atlanta team that looked like they could care less,'' Jackson 
said. ``But give the Knicks credit. They're playing better 
basketball, and it'll be a war of a series.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indiana won two of three regular-season games against New York  
this year. The two teams have met in four previous playoff series, 
each winning twice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990525.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 16:02:16 </DATE_TIME>
