<DOCNO> APW19990525.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 05:42:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House OKs Foreign Nurse Visa Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A fixed number of licensed, foreign nurses  
would be admitted to the United States to work in understaffed 
hospitals nationwide, mostly in poor inner-city and rural areas, 
under a bill the House passed Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill, which advanced to the Senate by voice vote, would  
create a program similar to one that expired in the fall of 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	The new program, which would expire four years after it is  
created, would authorize temporary work visas for up to 500 
qualified foreign nurses to enter the country each year to work in 
short-staffed hospitals for up to five years. 
</P>
<P>
	They must be paid the same wages and work the same hours as U.S.  
nurses, according to the bill, which also includes safeguards to 
protect American jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Hospitals would be required to prove they have exhausted all  
efforts to recruit and retain domestic nurses before they turn to 
the visa program. 
</P>
<P>
	They also must meet certain criteria to participate. Hospitals  
must be located in an area experiencing a shortage of health care 
professionals, as designated by the Department of Health and Human 
Services; have at least 190 acute care beds; and have certain 
percentages of their patients on Medicare and Medicaid. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill was sponsored by Rep. Bobby Rush, D-Ill.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is H.R. 441.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
