<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grain, Soybeans Move Higher / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures prices moved higher  
early today on the Chicago Board of Trade as investors eyed the 
potential for heat damage to newly planted crops. 
</P>
<P>
	Forecasters were calling for a high-pressure ridge to begin  
forming in Midwest growing regions next week, which could choke off 
rainfall and place heat stress on young crops. 
</P>
<P>
	Gains were limited, however, as farmers continued to proceed  
with fieldwork. The pace of corn and soybean planting generally has 
matched or exceeded five-year averages. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures also faced pressure from early harvesting of the  
winter wheat crop, where some farmers were reporting above-average 
yields. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery rose 1 1/4 cents to $2.48 1/2 a bushel; July  
corn rose 1 1/2 cents to $2.13 1/4 a bushel; July oats rose 1/2 cent to 
$1.18 1/4 a bushel; July soybeans rose 2 1/2 cents to $4.57 1/2 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef and lean hog futures were mostly lower on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange, while pork bellies advanced. 
</P>
<P>
	June live cattle fell .23 cent to 63.12 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle fell .47 cent to 74.85 cents a pound; June lean hogs 
fell .75 cent to 54.15 cents a pound; July pork bellies rose .75 
cent to 52.95 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
