<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> UN Seeks To Expand Refugee Camps </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BLACE, Macedonia (AP) -- U.N. aid officials were negotiating with  
Macedonia's reluctant government today for permission to expand 
refugee camps in the country to cope with a surge of ethnic 
Albanians fleeing Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	About 22,000 refugees, many bringing stories of abuse by Serbs,  
have streamed into Macedonia in the past three days, said Ron 
Redmond, spokesman for the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees. It 
is the biggest influx since early May. 
</P>
<P>
	Some reports Monday suggested that more than 150,000 people  
could flee Kosovo soon, but Redmond said it was impossible to tell 
how many were on the way. Aid officials have spoken of an apparent 
new push by Serbs to clear ethnic Albanians from the province. 
</P>
<P>
	Redmond said the UNHCR special envoy to the Balkans, Dennis  
McNamara, was negotiating with the government to expand some 
existing camps and possibly open two more. 
</P>
<P>
	A senior Western diplomat, speaking on condition of anonymity,  
said two sites that could accommodate about 16,000 refugees had 
already been chosen in western Macedonia. 
</P>
<P>
	Redmond said the United Nations also hopes to boost the number  
of refugees sent on to other countries from about 1,700 a day to 
2,500 daily within the next 10 days. 
</P>
<P>
	Macedonia, a former Yugoslav republic of 2.1 million people, now  
is the temporary home to nearly 247,000 refugees. The population of 
Macedonia is primarily Slavic, with ethnic Albanians making up 
about a third, and the government fears a possible demographic 
upheaval. 
</P>
<P>
	There currently are eight refugee camps in Macedonia holding  
about 96,000 people. The rest are staying mainly in private homes. 
</P>
<P>
	The government has at times sought to stanch the flow of  
refugees by closing the border. Aid officials were infuriated 
Monday after an abortive attempt by the government to bus several 
hundred new arrivals to Albania in the middle of the night. 
</P>
<P>
	Though Albania is a willing host, few refugees in Macedonia want  
to go there. A spokesman at UNHCR headquarters in Geneva, Kris 
Janowski, said only about 200 had volunteered. 
</P>
<P>
	``We hope to be able to somehow continue walking this tightrope  
between keeping the Macedonian government on board and at the same 
time ensuring that whatever happens is voluntary,'' Janowski said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to keep the border open,'' he added. ``If that border  
becomes closed, then those desperate people will rot in Kosovo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the 8,800 people who arrived in Macedonia on Monday were  
from the Kosovo capital of Pristina. They described a broken city, 
where paramilitary police wearing black masks ruled streets emptied 
of the ethnic Albanian residents who once dominated a thriving 
society of shops and cafes. 
</P>
<P>
	Fearing attacks from nearby Serb forces, NATO began relocating  
30,000 refugees today from Albania's northern border to safer camps 
deeper inside the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
