<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Ventures Into Bush Territory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EDINBURG, Texas (AP) -- Venturing into George W. Bush territory,  
Vice President Al Gore was ``very effective,'' but his boss was 
``masterful.'' That's the assessment of one who has worked with 
both. 
</P>
<P>
	Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo, son of a former New York  
governor famous for his oratorical power, was asked to explain why 
Gore received a more muted reception than President Clinton from 
the same audience. 
</P>
<P>
	``The president is a masterful communicator. Of historic  
proportions,'' Cuomo said. ``I think the vice president is a very 
effective communicator. Different style from the president, but 
every person has their own style. It doesn't matter if it's 
different. It's whether or not it's effective. And I think there's 
no question that he was effective today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, en route to a Florida vacation, stopped by an  
empowerment zone conference that Gore was hosting, an annual event 
that also allowed Gore to test the political climate in Texas, a 
stronghold for its governor and Republican presidential candidate 
Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the second joint Clinton-Gore appearance since Clinton  
told a reporter last week that Gore's campaign for the Democratic 
nomination was improving but Gore needed to loosen up a bit. Last 
Friday, the president and vice president were together at a gun 
legislation strategy meeting with Democratic lawmakers at the White 
House. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tuesday's speech, Clinton praised Gore effusively, saying he  
responded enthusiastically to Clinton's request to lead the push 
for creating empowerment zones in poor communities. He also 
credited Gore with helping spark an economic rebirth in urban 
America. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a challenge he embraced passionately,'' Clinton said.  
``I am profoundly grateful to him for proving that this is an idea 
whose time had come.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As the crowd cheered, Clinton then turned the podium over to  
Gore, who wasted no time in telling the crowd, ``I may be from 
Tennessee, but I feel right at home here today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore announced $32 million in urban brownfields grants, and  
referred to Martin Luther King Jr.'s dream and his call for a 
``beloved community.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Over the past seven years, we've come closer to realizing that  
dream,'' Gore said. Referring to the dragging death of James Byrd 
Jr., he also said, ``As long as a man can be dragged to his death 
from the back of a truck just because of the color of his skin, the 
dream is not yet fulfilled.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Gore's remarks lacked fire, and the audience didn't respond.  
At one point, Clinton propped his hand in his chin and listened 
intently, a serious expression on his face. At the end, he 
applauded Gore vigorously and worked the crowd with Gore afterward. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
