<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Campaign Free of Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Top politicians, driven by the need to  
demonstrate credibility and control, have been urging their ardent 
followers to abstain from violence in the campaign for the crucial 
June 7 parliamentary election. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, it's working.  
</P>
<P>
	With the campaign in its seventh day Tuesday, there has been  
little of the violence that many have predicted. The concerns had 
sparked beefed-up security and led many ethnic Chinese -- who were 
targeted in previous unrest -- and expatriates to flee the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Riot police have dispersed stone-throwing mobs with warning  
shots, but there have been few injuries. Media who swarmed to a 
rock-throwing incident Tuesday found only a dispute between two 
neighborhood gangs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Before this, the world was a little bit pessimistic that the  
general election in Indonesia would go peacefully,'' National 
Election Commission Chairman Rudini said. ``Until now ... it has 
been good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The country has not remained entirely free of violence.  
</P>
<P>
	In North Sumatra on Tuesday at least 15 people were injured when  
police fired rubber bullets to disperse an anti-government protest 
by students and farmers, witnesses said. 
</P>
<P>
	About 1,500 people took part in the demonstration in Tanjung  
Marawa, demanding dissolution of the ruling Golkar Party and the 
end of the military's role in politics. 
</P>
<P>
	And in the troubled Indonesian province of Aceh, separatist  
rebels shot a physician and nurse to death Tuesday as they rode in 
a police truck to carry out post mortem examinations on the bodies 
of two men killed earlier this week by rebels. 
</P>
<P>
	But the level of violence related to the campaign is much lower  
than had been expected. 
</P>
<P>
	One analyst said the frontrunners have told their supporters to  
exercise restraint because peaceful campaigning will boost their 
chances at the polls. 
</P>
<P>
	``The leadership of the contesting parties is aware that it has  
to have a successful general election,'' said Harry Tjan of 
Jakarta's Center for Strategic and International Studies. ``That's 
why they put in a very hard effort to calm down their followers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Tjan said the risk of rioting remained, for example, if an  
attack on a political party's office spilled over into looting of 
nearby shops. 
</P>
<P>
	Mulya Lubis, a member of the national Election Supervisory  
Committee, said Tuesday that Golkar will get a ``strong warning'' 
for allegedly offering to pay people to attend its rallies and 
allowing its guards to carry sharp weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	Riot police fired warning shots Monday outside a Golkar branch  
office in Jakarta to disperse a crowd that claimed the party 
reneged on promises of free T-shirts and $6. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten of the 48 parties were allowed to hold rallies Tuesday. The  
green of the Muslim-based United Development Party, known as the 
PPP, dominated as about 10,000 supporters rode in long parades of 
overloaded trucks, buses and motorbikes along Jakarta's 
thoroughfares. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamzah Haz, who addressed one PPP rally, said he hopes the party  
will win in Jakarta, as it did in 1977 when it took more than 100 
seats in Parliament. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Suharto, only three parties were permitted to field  
candidates. One is the PPP, which agreed last week to form a loose 
coalition with two other major opposition groups to ensure Golkar 
does not return to power. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, a top Golkar official who has previously criticized  
President B.J. Habibie said the ruling party still could reconsider 
its nomination of him as its presidential candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	Marzuki Darusman was quoted in local newspapers Tuesday as  
saying a decision could depend on progress in a government probe 
into allegations that Suharto enriched himself during his 32-year 
autocratic rule. 
</P>
<P>
	Habibie was Suharto's hand-picked successor and has been unable  
to shake his image as a loyalist friend. The next president will be 
chosen by a special assembly comprising the new Parliament and 
hand-picked government appointees. 
</P>
<P>
	Golkar is languishing in the opinion polls and has been the  
target of vandalism. 
</P>
<P>
	Golkar maintains its support remains healthy outside Jakarta, a  
sprawling and polluted metropolis of 11 million people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
