<HEADLINE> Don King Joins N.C. College Board </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- Boxing promoter Don King, who was given an  
honorary degree from Shaw University last year, has been named to 
the school's governing board of trustees. 
</P>
<P>
	King joined the private black college's 40-member board May 7,  
university spokeswoman Regina Boone said Monday. Last year, King 
gave Shaw a $200,000 donation and promised millions more for a Don 
King Fitness Center. 
</P>
<P>
	Trustees and alumni acknowledged King's controversial past but  
applauded his humanitarian efforts, said university president 
Talbert O. Shaw, who shares the school's name by coincidence. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it weren't for redemption, none of us would have a  
chance,'' Shaw said. ``King has a good heart, believe it or not, 
and he really wants to help young people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement, King said he was honored by the decision.  
</P>
<P>
	King was convicted of murder, a charge later reduced to  
manslaughter; faced numerous lawsuits from boxers and their 
handlers; was acquitted on tax evasion charges in 1985; and was 
acquitted last year of insurance fraud in the second of two trials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
