<DOCNO> APW19990525.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 22:11:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ventura Story Flops in the Ratings / TV Ratings  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- In terms Jesse ``The Body'' Ventura can  
understand, his television story was body-slammed by Michael 
Landon, Cleopatra and Will Smith. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS, with the help of Landon and Susan Lucci's victory at the  
Daytime Emmy Awards on Friday, won last week's Nielsens prime-time 
ratings race over second-place NBC as the May ratings ``sweeps'' 
continued. 
</P>
<P>
	For the broadcast networks, Sunday nights are often the most  
competitive sweeps month battlegrounds. Sunday is usually the most 
popular night for TV viewing and the time for the networks' 
high-profile movies and mini-series. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS's Sunday movie, ``Michael Landon: The Father I Knew''  
narrowly beat ABC's critically-praised miniseries opener, 
``Cleopatra.'' Both were in the week's top 10. 
</P>
<P>
	Fox's showing of the Smith movie, ``Independence Day,'' came in  
third place Sunday night. But it was still the network's second 
most-watched program of the week behind ``Ally McBeal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NBC's TV movie on Ventura, the former pro wrestler and now  
Minnesota governor, was the big loser. It drew poor reviews and 
even worse ratings, a dismal 58th place for the week. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC can take some solace from the solid performance of its  
Thursday night lineup. The triumvirate of ``ER,'' ``Frasier'' and 
``Friends,'' in their season finales, was easily the week's three 
most-watched programs. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS's telecast of the Daytime Emmy awards was Friday's most  
popular program. Soap star Lucci climaxed that broadcast by winning 
her first best actress award after 18 defeats. 
</P>
<P>
	For the week, CBS had a 9.6 rating and 16 share, and NBC had a  
9.3 rating and 16 share. ABC was third at 7.3 and 12, while Fox had 
a 7.0 rating and 12 share. The WB had a 3.4 rating and 6 share, UPN 
had a 1.7 rating and 3 share and Pax TV was at 0.7 and 1. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC's ``Nightly News'' won the evening news competition with a  
7.4 rating and 17 share. ABC's ``World News Tonight'' was second 
with a 7.1 rating and 16 share, while the ``CBS Evening News'' had 
a 5.8 and 13. 
</P>
<P>
	A rating point represents 994,000 households, or 1 percent of  
the nation's estimated 99.4 million TV homes. The share is the 
percentage of in-use televisions tuned to a given show. 
</P>
<P>
	For the week of May 17-23, the top 10 shows, their networks and  
ratings were: ``ER,'' NBC, 22.1; ``Frasier,'' NBC, 18.1; 
``Friends,'' NBC, 17.0; ``CBS Tuesday Movie: Joan of Arc, Part 
Two,'' CBS, 12.9; ``Touched By an Angel,'' CBS, 12.6; ``CBS Sunday 
Movie: Michael Landon, the Father I Knew,'' CBS, 12.4; ``ABC 
Premiere Event: Cleopatra,'' ABC, 11.9; ``60 Minutes,'' CBS, 11.7; 
``Home Improvement'' special, ABC, 11.6; ``Ally McBeal,'' Fox, 
11.3; ``Law and Order,'' NBC, 11.3. 
</P>
</TEXT>
