<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 01:01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	China Rejects Allegations of Spying  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- China today rejected allegations that it  
bolstered its nuclear arsenal by pilfering U.S. military secrets, 
saying Beijing has never stolen classified material from any 
foreign country. China's Foreign Ministry had no immediate reaction 
to the allegations contained in a U.S. congressional report to be 
released later today. But a Defense Ministry official noted that 
Chinese leaders have repeatedly denied allegations of nuclear 
thefts. The report by a select House committee on Chinese espionage 
chaired by Rep. Christopher Cox said China stole secrets about 
seven major warheads in the U.S. nuclear arsenal as well as the 
neutron bomb. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Campaign Enters Third Month  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO's bombing campaign entered its  
third month today with missiles striking the abandoned Serb police 
headquarters in downtown Belgrade. In western Kosovo, fierce 
fighting was reported between rebels and the Yugoslav army. 
Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital, was down to its last 8 percent of 
water reserves today because of damaged pumping stations and a 
power outage, Serbian media reported. NATO planes had targeted 
power plants over the weekend, cutting electricity to water 
services. 

</P>
<P>
	39 Miners Killed in E.Ukraine Blast  
</P>
<P>
	KIEV, Ukraine (AP) -- Rescuers have recovered the bodies at least  
39 miners killed in an underground gas explosion, Ukrainian 
officials said today. Another 48 workers were hospitalized with 
injuries from yesterday's blast, including two miners in grave 
condition, said a spokeswoman at the State Work Safety Committee in 
Donetsk, a coal-rich area in eastern Ukraine. The methane gas blast 
occurred at a depth of about 4,125 feet in the Zasiadko mine, one 
of the largest in the Donetsk region and one of a few profitable 
mines in the former Soviet republic. 

</P>
<P>
	Barak's Plan Tough on Palestinians  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israel's new government will make the  
resumption of peace talks with Syria and the Palestinians a top 
priority but will not forge ahead at any price, a lawmaker close to 
Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak said today. Labor party legislator 
Shlomo Ben-Ami spoke a day after Barak asked potential coalition 
partners to accept a 10-point plan that ruled out a withdrawal from 
all of the West Bank and Gaza Strip and failed to mention peace 
talks with Syria and Lebanon. The plan forms the basis of coalition 
talks that entered their second day today. Barak has 45 days to 
form a government. 

</P>
<P>
	Frays in Alliance Drawing Attention  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Frays in the alliance are drawing attention,  
with Germany bringing its dissenting views on ground troops to the 
Clinton administration. Today's visit of Foreign Minister Joschka 
Fischer is the first in a series by allied leaders in which 
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will try to put the best face 
possible on NATO's degree of unity. Germany vehemently opposes any 
consideration of sending combat troops into the unresolved conflict 
-- an option the State Department said yesterday was open -- and is 
making a public point of errant targeting that embarrassed the 
allies and touched off a furor with China after its embassy in 
Belgrade was hit. 

</P>
<P>
	Attorney: NYC Cop To Plead Guilty  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A police officer accused of torturing a prisoner  
in a Brooklyn stationhouse will change his plea to guilty, his 
lawyer told a U.S. judge. ``We would like to enter a plea,'' 
attorney Marvyn Kornberg, lawyer for Justin Volpe, said in a 
transcript. A source connected with the prosecution said there was 
no agreement with Volpe on a recommended sentence. The case against 
four remaining officers was expected to proceed. The five were 
accused of mistreating a black Haitian immigrant. 

</P>
<P>
	Japan Stock Prices Close Lower  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks dropped today on renewed concern about  
Japan's debt-ridden banks. The Nikkei Stock Average shed 176.26 
points to close at 16,214.23. 

</P>
<P>
	Astros 5, Rockies 2  
</P>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Shane Reynolds pitched a nine-hitter for his  
first complete game of the season and the Houston Astros took 
advantage of Lenny Harris' Colorado-record three errors to beat the 
Rockies 5-2 last night. The Astros beat Brian Bohanon to improve to 
12-2 this season against left-handed starters. Bohanon pitched six 
innings, allowing five runs -- four earned -- and seven hits. 

</P>
<P>
	Twins 10, Mariners 5  
</P>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Ron Coomer homered twice and rookie Dan  
Perkins got his first major league win last night as the Minnesota 
Twins beat the Seattle Mariners 10-5 for their fourth straight 
victory. Ken Griffey Jr. hit his 17th homer -- a two-run shot in the 
ninth off Bob Wells -- for the Mariners. Griffey also had an RBI 
double to extend his hitting streak to a career-high 13 games. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS  
</P>
</TEXT>
