<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> British Airways Has Pre-Tax Loss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- British Airways PLC posted a pretax loss in the  
fourth quarter and a 61 percent decline in pretax earnings for the 
year due to weaker demand in Asia and fewer bookings for premium 
seats. 
</P>
<P>
	The company reported today it had a pretax loss of 85 million  
pounds, or $135 million, in the three months ended March 31 in 
contrast to a profit of 70 million pounds a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Quarterly revenue was 2.05 billion pounds, or $3.25 billion, up  
slightly from 2.02 billion pounds the previous year. 
</P>
<P>
	For the year, British Airways earned 225 million pounds, or $357  
million, down from 580 million pounds a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Annual operating profit fell 12 percent to 442 million pounds  
from 504 million pounds. But revenue increased 3 percent to 8.92 
billion pounds, or $14.16 billion, from 8.64 billion pounds a year 
earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Industry analysts and investors had anticipated the poor  
results. The company's shares rose almost 4 percent in afternoon 
trading. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a very simple story. There is more capacity in the market  
than there is demand,'' chief executive Bob Ayling said. 
</P>
<P>
	Over-capacity, particularly on transatlantic flights, was ``not  
likely to improve materially in the short-term,'' Ayling said. 
</P>
<P>
	Asia's lingering financial crisis squeezed profits, as did  
industry-wide fare discounting and a drop-off in business and 
first-class bookings. 
</P>
<P>
	Stiffer competition in the economy-priced market also ate away  
at BA's bottom line. In response to this challenge, BA launched its 
own economy airline brand, Go, last year. Ayling expressed 
satisfaction with Go's performance so far. 
</P>
<P>
	BA said a cost-cutting program had saved it 610 million pounds  
during the year. 
</P>
<P>
	The airline's strategy for recovery focuses on replacing its  
Boeing 747 planes with smaller 777 aircraft, which have fewer 
economy seats and more premium seats. By eliminating more of its 
discounted seats, the airline hopes to boost its profit on each 
ticket sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The airline plans for half its fleet to consist of the smaller  
777s by 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	BA also plans to market more aggressively to business  
passengers, introducing new products like flat beds in its premium 
Club class. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is the right strategy, but it is going to take a while for  
the benefits to come through in the financial figures,'' said 
Jeremy Batstone, head of research at NatWest stockbrokers. ``The 
company is not yet out of the woods.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ayling denied reports that BA might cut back on its domestic  
British flights but said the airline was reevaluating its shorter 
flights from London's Heathrow airport to destinations in 
continental Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
