<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that moved substantially or traded  
heavily Tuesday on the New York Stock Exchange, Nasdaq Stock 
Market, and American Stock Exchange. 

</P>
<P>
 *NYSE    	

</P>
<P>
 *McKesson HBOC Inc. fell 4 11/16 to 33 1/2    	
</P>
<P>
	The medical supplies distributor will revise downward its fiscal  
1999 earnings for a second time in two months. McKesson said the 
revision is due to accounting problems at HBO, which it recently 
acquired. 

</P>
<P>
 *First Union Corp. fell 4 5/16 to 45 5/8    	
</P>
<P>
	The nation's sixth-biggest banking company said its  
second-quarter profits will miss analysts' expectations, due 
primarily to the costs of acquiring CoreStates Financial Corp. 
First Union said its results for the fiscal year may also fall 
short of Wall Street estimates. 

</P>
<P>
 *TNP Enterprises rose 3 3/8 to 38 5/16    	
</P>
<P>
	The parent company of Texas-New Mexico Power Co. has agreed to  
be acquired by an investor group in a transaction valued at 
approximately $1 billion, including assumed debt. TNP will be 
privately held once the deal is completed. 

</P>
<P>
 *Promus Hotel Corp. fell 5 3/8 to 25 1/8    	
</P>
<P>
	Promus reduced its earnings estimates for 1999, citing weak  
market conditions and poor performance at its Red Lion hotels. Two 
brokerages lowered their ratings on Promus, which franchises or 
owns hotel chains including Doubletree, Embassy Suites and Hampton 
Inn. 

</P>
<P>
 *Belden Inc. rose 3 1/8 to 23 7/16    	
</P>
<P>
	The maker of specialty wires and cables will acquire privately  
held Cable Systems Holding Co. for $180 million in cash. Belden 
said the deal should add slightly to 1999 earnings and 
significantly to 2000 earnings. 

</P>
<P>
 *Smtek International fell 1 5/8 to 5 7/8    	
</P>
<P>
	Smtek, which provides electronics-manufacturing services to  
original equipment manufacturers, completed a reverse 1-for-20 
split of its stock. 

</P>
<P>
 *NASDAQ   	

</P>
<P>
 *Lycos fell 1 1/4 to 96 1/2    	
</P>
<P>
	Lycos ended lower amid a major selloff of Internet stocks, but  
rose for much of the session. Credit Suisse First Boston raised its 
rating on Lycos to ``buy'' from ``hold.'' Also, Lycos was added to 
the Nasdaq 100 index, which lists the largest nonfinancial domestic 
companies traded on the Nasdaq National Market. 

</P>
<P>
 *barnesandnoble.com priced at 18, rose to 22 15/16    	
</P>
<P>
	The online wing of bookseller Barnes &AMP; Noble raised about $421.6  
million in its initial public offering. The company plans to use 
proceeds for expansion, including new computer and distribution 
systems. 

</P>
<P>
 *SpeedUs.com rose 2 7/8 to 6 5/8    	
</P>
<P>
	The Internet service provider is about to begin offering  
full-screen motion video along with its online service. SpeedUs.com 
is now working with content providers to develop programming. 

</P>
<P>
 *Evans Systems fell 4 7/8 to 26 1/2    	
</P>
<P>
	Evans posted a second-quarter operating loss of 16 cents per  
share, compared with a loss of 2 cents per share in last year's 
second quarter. The company provides electronic commerce marketing 
and advertising to convenience stores. 



</P>
