<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Panel Shifts Defense Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate Appropriations Committee voted  
Tuesday to shift $3.1 billion from defense to domestic programs as 
they struggled to write spending bills that honor stringent limits 
required by Congress' budget. 
</P>
<P>
	As they did, a conservative rebellion against Republican leaders  
slowed House debate to a crawl on a $61 billion measure financing 
agriculture and food programs. The first spending bill of the year 
to reach the full House, it became the target of repeated attempts 
at cutting. The assault was led by Rep. Tom Coburn, R-Okla., who 
said GOP leaders were on a course to ignore spending limits. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a leadership issue that we need to deal with,'' Rep.  
Steve Largent, R-Okla., told his colleagues. ``And I need to tell 
you, this was a last resort to come to the House floor, because we 
hit dead end after dead end in trying to carry on this family 
discussion inside our own house.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The House debated the bill for nearly nine hours before quitting  
for the evening. Only one of the six amendments conservatives 
offered was approved. It would cut the Agriculture Department's 
chief information officer's budget by $500,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Things were less chaotic on the Senate side of the Capitol, but  
the budget pressures were just as knotty. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate Appropriations Committee voted 24-3 to divide $536  
billion among its 13 annual spending bills for federal agencies for 
fiscal 2000, which begins Oct. 1. The only opponents were three 
Democrats: Richard Durbin of Illinois, Dianne Feinstein of 
California and Byron Dorgan of North Dakota. 
</P>
<P>
	Like an outline approved last week by the House Appropriations  
Committee, the Senate plan would leave bills covering education, 
environment and other domestic programs about $24 billion below 
this year's levels and more than $30 billion below what President 
Clinton requested. 
</P>
<P>
	To begin bridging that gap, the Senate panel voted by voice to  
set aside $3.1 billion approved in earlier bills for defense 
programs, eventually to use the money for domestic spending bills 
instead. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to go step by step by step across each little  
puddle,'' said Senate Appropriations Committee Chairman Ted 
Stevens, R-Alaska. But Stevens conceded his panel remained billions 
of dollars short of what it would need for its spending bills this 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Stevens said the $3.1 billion came from unspent allocations and  
from money approved in advance this year for fiscal 2000 programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked why Republicans had put more defense money than Clinton  
requested into a recent $15 billion emergency measure for Kosovo, 
knowing earlier defense funds were unspent, Stevens said, ``because 
we had this in mind,'' the shift of defense spending to domestic 
programs. ``I do think beyond the next job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate and House plans are designed to live within spending  
limits imposed by the GOP-written budget Congress approved this 
year. At GOP leaders' insistence, that budget honored spending 
reductions promised by the 1997 budget-balancing deal between 
Clinton and Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Because spending is limited so severely, most lawmakers believe  
it will take negotiations between themselves and the White House 
before some of the measures will be enacted this fall. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the Senate Appropriations Committee approved a $267.6  
billion measure for the Pentagon, $4.3 billion more than Clinton 
wanted. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Appropriations subcommittees approved two spending  
bills: a $21.2 billion measure for energy and water projects, and a 
$48.9 billion transportation bill. In each case, lawmakers grumbled 
they did not have enough money. 
</P>
<P>
	The energy and water bill would spend $100 million less in the  
fiscal year starting Oct. 1 than this year and $400 million less 
than Clinton wanted. The transportation measure would spend $1.6 
billion more than this year, but that's $1.3 billion less than 
Clinton proposed. 
</P>
<P>
	Amtrak, the nation's passenger railroad, would get $571 million,  
$38 million less than this year. Construction on Army Corps of 
Engineers water projects would get $1.1 billion, a cut of $318 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	The transportation measure also places new requirements on how  
airlines treat passengers, said subcommittee Chairman Richard 
Shelby, R-Ala. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would require an airline that knows a flight's arrival  
will be delayed to notify passengers before they board the plane. 
Airlines advertising bargain fares would have to specify the 
numbers of seats available at that rate. And passengers who don't 
use a portion of a ticket could not be penalized. 
</P>
<P>
	The House agriculture bill was $500 million less than Clinton  
requested. Rep. Joe Skeen, R-N.M., chairman of the Appropriations 
agriculture subcommittee, said it was the best that could be done 
under a tight budget, but the bill drew fire from both sides. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration said in a statement the measure was  
``simply inadequate to make the necessary investments our citizens 
need and expect.'' It urged the House to increase spending for food 
safety, child nutrition, seafood inspection, conservation and 
agricultural research. 
</P>
<P>
	On the other side, conservatives said the measure would set  
Congress on course to violate spending caps. They said the extra 
spending would have to come out of Social Security's surplus, 
something both parties say they want to avoid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990525.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 13:32:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Soccer: It's United Vs. Bayern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BARCELONA, Spain (AP) -- Two of the biggest clubs in European  
soccer end their long waits Wednesday for another shot at the 
continent's most prestigious prize. 
</P>
<P>
	When Manchester United and Bayern Munich meet in the Champions  
Cup final at Camp Nou stadium, each will be chasing a rare triple -- 
and the one victory it really wants. 
</P>
<P>
	``These are absolutely the two top teams in Europe right now,''  
Bayern Munich midfielder Stefan Effenberg said. ``But only if we 
win Wednesday we can call ourselves true champions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Manchester United last won the cup in 1968, with a lineup that  
included George Best and Bobby Charlton. Charlton scored twice, 
Best and Brian Kidd added one goal apiece, and United beat Benfica 
Lisbon 4-1 in overtime. 
</P>
<P>
	Bayern's 1-0 win over St. Etienne in 1976 was its third  
Champions Cup win in a row and the last major trophy won by Franz 
Beckenbauer, Gerd Mueller &AMP; Co. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither club won its national title last season, but qualified  
for the expanded Champions League. If they were below par last 
season, the two European powers have been outstanding this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Both have won their league titles, and Manchester United added  
the Football Association Cup to move within one victory of becoming 
the first English club to win all three in the same season. 
</P>
<P>
	It also would be the first English club since Liverpool in 1984  
to win the Champions Cup. English clubs were excluded form European 
cup tournaments after deadly riots between Liverpool and Juventus 
fans at the 1985 cup final in Belgium. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's significant,'' Manchester manager Alex Ferguson said.  
``The English teams in the 1980s were fantastic and you could say 
they dominated the competition, really. I think we've progressed to 
that level and we're as good as any English team that has been here 
before. So that must give us a great chance to change the 
pattern.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bayern is one step behind United in the triple crown chase -- it  
still has to play the German Cup final June 12. 
</P>
<P>
	United has not lost in 32 games and is averaging 3.05 goals a  
game, getting sparkling play from star wingers David Beckham and 
Ryan Giggs and strikers Dwight Yorke and Andy Cole. 
</P>
<P>
	By scoring 27 goals en route to the final, United is the  
highest-scoring finalist since the Champions League began seven 
years ago. Bayern has been almost as impressive domestically. 
</P>
<P>
	The two teams met twice in group matches and both ended in ties  
-- 2-2 in Munich and 1-1 in Manchester. 
</P>
<P>
	When asked what will decide Wednesday's game, Bayern goalkeeper  
Oliver Kahn replied: ``Luck and only luck.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bayern arrived in Barcelona on Tuesday, while United settled  
into the seaside resort of Sitges just outside the Catalan capital 
after arriving Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Camp Nou has been sold out for the final with 90,000 fans, each  
team officially receiving 30,000 tickets each. 
</P>
<P>
	Both teams are missing stars. Manchester will be without  
suspended captain Roy Keane and midfielder Paul Scholes, while 
Bayern is without injured Bixente Lizarazu and striker Giovane 
Elber. 
</P>
<P>
	There are some intriguing matchups, like the duel between  
Manchester's Jaap Stam, the most expensive defender in the world, 
and Bayern's burly striker, Carsten Jancker. 
</P>
<P>
	UEFA, European soccer's ruling body, said 42 flights bringing  
fans from England and nine flights from Germany were expected at 
Barcelona's El Prat airport. Fans also flew into airports at Girona 
and Reus. 
</P>
<P>
	As they began arriving, UEFA warned that forged tickets were  
being circulated in Barcelona and would be confiscated at the 
stadium gates. 
</P>
<P>
	Fearing crown problems, Spanish authorities said 6,000 police  
officers would be used to maintain security for the final. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
