<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 21:41:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> `Mom-and-Pop' Motels a Dying Breed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRENTWOOD, Tenn. (AP) -- Travelers Rest Inn looks like it's  
caught in a time warp. 
</P>
<P>
	The 36-room, bracket-shaped motel with its quaint ambiance and  
antique decor hasn't changed much since it opened 45 years ago, but 
everything around it has. 
</P>
<P>
	The sleepy two-lane road in front has been replaced by a  
traffic-clogged five-lane highway. The farm behind where 
Clydesdales were raised now is an office park with gleaming new 
buildings. 
</P>
<P>
	And all around it are restaurants, banks, gas stations and other  
businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	The motel industry has changed almost as much as Travelers  
Rest's surroundings. Family-owned motels like Travelers Rest -- 
those places where baby boomers stopped on long car trips with 
their parents -- are dying off, replaced by chains that can offer 
more modern conveniences. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're one of the last mom-and-pop motels left,'' said Gina  
Delboy, who took over management of Travelers Rest with her 
husband, Jan, after her father retired. Mrs. Delboy's brother, Alex 
Noble, is part-owner. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike many modern chain motels, Travelers Rest doesn't offer  
room service, free movies or complimentary breakfast. 
</P>
<P>
	What it does offer is rooms with bed posts and easy chairs  
reminiscent of a grandmother's bedroom; dark-wood rocking chairs 
out front offering weary motorists a reprieve from their car seats; 
and doors that open with keys, not plastic cards. 
</P>
<P>
	Sharon Erbe of Naples, Fla., stays at Travelers Rest every time  
she visits Nashville. 
</P>
<P>
	``For me, it's the nostalgia,'' Erbe says. ``You go to Opryland  
(Hotel), and everything's fake. They're trying to achieve what this 
has.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Terry Howe of Cincinnati recently spent three nights at  
Travelers Rest while in town on business. He chose it because it 
has ``a little more charm'' than chain motels. 
</P>
<P>
	The first motels were less charming. In fact, they weren't  
motels at all; they were campsites that sprang up along roads with 
the advent of the automobile around the turn of the century. 
</P>
<P>
	For travelers who didn't want to march across the lobby of a  
hotel in their road-worn clothes, camping in a farmer's field or on 
a lake front was a popular alternative. 
</P>
<P>
	``(Traveling) was a great adventure for people, and camping was  
part of that adventure,'' said Jefferson Rogers, coauthor of the 
book ``The Motel in America'' and assistant professor of geography 
at the University of Tennessee-Martin. 
</P>
<P>
	These campers became known as ``tin-can'' tourists for the trash  
they left behind, and eventually municipalities began cracking down 
on them. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1930s, cabins started sprouting along highways. Typical  
of the time was the U-Smile Cabin Camp in Kansas City. Guests paid 
$1 a night for a cabin and 25 cents more for a mattress. Blankets, 
sheets and pillows were 50 cents more. 
</P>
<P>
	Eventually, places like U-Smile added laundry rooms. Gas  
stations and restaurants were built nearby ``and we start seeing 
the development of roadside businesses on the outskirts of town,'' 
Rogers said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the early 1940s, cabins were replaced with cottages equipped  
with car ports. Seeking to maximize profits, owners later replaced 
car ports with more rooms and the ``motor hotel'' -- later shortened 
to ``motel'' -- was born. 
</P>
<P>
	Warren Belasco, professor of American studies at the University  
of Maryland-Baltimore County and author of ``Americans on the 
Road,'' said the motel became as integral a part of a trip as 
reaching the destination. 
</P>
<P>
	``Motels were the places where you found the latest  
conveniences,'' Belasco said. ``For many people, it was the first 
place they may have encountered a shower. In more recent years, 
things like cable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As the years went by and travelers demanded more amenities, the  
line between hotels and motels blurred. Chains emerged, promising 
guests the same service in the same surroundings whether they were 
in Portland, Maine, or Portland, Ore. 
</P>
<P>
	While these changes were occurring, Travelers Rest stayed the  
same. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Delboy's parents, Glenn and Iva Lee Noble, opened the motel  
when she was a senior in high school. It had 12 rooms that went for 
$4 to $6 a night. 
</P>
<P>
	The motel has tripled in size since then. Prices now range from  
$42 to $52 a night. 
</P>
<P>
	Motels like Travelers Rest face an uphill battle to stay in  
business as guests continue demanding more perks. A family-owned 
motel across the street from Travelers rest went out of business 
several years ago, and a Holiday Inn and Hampton Inn have been 
built nearby. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Travelers Rest endures, and the Delboys have no plans to  
sell or change. They believe they offer travelers something the 
chains can't -- a family atmosphere. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was born and raised on this corner,'' Delboy says. ``We have  
a lot of people who've been coming back for years. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been here a long time, and we treat them like family.''  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
