<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Mostly Higher / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bonds were mostly higher Tuesday in a second day  
of quiet trading amid steep downturn by stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose 5/32  
point, or 1.56 cents per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which 
moves in the opposite direction, fell to 5.74 percent from late 
Monday's 5.76 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices of short-term Treasuries ranged from unchanged to a loss  
of 1/32 point, and intermediate maturities ranged from unchanged to 
3/32 point higher, reported Bridge Telerate. 
</P>
<P>
	Bonds struggled early on in the session as stocks showed signs  
of a rebound from Monday's heavy selling, which sliced about 175 
points off the Dow Jones industrial average. 
</P>
<P>
	But by midafternoon on Tuesday, stocks turned lower, leaving the  
Dow another 123 points lower and sending money in search of safe 
harbors such as bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading Tuesday, yields on three-month Treasury bills  
rose to 4.62 percent from late Monday's 4.61 percent, while the 
discount rose 0.01 percentage point to 4.50 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Six-month yields rose to 4.77 percent as the discount rose 0.02  
percentage point to 4.59 percent. One-year yields rose to 4.86 
percent from late Monday's 4.82 percent, while the discount was 
unchanged at 4.62 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, rose to 4.81 percent from late Monday's 4.69 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell 5/32 point to 122 3/32. The average 
yield to maturity was rose to 5.36 percent from late Monday's 5.35 
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
