<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Weather Improves for Shuttle Launch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- The weather is looking better for  
Thursday's launch of space shuttle Discovery. 
</P>
<P>
	NASA issued a forecast today calling for 80 percent acceptable  
conditions for the 6:48 a.m. liftoff. Previous forecasts indicated 
a greater chance of fog. 
</P>
<P>
	The countdown was proceeding well for the year's first space  
shuttle flight, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Discovery is loaded with 1 1/2 tons of equipment for the new  
international space station. The seven-member crew will unload the 
gear, make repairs to the station and, during a spacewalk, attach 
cranes and tools to the outside of the station. 
</P>
<P>
	Five of the astronauts are U.S. citizens. One is Russian and the  
other is Canadian. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
