<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> More Than 136,000 Saturns Recalled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPRING HILL, Tenn. (AP) -- Saturn Corp. is recalling 136,300 cars  
because their seat backs can recline or collapse suddenly, which 
has caused at least one driver to crash. 
</P>
<P>
	No one was killed, but at least two people reported injuries  
because of the faulty seat backs, spokesman Bill Betts said 
Tuesday. He had no further details. 
</P>
<P>
	The gear teeth on the reclining mechanisms of driver and front  
passenger seats in 1994 and 1995 models are to blame, according to 
the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration. 
</P>
<P>
	``If this happens while the vehicle is being driven it could  
cause a loss of control, increasing the risk of a crash,'' 
according to a NHTSA report. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 123 Saturn customers said the seat reclined or collapsed  
after the car was rear-ended by another vehicle, according to 
NHTSA, which spent a year investigating the problem. 
</P>
<P>
	An NHTSA spokesman said he knew nothing more than what was in  
the report. 
</P>
<P>
	Betts said the company discovered the problem by examining  
computer data on warranty work for customers, and that it was the 
seat supplier's fault. 
</P>
<P>
	The seats were provided by Hyperion Corp. of Lawrenceburg, which  
fixed the problem in later models and has supplied all of Saturn's 
seats since the Spring Hill plant began operating in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	Hyperion officials did not immediately return phone calls.  
</P>
<P>
	Betts said Saturn began notifying owners of the recall in March,  
but they haven't all brought their cars to dealerships to be fixed, 
a process that takes about two hours. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
