<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 23:21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rookies Must Learn in Indy 500 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The Indy Racing League is succeeding in its  
plan to bring young drivers into the sport. 
</P>
<P>
	Including the four who will take the green flag on Sunday, there  
have been 42 first-year starters at Indianapolis since the IRL took 
over in 1996, the largest group of rookies in any four-year span 
since 57 newcomers were in the lineup from 1929-32. 
</P>
<P>
	But unlike the 1970s, '80s and even the early 90s, when drivers  
such as A.J. Foyt, Johnny Rutherford, Al Unser Sr., Gordon 
Johncock, Mario Andretti and Rick Mears raced year after year, even 
decade after decade, experience is at a premium. 
</P>
<P>
	``With this bunch of young kids that we have coming on ... they  
grew up driving sprint cars and midgets,'' said Rodger Ward, who 40 
years ago earned the first of his two Indy 500 victories. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can tell you this, that when you learn how to drive a race  
car, coming here and going this fast is a little bit different, but 
the training you get in a midget and sprint car and perhaps in a 
Silver Crown car is really the kind of experience that makes you 
into a damn good race driver,'' said Ward, 78, the oldest living 
former winner. 
</P>
<P>
	Seven years ago, the Indy lineup had a record 260 driver-years  
of experience. Two years ago, after the boycott of many veteran 
Championship Auto Racing Teams drivers and the retirement of most 
of the old guard, the starters had a combined 70 years of previous 
starts at Indy, the fewest in modern Speedway history. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides pole-winner Arie Luyendyk and Roberto Guerrero, each  
making his 15th start; Raul Boesel, in the race for the 11th time; 
Eddie Cheever, making his 10th start; and Scott Goodyear, his 
ninth, no other driver this year has more than four previous 
starts. 
</P>
<P>
	``The new guys have all got talent from other arenas, and they  
come from the same place we came from,'' Rutherford said of the 
short-track background of many of today's Indy drivers. ``We all 
did the same bull-ring racing before, and I think it's just a 
mindset.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No rookie has won at Indianapolis since Graham Hill in 1966.  
Guerrero in 1984, Jacques Villeneuve in 1994 and Christian 
Fittipaldi in 1995 finished second; the top rookie each of the past 
three years -- Richie Hearn, Jeff Ward and Steve Knapp -- finished 
third. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Knapp, Robby Unser, Andy Michner and J.J. Yeley all  
finished among the Top 10, the most since five rookies were among 
the Top 10 in 1965. 
</P>
<P>
	Even before Speedway president Tony George founded the IRL,  
which prompted the CART boycott, rookies were showing significant 
success at Indianapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	After Donnie Allison in 1970, the first rookie to drive the full  
500 miles was Nigel Mansell in 1993. Villeneuve then did it in 
1994, Fittipaldi and Eliseo Salazar matched the feat in 1995, Hearn 
did it in 1996, and Ward and Knapp did it in 1997 and 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	A big reason for the rookies' success has been their better  
preparation before practice even begins. The Speedway started the 
annual Rookie Orientation Program in the early '80s. It was 
optional at first, then mandatory. No driver who hopes to qualify 
for the 500 can afford to pass it up. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had all the rookies here in April and they went through  
their tests without the pressure of a lot of cars on the track,'' 
Rutherford said. ``They had a chance to run their tests, get 
through that, get some speed, have a couple of days to run on their 
own and experiment and be with other cars on the track.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Once that's out of the way, the newcomers can focus on  
qualifying and the race. 
</P>
<P>
	``We tested previously twice, but this was a good step in the  
progression,'' said John Hollansworth Jr., the fastest rookie 
qualifier, who will start 12th, on the outside of the fourth row. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's incredible,'' said Robby McGehee, who will start 27th, on  
the outside of Row 9. ``I'm at a famous track and a famous race. 
It's been a childhood dream. What more could I say?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rookie Jeret Schroeder qualified 21st for a start on the outside  
of Row 7. Wim Eyckmans, driving for owner-teammate Cheever, was the 
slowest qualifier and will start from the middle of Row 10. 
</P>
<P>
	``Eddie's experience has helped me quite a lot,'' the rookie  
from Belgium said. ``He told me to drive like I always do, and do 
what you have to, to qualify. Mentally, it's really hard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But, as Cheever said, ``The most important thing about the 500  
is to be in it.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
