<DOCNO> APW19990525.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 16:32:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NFL Owners Approve Redskins Sale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The price was $800 million, the highest for a  
franchise in sports history. A heavy tab for a 34-year-old lifelong 
Washington Redskins fans. 
</P>
<P>
	But Daniel Snyder, a communications mogul and college dropout,  
finally got what he wanted Tuesday -- ownership of one of the 
league's premier teams. 
</P>
<P>
	``Wow!'' exulted Snyder after receiving unanimous approval from  
NFL club owners. ``It's been an unbelievable journey.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a league long ruled by old money, he becomes the youngest  
among the league's current owners. 
</P>
<P>
	The 31 owners accepted his record bid in the only action taken  
at the start of two days of meetings. 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty-four votes were needed to approve the sale, which  
includes the new Jack Kent Cooke Stadium. Approval was widely 
expected following last week's endorsement by the NFL's finance 
committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The owners also discussed the situation in Los Angeles, which  
lost its two NFL teams after the 1994 season. Two ownership groups 
are jockeying for the franchise, which the NFL hopes to have ready 
for the 2002 season. 
</P>
<P>
	The debate concerning Los Angeles involves parking lots. One of  
the plans put forward Tuesday included a garage at the renovated 
Coliseum that would cost more than $200 million by itself. 
</P>
<P>
	Snyder had been a junior partner to Howard Milstein in a  
previous bid to buy the team from the trustees of the late Jack 
Kent Cooke. 
</P>
<P>
	When Milstein pulled out after it became clear he couldn't win  
support from other owners, Snyder went his own way. He brought in 
Fred Drasner and Mort Zuckerman, co-owners of the Daily News in New 
York. 
</P>
<P>
	Snyder's bid was the same as Milstein's. But he backed it with a  
$300 million down payment that sold the rest of the owners. 
</P>
<P>
	The previous high price for a franchise was the $550 million Al  
Lerner paid for the new Cleveland Browns, who will begin playing in 
September as the NFL's 31st team. 
</P>
<P>
	The Redskins sale has been a long-running soap opera since the  
team was put up for sale by the trustees of the estate of Jack Kent 
Cooke, who died in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Cooke's son, John, was one of the bidders when Milstein got the  
franchise. When Milstein dropped out, he sued John Cooke and 
general manager Charley Casserly. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has been a long goodbye,'' Cooke said in a statement.  
``As disappointing as it has been, it has also been very gratifying 
to hear how much my family has meant to the National Football 
League and Redskins fans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Snyder has said that for this season he will retain Casserly and  
coach Norv Turner. He also expects to hire a team president soon, 
but not necessarily someone from football, although one of those 
mentioned is former Miami coach Don Shula. 
</P>
<P>
	In Los Angeles, the NFL has decided the renovated Coliseum will  
be the venue of choice. Now parking -- always a vexing issue in the 
city -- figures into the discussion. The NFL insists 25,000 parking 
spaces be available. 
</P>
<P>
	One group, headed by Hollywood agent Michael Ovitz, presented a  
plan Tuesday for a parking garage with a park on top that could 
cost as much as $225 million. The project features a garage covered 
with trees, grass in front of luxury suites and a cooling system 
that would spray mist on sweltering fans. 
</P>
<P>
	It impressed commissioner Paul Tagliabue, who called it  
``exactly the kind of vision necessary to transform the venue in 
the interests of the city of Los Angeles.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But public money must cover some of the costs, and California  
politicians are not all that happy. 
</P>
<P>
	``With 2.5 million uninsured children and adults in this county,  
with 75,000 children in foster care ... with sidewalks that can't 
be repaired by the city? Give me a break,'' Los Angeles County 
Supervisor Zev Yaroslavsky said. 
</P>
<P>
	Added Assemblyman Roderick Wright of Los Angeles: ``Why should a  
lady in Fresno pay for parking spaces for the Coliseum?'' 
</P>
<P>
	The other group, led by developer Eli Broad, has a more modest  
plan. It would provide a 7,500-car garage plus space for more than 
17,000 other cars, using the adjacent campus of the University of 
Southern California and other existing space. 
</P>
<P>
	Los Angeles, which beat out Houston for the expansion team, has  
until Sept. 16 to present owners with a workable plan although that 
deadline is believed to be flexible if progress is shown. 
</P>
<P>
	The owners are to discuss the New England Patriots' decision to  
stay in the Boston area after withdrawing a commitment to Hartford, 
Conn. Massachusetts Gov. Paul Cellucci signed legislation Monday 
that will provide $70 million to help the Patriots build a new 
stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	The owners will also discuss stadium situations in Denver and  
Philadelphia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990525.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 16:01:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Petrie Named NBA Exec of the Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Geoff Petrie, Sacramento's vice  
president of basketball operations, was selected NBA Executive of 
the Year on Tuesday, capping a spectacular comeback year for him 
and the Kings. 
</P>
<P>
	The award, announced in New York by The Sporting News,  
recognized Petrie's key role in rebuilding a team which had not had 
a winning season since moving from Kansas City to Sacramento in 
1985. 
</P>
<P>
	Starting his fifth year with the Kings, Petrie made a series of  
trades and signings, some of them controversial, that resulted in 
four new starters playing for a new coach, Rick Adelman. 
</P>
<P>
	The NBA lockout meant an abbreviated training camp and season  
for the young team, and the start was rocky. The Kings' 
inconsistency and lapses often made them look like the 27-55 team 
of the previous season. 
</P>
<P>
	But Sacramento closed the regular season with 10 wins in their  
final 11 games for a 27-23 record. Then they came within one missed 
shot on the final buzzer of upsetting the Utah Jazz, the defending 
two-time Western Conference champion, in the fifth and final game 
of the opening round of the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Petrie received eight of a possible 33 votes from his fellow NBA  
executives and league representatives. Orlando's John Gabriel 
received seven votes, followed by Toronto's Glen Grunwald with five 
and Portland's Bob Whitsitt with four. 
</P>
<P>
	Petrie said the award was especially gratifying ``coming with  
the type of year we had ... the way it came together under such 
great uncertainty and much doubt. I'm really proud of everybody 
associated with the team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A lot of that doubt and uncertainty involved Petrie's own job.  
Earlier this year, as Petrie faced a scheduled mid-year change in 
team ownership and the expiration of his contract. At one point he 
reportedly was just hours away from resigning. 
</P>
<P>
	But Petrie signed a multiyear contract extension in January, and  
his team of strangers -- nine new players on the 12-man roster -- won 
national attention with a sometimes erratic but always exciting 
style. 
</P>
<P>
	Petrie's major accomplishments were trading for power forward  
Chris Webber, signing free agent center Vlade Divac and drafting 
point guard Jason Williams. 
</P>
<P>
	Almost as important were the free agent signings of guards  
Vernon Maxwell and Jon Barry and forward Scot Pollard and the 
recruitment and signing of guard Peja Stojakovic, a 1996 
first-round draft choice from Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	Only forwards Corliss Williamson and Lawrence Funderburke and  
guard Tariq Abdul-Wahad -- all draft choices during Petrie's 
five-year tenure -- returned from the 1997-98 squad. 
</P>
<P>
	``Geoff has done a terrific job in rebuilding the Sacramento  
Kings. A lot of hard work has started to pay off for the 
organization,'' said Kings chief executive officer Jim Thomas, who 
hired Petrie in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Gavin Maloof, whose family will assume control of the franchise  
from Thomas on July 1, said the honor was well deserved. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't say I was surprised,'' Maloof said from Las Vegas. ``I  
do know it's an honor for him individually and for the Kings 
organization to have a person of his quality. It's certainly a very 
prestigious award, and I'm happy for him because he works very hard 
and deserves it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Petrie, 51, shared the NBA Rookie of the Year award in 1971,  
when he played for the Portland Trail Blazers. His latest award 
makes him the first person to win both the NBA's rookie and 
executive honors. 
</P>
<P>
	Petrie played six years for the Trail Blazers. After his playing  
career was curtailed by injuries, he spent five years as a members 
of the Trail Blazers broadcast team and another four years in the 
team's front office before joining the Kings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
