<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Library Tax Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- A 1 cent sales tax increase, a small  
piece of which could have helped pay for the site for the Bill 
Clinton presidential library, was defeated by more than a 2-1 vote 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The increase would have funded $200 million in improvements to  
city streets, parks, and its zoo, and barely 4 percent of the money 
could have gone toward paying off the debt incurred buying land for 
the Clinton library. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents complained that voters were not told some of the money  
could go toward the library. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the people who have not liked the president all along.  
They dislike anybody associated with the library,'' said Skip 
Rutherford, a friend of Clinton. ``You're going to have those 
people who are going to criticize the Clintons, but this package is 
far broader than that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal included two taxes -- a 3/4-cent temporary tax to  
raise $150 million over five years and a 1/4-cent permanent tax to 
raise $9.3 million annually. The city now has a half-cent local tax 
rate, and state and county sales taxes push the figure to 6 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The results of Tuesday's vote on the 3/4-cent tax was 15,061 to  
6,891, or 69 percent to 31 percent. The 1/4-cent tax was voted down 
15,541 to 6,144, or 72 percent to 28 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Lynda Cooper said the ballot was confusing.  
</P>
<P>
	``The city will be sorry when they find out that most people  
couldn't understand it,'' said Ms. Cooper, 39. ``I'm sure people 
stayed away from voting because they didn't know what was going 
on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Clinton selected Little Rock as his library site in 1997,  
city officials scrambled to make good on a pledge to provide the 
land. They considered raising the city tax on hotels and 
restaurants, but settled on using $11.5 million from a bond issue 
that also benefits the city zoo and golf courses. 
</P>
<P>
	The city is in the process of buying the land. Private donations  
will construct the complex and the federal government will operate 
it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
