<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baseball Fires Curve at ESPN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The nasty feud continues between ESPN and Major  
League Baseball, with MLB countersuing the cable network over three 
late-season games that conflict with NFL telecasts. 
</P>
<P>
	ESPN sued MLB earlier this month after the sport terminated a  
regular-season contract with the cable network that was supposed to 
run through 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	MLB countersued Friday in papers filed in U.S. District Court in  
Manhattan. The judge received the papers Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	MLB is claiming it should be paid damages because the cable  
television network broke its contract when it decided three 
football games would draw much higher ratings than three baseball 
games. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, ESPN wanted to switch three Sunday baseball games to  
ESPN2 so it could show three NFL games instead. The two sides 
couldn't reach an agreement and the games were given back to local 
outlets. 
</P>
<P>
	``The NFL was and is unwilling to have its games telecast on  
ESPN2, even three games in September at the very start of its 
season,'' MLB said. 
</P>
<P>
	MLB said in court papers that ESPN deliberately broke its 1996  
contract ``solely to cut a deal that it viewed as promising and 
having a more positive impact on the network's pricing structure 
and the corporate bottom line.'' 
</P>
<P>
	MLB demanded unspecified damages, saying ESPN2, which is  
available in 64 million homes, to be inferior to ESPN, which is in 
76 million homes. 
</P>
<P>
	Dick Glover, ESPN executive vice president of programming, said  
Monday that the cable network did not violate the contract when it 
exercised its right to pre-empt three baseball games with football 
games because the football games were of significant viewer 
interest. 
</P>
<P>
	MLB said in its court papers that ESPN could not do so without  
MLB's written permission, which MLB did not grant. 
</P>
<P>
	Glover called the NFL the ``gold standard of viewer interest.''  
</P>
<P>
	He said baseball averaged a 2.5 rating for its Sunday night  
games last year, while football had a 7.3 rating for its first 
three Sunday night games. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel that we've been not only a good partner, but by far  
their best partner for 10 years and don't understand why they would 
look to terminate the relationship over three games out of 500 
hours,'' Glover said. ``If they won the suit, it would be terrible 
for baseball. ESPN being out of baseball would be terrible for 
baseball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Glover also said he believed MLB was trying to force ESPN to pay  
more money for a contract it had already negotiated. In its court 
papers, ESPN said MLB was asking for an additional $350 million for 
1999-2002 and a two-year extension at an annual threefold increase 
over the rights fee agreed to for 2002. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
