<HEADLINE> SLOC Shuffles Staffing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- The Salt Lake Organizing Committee on  
Tuesday announced the hiring of Judy Shoemaker to handle the 
marketing and promotion services for the 2002 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	The SLOC also announced the shifting of another official and the  
hiring of a third. 
</P>
<P>
	Shoemaker will be responsible in developing activities promoting  
the torch relay, mascot tour, education and youth sports, arts and 
culture program. 
</P>
<P>
	She developed the ``I Love This Game!'' campaign as vice  
president of marketing for NBA Properties, Inc. before leaving to 
start her own marketing company, then joining Robinson &AMP; Maites. 
</P>
<P>
	``Judy brings a wealth of experience in sports marketing,  
special events and strategic planning,'' said Mark Lewis, SLOC vice 
president of marketing and licensing. ``Her creativity and 
background in client services will be a tremendous asset to the 
organizing committee.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dianne Hesleph, who has been director of education since June 1,  
1998, was named director of training for the organizing committee. 
She will be responsible for developing and implementing training 
programs and materials for the SLOC staff, loaned employees, 
interns and volunteers. 
</P>
<P>
	Hesleph spent 15 years in the Granite School District before  
being hired by the SLOC, including seven years as principal of 
Granite High School. 
</P>
<P>
	She will be replaced by Dr. Judy Stanfield, a 32-year Granite  
District veteran. Her hiring takes effect June 27. Stanfield has 
been principal of Skyline High School since 1996, was named the 
district's administrator of the year for 1999 and recently won the 
Jon M. Huntsman Excellence in Education Award. 
</P>
<P>
	Stanfield will be responsible for 14 programs, ranging from  
school activities to classroom curriculum. 
</P>
<P>
	``The organizing committee feels fortunate to have someone with  
Judy's background and credentials to further develop these vital 
programs,'' said Shelley Thomas, vice president of communications 
and public affairs, which oversees the education programs. 
</P>
