<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 13:22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Harassment Ruling May Change Little </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The Supreme Court decision holding schools responsible for  
sexual harassment between students was so narrow that some legal 
experts say it may have little effect in the courts, and even less 
sway on America's playgrounds. 
</P>
<P>
	The 5-4 ruling Monday opens the door to lawsuits against school  
boards, but only if officials were deliberately indifferent to 
sexual harassment so severe and pervasive that it deprived a 
student of his or her right to an education. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a very high standard,'' said Catherine Fisk, a law  
professor at Loyola University in Los Angeles who has written 
extensively on sexual harassment. ``I don't think it is a big 
change in what most people thought the law was.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She added: ``I suspect that the usual kids being mean to other  
kids, pulling up girls' dresses or whatever, isn't going to meet 
the standard of pervasive and severe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling follows a Supreme Court decision last June that said  
schools could be sued under the anti-bias federal law known as 
Title IX for a teacher's sexual harassment of a pupil. The ruling 
Monday extends that to student-against-student harassment. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision stems from a Georgia case in which the mother of a  
fifth-grade girl named LaShonda Davis claimed that Monroe County 
school officials ignored her daughter's repeated complaints about a 
classmate who had allegedly groped and sexually threatened her. 
</P>
<P>
	The high court set a very high standard for holding school  
officials responsible, saying they had to have direct knowledge of 
the harassment and fail to act. 
</P>
<P>
	Some education officials said that is a narrower definition than  
Education Department guidelines issued in 1997. Under the 
guidelines, officials have a responsibility even if they had no 
knowledge of sexual harassment, but should have known. 
</P>
<P>
	``The court was quite clear that to be liable for damages it has  
to be pretty egregious. Basically, you knew about it and didn't do 
anything at all,'' said Stephen Yurek, general counsel for the 
National Association of Secondary School Principals. 
</P>
<P>
	Yurek said schools are already cracking down on sexually  
inappropriate behavior under the Education Department guidelines. 
</P>
<P>
	``Schools, particularly in this day and age, have to err on the  
side of safety and protecting the kid,'' he said. ``The days of 
`boys will be boys, girls will be girls' are gone, and schools have 
a responsibility for educating kids on having respect for others.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Houston, executive director of the American Association of  
School Administrators, which opposed the high court decision, said 
he worried the case could raise schools' legal costs and prompt 
officials to overreact to student misconduct. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm afraid that people may come down overly hard on kids for  
things that aren't actually sexual harassment,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Others said the case should prompt schools to adopt more  
counseling for students and training for teachers. 
</P>
<P>
	Peggy Stockdale, a psychology professor at Southern Illinois  
University in Carbondale and an expert on sexual harassment in the 
workplace, said the ruling puts school systems ``on notice that 
they should take this seriously.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But she said it will still be more difficult to sue a school  
than a company. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a difference. We are talking about kids, and teaching  
them lessons,'' Stockdale said. ``In the workplace people are 
adults and they should know better. But in school, it is a 
developmental process.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990525.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 09:31:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  MSG Chief Apologizes to Van Gundy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Jeff Van Gundy will remain in limbo for the  
foreseeable future. 
</P>
<P>
	The coach of the New York Knicks met with the president of  
Madison Square Garden on Monday and received an apology for being 
lied to about the team's meeting with former Bulls coach Phil 
Jackson. 
</P>
<P>
	But rather than put the issue completely to rest by assuring  
everyone that Van Gundy would remain as coach next season, team 
president Dave Checketts said no decisions will be made until the 
season ends. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not fair to make an evaluation on somebody or a judgment  
on what should happen in the organization based on one series, one 
shot or one win,'' Checketts said. ``He (Van Gundy) has agreed to 
that and he's comfortable with that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Van Gundy, however, was clearly uncomfortable with discussing  
the subject after the Knicks defeated the Atlanta Hawks 79-66 for a 
4-0 sweep of their second-round series. 
</P>
<P>
	It's not every day, after all, that one's boss comes into an  
underling's office and says he's sorry for lying to your face. 
</P>
<P>
	``He explained himself to me and I listened,'' Van Gundy said.  
``It's a non-issue to me. The only thing I was worried about was 
getting one more win, and now all I'm concerned with is trying to 
get back to the finals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For the better part of the day Sunday, Checketts denied having  
any contact with Jackson despite two newspaper reports saying they 
sat down together to gauge Jackson's interest in the job. 
</P>
<P>
	But late in the afternoon, while Game 3 was still being played,  
Checketts confessed the truth. He was lambasted in Monday's papers 
as a shiftless corporate snake in a building of backstabbers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I regret that I lied about it,'' Checketts said. ``We met for  
a couple of hours, and there were no offers exchanged. There was 
nothing that came out of the meeting other than getting acquainted 
with a guy who I felt was a tremendous option for us if we had not 
made the playoffs and needed a new direction. 
</P>
<P>
	``If anything, what I did is err on the side of protecting  
everyone. I had to do the job of finding out if I had an option 
like that,'' Checketts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Checketts, the president of Madison Square Garden, has been  
running the Knicks on a day-to-day basis since general manager 
Ernie Grunfeld was demoted in mid-April because of a rift between 
him and Van Gundy. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the unanswered questions surrounding the  
Checketts-Jackson meeting is who set it up. Checketts said he 
contacted Jackson through an intermediary, but he refused to say 
who it was. 
</P>
<P>
	Tony Wyche, a spokesman for presidential candidate Bill Bradley,  
said the former Knicks forward was not the emissary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990525.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 18:41:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Stocks Fall / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks tumbled at the open of trading  
Wednesday, hurt by declines on Wall Street and pessimism the 
stronger yen could erode profits at exporters. The dollar fell 
again against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 107.93 points,  
or 0.67 percent, to 16,086.81 in the first 30 minutes of trading. 
On Tuesday, the average lost 176.26 points, or 1.08 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 122.34 yen in early trading, down 0.38 yen  
from late Tuesday in Tokyo and also below its late New York level 
of 122.70 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of electronics and telecommunications companies were  
among the biggest decliners, with NEC Corp. and Nikon Corp. leading 
the fall. 
</P>
<P>
	Selling came as the technology-laden Nasdaq Composite index fell  
3 percent in the United States. The Dow Jones Industrial Average 
also fell, losing about 1.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The stronger yen was also seen driving up the prices of these  
companies' products overseas, eating into export earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank shares fell after the nation's top lenders announced record  
losses this week. The 15 largest banks said they spent $82 billion 
over the last year writing off failed loans left on their books 
from the speculative 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
exchange's first section was down 9.40 points, or 0.72 percent, to 
1,299.28. The TOPIX lost 8.83 points, or 0.67 percent, the day 
before. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar remained under selling pressure  
from domestic investors taking profits on recent gains. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, the dollar climbed to a seven-month high against the  
yen, rising above 124 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 129.76 yen, down  
from 130.35 yen late Tuesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond fell  
to 1.320 percent from Tuesday's finish of 1.355 percent, driving 
its price up to 100.70 yen from 100.39 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
