<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 18:21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cards' Osborne Out 2-3 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Often-injured St. Louis left-hander Donovan  
Osborne will be sidelined 2-3 months after undergoing arthroscopic 
surgery on his pitching shoulder Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's 2-3 months and then you don't know how long before he  
gets in pitching shape,'' general manager Walt Jocketty said. 
</P>
<P>
	``You don't know if he could help us at the end of the year or  
not,'' he said. ``We have to pretty much figure he won't be back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Frank Jobe performed the surgery in Los Angeles, repairing  
an arthritic joint in Osborne's shoulder. Osborne had 
reconstructive surgery on the shoulder in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Osborne, 29, was the Cardinals' opening day starter for the  
first time of his career. He went on the disabled list for the 
seventh time in seven major league seasons on May 7. 
</P>
<P>
	Osborne is 1-3 with a 5.52 ERA in six starts in the final season  
of a three-year, $12.75 million contract. He has missed much of the 
first two seasons because of a hernia, two groin injuries and a 
shoulder injury, totaling 14 starts in 1998 and 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Jobe gave Osborne a cortisone shot last week, but the pitcher  
told the team it had no effect. 
</P>
<P>
	``Originally what we were going to do was wait a month and see  
how it was, but it just wasn't getting any better,'' Jocketty said. 
</P>
<P>
	Osborne's injury means that Juan Acevedo, who began the year as  
the closer, likely will now be a full-time starter. Acevedo, who 
struggled as the closer, will make his third start Thursday against 
the Giants. 
</P>
<P>
	Jocketty said he's been frustrated in efforts to trade for  
another starter. He doesn't expect much to happen before the July 
31 trade deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	Down the road, the Cardinals may get right-hander Alan Benes  
back. Benes, who totaled 22 victories in 1996 and '97, has been 
sidelined since the middle of the '97 season with rotator cuff 
injuries, but has been throwing off a mound without pain. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's probably closer than Donovan,'' Jocketty said. ``He could  
be back, but you've got to remember you can't really count on him. 
If he comes back, it's a plus.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
