<DOCNO> APW19990525.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 05:42:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Panel Urged To Double President Pay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A House plan to double the president's  
$200,000 annual salary after President Clinton leaves office is 
overdue and can be sold to a skeptical public, former top aides to 
Democratic and Republican presidents are telling Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not a business of polling. This is a question of  
equity,'' Kenneth Duberstein, who was chief of staff to President 
Reagan, told a House subcommittee on Monday. ``I think the American 
people will in fact support a significant pay raise for the 
president of the United States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Duberstein was among seven top presidential assistants, joined  
by representatives of think tanks and experts on executive 
compensation, who testified to a House Government Reform 
subcommittee. Almost all supported current legislation to double 
the next president's salary, with many saying the increase should 
be even higher. 
</P>
<P>
	``The president's salary should reflect the importance the  
American people place on this job,'' said Thomas ``Mack'' McLarty 
III, who was Clinton's first chief of staff. 
</P>
<P>
	Language raising the salary to $400,000 for whomever succeeds  
Clinton in January 2001 was included in a $13.7 billion spending 
bill for the Treasury, White House and other agencies approved May 
14 by a House Appropriations subcommittee. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan has the support of House GOP leaders, said top  
Republican aides. It is also backed by the Clinton administration, 
which submitted a statement warning that failing to grant the 
increase would keep other senior federal salaries too low and make 
it hard for the government to attract talented people. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the Constitution, lawmakers may vote pay raises only for  
future presidents, not sitting ones. Republicans have been 
underlining that point because of Clinton's deep unpopularity 
within their party. 
</P>
<P>
	``This hearing is not about whether President Clinton should get  
a pay raise,'' said the subcommittee's chairman, Rep. Stephen Horn, 
R-Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	Also released at the hearing was a poll by the Pew Research  
Center for the People and the Press showing scant public support 
for increasing presidential pay. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey, taken earlier this month, showed that when told the  
last presidential pay raise was in 1969, 49 percent favored an 
increase for the next president. Support dropped to 41 percent when 
the question noted that the president currently receives $200,000 
plus housing and travel expenses. And only one in four said the 
president's pay should be increased by more than $20,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, most of the former presidential aides said the public  
would accept an increase to $400,000 once it learned all the 
reasons why it was needed. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the American people are ready to take this if it's  
given to them with factual data,'' said Alexander Haig, President 
Nixon's chief of staff. 
</P>
<P>
	The last presidential pay raise was granted in 1969, when it was  
doubled from $100,000. If the current $200,000 had been adjusted 
annually for inflation as measured by the consumer price index, it 
would now be $923,000, said Jane Weizmann, senior consultant for 
Watson Wyatt Worldwide, a human resources consulting firm. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Gary Ruskin, director of the Congressional Accountability  
Project, which is affiliated with consumer advocate Ralph Nader, 
argued that the president already earns more than 99 percent of 
Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	``Such a high presidential compensation package begins to look  
as if the president were taking advantage of the taxpayers,'' 
Ruskin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990525.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 09:41:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Criticizes Clinton on China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush today sharply  
criticized the Clinton administration over the theft of nuclear 
secrets by China, even though some of the espionage occurred while 
his own father was in the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, the front-runner for the Republican presidential  
nomination, said the congressional report calls into question the 
Clinton administration's China policies and response to the 
espionage. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the balance of power is going to shift as a result of  
this. I think it's going to accelerate China's emergence as a 
nuclear power. And the next president and presidents after that are 
going to have to deal with that,'' Bush said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Washington, the chairman of the congressional investigating  
committee said China has stolen classified information about every 
currently deployed nuclear weapon in the U.S. arsenal and it is 
``exceptionally likely'' that Chinese spying continues to this day. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush called for a congressional investigation into ``what went  
wrong and why.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Today's report also shines a glaring light on the current  
administration's failed policies toward China,' Bush said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Presented with detailed information about China's espionage,  
the administration apparently did not take it seriously, did not 
react promptly and is still trying to minimize the scope and extent 
of the damage done,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush acknowledged that the problem has been going on for years,  
including the time his father, George, was vice president and 
president. But he said he doesn't believe that gives Clinton an 
excuse. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's unfortunate that China has been stealing secrets during  
Carter, Reagan, Bush and Clinton. But there is only one 
administration that has been given the news; only one 
administration knew -- and that's the Clinton administration. The 
interesting question is when did they know? 
</P>
<P>
	``There are reports that the national security adviser knew in  
1996. Should I run and should be the president, I can assure you 
that if my national security adviser knew that secrets were being 
stolen, I'd want to know about it and I'd do something about it 
immediately.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the espionage allegations, Bush said he still believes  
China and the United States should be trading partners and that 
China should be admitted to the World Trade Organization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990525.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 10:41:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Quaranta Wins Tour of Italy Stage 11 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CESENATICO, Italy (AP) -- Ivan Quaranta outdueled sprint  
specialist Mario Cipollini in the stretch Tuesday for his second 
stage victory in the Tour of Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	Frenchman Laurent Jalabert increased his lead in the standings  
over defending champion Marco Pantani as the 22-stage race hit its 
halfway point. Jalabert picked up four bonus points for being in 
second place at the checkpoint 25 miles from the finish. 
</P>
<P>
	The 78-mile run ended in Cesenatico, the Adriatic coast city  
where Pantani was born. 
</P>
<P>
	Organizers added Cesenatico to the race's route this year to  
honor Pantani, who won both the Tour of Italy and Tour de France 
last summer. He tried but failed to cross the finish line first. 
</P>
<P>
	``Pantani wanted to get ahead of me, because he wanted to arrive  
at his home in the pink jersey. But I didn't let him, because it's 
important to me, too, to wear this jersey,'' Jalabert said of the 
jersey always worn by the overall leader. 
</P>
<P>
	Quaranta, who won the race's opening stage, beat Cipollini by  
half a bicycle length and crossed the finish line in the unofficial 
time of 2 hours, 53 minutes and 49 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	Cipollini was seeking to become the first rider to win  
consecutive stages this year. His victory Monday was the 27th Giro 
stage win of his career. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
