<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> California Cities Suing Gun Makers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A group of California cities and counties led  
by Los Angeles and San Francisco sued handgun makers Tuesday, 
hoping to force the weapons industry to pay for gun-related 
injuries and deaths. 
</P>
<P>
	Using state laws against public nuisances and unfair business  
practices, the lawsuits claim the industry's marketing practices 
allow guns to fall into the hands of criminals and children. 
</P>
<P>
	``They need to pay for the violence in this country,'' Los  
Angeles City Attorney James Hahn said. ``They need to pay for the 
bloodshed. They need to pay for the suffering.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Compton, West Hollywood, Sacramento, Berkeley, San Mateo County  
and Alameda County joined Los Angeles and San Francisco in the twin 
Superior Court actions. 
</P>
<P>
	The suits claim the industry floods areas with more guns than  
the legitimate market can absorb and doesn't place any controls on 
distributors or dealers to ensure the weapons don't fall into the 
wrong hands through illegal purchases or via ``straw buyers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gunmakers' contracts with distributors don't use background  
checks to ensure dealers are not lawbreakers, according to the 
suits. They also claim gunmakers ignore safer gun technology, such 
as devices that allow only the registered owner to fire the 
weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	One gun manufacturer said the suits' issues have failed legal  
tests in the past. 
</P>
<P>
	``These theories all been tried before and have all been shot  
down before,'' said Steve Sanetti, vice-president and general 
counsel of Sturm, Ruger &AMP; Co., the largest and only publicly traded 
gun manufacturer in the United States. ``They have a very tough 
time to try to make these cases withstand legal scrutiny. These are 
political lawsuits.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The claims in the California suits differ from other suits  
around the country in that they do not rely on product liability 
laws. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that's absolutely ridiculous,'' said Robert Ricker,  
executive director of the American Shooting Sports Council. ``This 
industry follows the law. How can following the law be an unfair 
business practice?'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
