<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DC Tuition Bill Advances to Senate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- District of Columbia high school graduates  
would get a break on their college tuition under a bill awaiting 
Senate consideration. 
</P>
<P>
	The House passed the $17 million measure by voice vote Monday.  
</P>
<P>
	Under the bill, District of Columbia high school graduates  
accepted to a public university outside the city would be treated 
as though they were residents of the school's state, thus allowing 
them to pay reduced in-state tuition to attend. 
</P>
<P>
	Public colleges and universities charge higher tuition of  
students who come from outside the state that funds them than for 
students who are state residents. 
</P>
<P>
	Sponsors say the measure will help ``level the playing field''  
for D.C. graduates, who pay higher tuition to attend public 
colleges and universities other than the University of the District 
of Columbia, the city's open enrollment institution of higher 
learning. 
</P>
<P>
	``The city, by its very nature, lacks the capacity for a  
university system of higher education as that concept is understood 
in the 50 states,'' said Rep. Tom Davis, R-Va., a prime sponsor. 
``The same choices and opportunities simply do not exist for 
students and parents here as exist elsewhere in the United 
States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under the program, the federal government would pay the  
difference in tuition rates through a fund administered by the 
city's mayor, who would award scholarships of up to $10,000 per 
academic year to qualified students. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill also includes an incentive to keep talented District of  
Columbia students in the region, making them eligible for 
scholarships of up to $3,000 for attending private colleges in the 
District of Columbia, Maryland or Virginia. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure, which the Clinton administration supports, would  
not alter the admissions policies of any public college or 
university. 
</P>
<P>
	A competing Senate version, however, would restrict scholarship  
assistance to public universities in Maryland and Virginia. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is H.R. 974.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
