<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Starr Won't Retry Julie Hiatt Steele </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Bowing after legal setbacks, Independent  
Counsel Kenneth Starr won't retry a Virginia woman accused of 
hindering his investigation, The Associated Press has learned. The 
case ended with a deadlocked jury earlier this month. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr on Tuesday informed the federal judge who oversaw the case  
of Julie Hiatt Steele of his decision, according to legal sources 
familiar with his decision. 
</P>
<P>
	The independent counsel's move came after juries handed him  
consecutive setbacks in his efforts to punish witnesses he 
contended were uncooperative or gave false testimony that delayed 
his investigation. Jurors deadlocked in both the cases of Ms. 
Steele and Whitewater figure Susan McDougal. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr still has two more trials involving another witness he has  
accused of being uncooperative, presidential friend and former 
Justice Department official Webster Hubbell. 
</P>
<P>
	Hubbell, who has already served prison time on charges brought  
by Starr, faces separate indictments alleging tax evasion and false 
testimony. The first of those trials is to begin in August. 
</P>
<P>
	But the decision in the Steele case is another sign that, in the  
aftermath of President Clinton's impeachment, Starr may be closer 
to winding down his five-year, $40 million-plus investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Three of Starr's key deputies during the height of the  
investigation left his office to join private law firms this 
spring. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr's office charged Ms. Steele, of Richmond, Va., with lying  
to federal investigators in her testimony that undercut the claims 
of presidential accuser Kathleen Willey. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Willey alleged Clinton made an unwanted sexual advance  
inside the White House in 1993 and that she told Ms. Steele 
immediately about the episode. Ms. Steele testified that Mrs. 
Willey had not told her about the incident and later asked her to 
lie about it. 
</P>
<P>
	Though Starr provided testimony from friends that Ms. Steele had  
indeed told them about Mrs. Willey's allegation shortly after the 
alleged incident occurred, a jury in northern Virginia earlier this 
deadlocked on the charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr had accused Mrs. McDougal, a former business partner of  
the president and first lady, of obstructing his investigation and 
defying a federal judge's order by refusing to testify before the 
grand jury that probed the Clintons' Arkansas business dealings. 
</P>
<P>
	But a jury in April acquitted Mrs. McDougal of the obstruction  
charge and deadlocked on the two contempt of court charges. 
Mistrials were declared in both cases, giving the Starr the option 
to pursue the charges again. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
