<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ping Celebrates 40 Years of Putters  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	It started with two sugar cubes, two popsicle sticks and a  
``ping.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Karsten Solheim was working as a mechanical engineer for General  
Electric in 1959 when he developed the design for his 1-A putter, 
placing the sticks on each side of the cubes with a shaft in the 
middle. 
</P>
<P>
	Upon contact with a golf ball, the putter made a high-pitched  
ringing sound that gave birth to the brand name Ping. 
</P>
<P>
	The sleeve of a 78-rpm record made Solheim leave GE for a new  
career making clubs. On that sleeve is his sketch of a 
revolutionary idea for another putter -- the Ping Anser, which has 
become a model for today's most popular styles. 
</P>
<P>
	Having grown from such extraordinary roots, Ping is celebrating  
its 40th anniversary this year as a family run business that has 
helped shape the golf-equipment industry. 
</P>
<P>
	The founder, who gave women's golf the Solheim Cup and has two  
college golf courses named for him, spends most of his time in a 
wheelchair now. Solheim has Parkinson's disease and is unable to 
communicate effectively. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, he has lunch with his wife every day at Moon Valley Golf  
Club. He also joined the Ping staff for pizza and soft drinks when 
it held a 40th birthday party this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Knowing that he's helped so many people's golf games just made  
him feel real good inside,'' said John Solheim, his son and now 
president of Ping. 
</P>
<P>
	John Solheim was in junior high when his father began making the  
1-A putter in the garage of their Redwood City, Calif., home. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dad had me drilling the holes in the putter head for the  
shaft,'' Solheim said. ``My brother was doing the grips. It turned 
into a family affair.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Looking back over 40 years, Solheim went silent when asked what  
first comes to mind when Ping is mentioned. 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps the Anser putter, which has been used to win 500 events  
on professional tours around the world, or investment casting, 
another Solheim innovation aimed at improving product consistency. 
</P>
<P>
	Who can forget perimeter weighting on the Ping Eye2 irons?  
Solheim was the first to design clubs that distributed weight to 
the extremities, which increased the sweet spot and offered more 
forgiveness. 
</P>
<P>
	Ping also put an ``L'' on a high-lofted club that has become  
part of golf's glossary these days -- the lob wedge. 
</P>
<P>
	John Solheim is just as enthused looking forward as looking back  
at 40 years. 
</P>
<P>
	He measured Ping's growth in double digits last year and  
anticipates a big push over the next 12 months. Having done well 
with its new TiSi driver, Ping plans to unveil a new line of 
fairway metals in the fall. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have a low center of gravity, but not the shallow heads  
like what the current market trend is,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The big surprise is what's in store next year. The company that  
has become known for its offset clubs with the modern cavity back 
plans to introduce its own line of blade irons. 
</P>
<P>
	``We totally believe in the offset club,'' Solheim said. ``There  
is part of the marketplace that refused to go with offset. We 
decided we're going to build a blade -- but not like every else's 
blade.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a way, Ping will have come full circle. The company  
essentially took off when Karsten Solheim was looking for an answer 
to the blade putters that Arnold Palmer popularized by winning six 
major championship in a five-year span. 
</P>
<P>
	The answer, which became the Anser, can be found on the record  
sleeve and dated Jan. 16, 1966. The sketch shows a cavity-back 
design for heel-toe balance and the offset hosel. 
</P>
<P>
	The only problem was, Solheim wanted to fit the name on the back  
of the toe, and ``Answer'' was one letter too long. 
</P>
<P>
	``This really upset him because my mother told him to name it  
'Answer,''' Solheim said. ``The next morning she said, 'Why don't 
you take the 'w' out?' He took it out and it fit perfectly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ping got a boost when Julius Boros won the Phoenix Open the next  
year using the Ping Anser. Now, the company has a vault at its 
headquarters with more than 1,800 gold-plated replicas of putters 
that have won on the major professional tours around the world. It 
also sends a replica to the player. 
</P>
<P>
	Seve Ballesteros has the most of the gilded putters -- 45. He has  
used the Scottsdale Anser for most of his international victories, 
and Ping gave him another one for his role as captain of Europe's 
winning Ryder Cup team in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Ping also has three gold-plated sand wedges in the vault from  
three memorable victories -- Bob Tway, holing out from the bunker on 
the 72nd hole of the 1986 PGA Championship; Paul Azinger doing the 
same thing in the 1993 Memorial; and Jeff Maggert chipping in for 
birdie on the 38th hole to win $1 million in the Match Play 
Championship. 
</P>
<P>
	It hasn't always been smooth sailing for 40 years.  
</P>
<P>
	Ping also was out front by taking on the USGA and the PGA Tour  
over its use of square grooves. The controversy and subsequent 
lawsuits lingered for eight years. 
</P>
<P>
	Ping agreed to reduce the width between the grooves the size of  
a human hair in settling a lawsuit with the USGA in 1990. Three 
years later, the PGA Tour backed away from its threat to require 
only V-shaped grooves in competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the courtroom battles took a toll.  
</P>
<P>
	``His mind was not on golf clubs, it was on the lawsuit,'' John  
Solheim said of his father. ``That took a lot out of him. What 
Karsten really enjoyed was designing clubs and making them 
better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	From a popsicle sticks and sugar cubes, Ping has been doing that  
for 40 years. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990525.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 18:31:30 </DATE_TIME>
