<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Martin Wins Kentucky GOP Nomination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRANKFORT, Ky. (AP) -- A publicist edged a former Democrat on  
Tuesday for Kentucky's Republican gubernatorial nomination and will 
face heavily favored incumbent Gov. Paul Patton in the general 
election. 
</P>
<P>
	This is the first Kentucky gubernatorial race in which an  
incumbent has been allowed to succeed himself. The state 
constitution was changed in 1992 to allow succession, which had 
been banned in Kentucky for nearly 200 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Patton was not challenged in the Democratic primary.  
</P>
<P>
	With 98 percent of precincts reporting in the GOP race, Peppy  
Martin had 19,173 votes, or 51 percent, while David L. Williams, 
who ran for the Senate as a Democrat a year ago, had 18,185 votes, 
or 49 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Martin spent only $10,000 on her campaign, and Williams  
spent next to nothing. Williams, a onetime operator of a 
construction company who lives in a trailer with his running-mate 
wife, Joanna, a candidate for lieutenant governor, had declined 
interviews and had his telephone disconnected. 
</P>
<P>
	Patton is heavily favored to win re-election, largely because  
Democrats vastly outnumber Republicans on Kentucky voter 
registration rolls. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Tuesday, Jonathan Miller, a former member of Vice President  
Al Gore's staff, won the Democratic nomination for state treasurer. 
Miller spent nearly $500,000 on the race, about 10 times his 
rival's total. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
