<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  IRL Introduces Safety Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Unfortunately, the only place to crash test  
Indy cars at 200 mph is on a racetrack. 
</P>
<P>
	That's why Leo Mehl and the rest of the top officials of the  
Indy Racing League say they can't guarantee that the introduction 
of a ``suspension wheel energy management system'' will insure the 
safety of spectators. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody can test at 200 mph, and our cars spend a great deal of  
their racing life over 200,'' said Mehl, the executive director of 
the IRL and vice president of the Indianapolis Motor Speedway. ``A 
normal crash creates 60 to 85 G's of energy. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think any of us are sure what's going to happen when  
you hit at 85 G's. I think it's going to be much better. I think 
we're going to have less wheels, less suspensions running around in 
the middle of the racetrack that can be run into. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think anybody would be crazy to say this system is going to  
retain every wheel at 210 miles per hour.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He added, ``I think we're doing everything possible to make it  
as safe for the fans as it can be. I mean, there isn't a 100 
percent guarantee that we're going to walk out there and not get 
run over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mehl said the system designed to keep suspension parts from  
flying off the open-wheel cars will be installed prior to 
Thursday's two-hour ``Carburetion Day'' practice. That is the only 
time between the end of qualifications and the 500-mile race that 
the 33 starters can drive on the speedway oval. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday's announcement of the move to tether the suspension parts  
to the Indy cars came just 24 days after the tragedy at Lowe's 
Motor Speedway in Concord, N.C., where flying wheel and suspension 
parts flew into the grandstand. 
</P>
<P>
	Three spectators also were killed and several others injured  
last July at Michigan Speedway in Brooklyn, Mich., by a wheel and 
other debris from a crash during a CART event. 
</P>
<P>
	Both of those tracks are high-speed, high-banked ovals.  
</P>
<P>
	Formula One began the 1999 season with a tethering system on its  
cars, while Championship Auto Racing Teams, the IRL's U.S.-based 
rival, will debut similar wheel and suspension restraints -- though 
for the front wheels only -- Saturday in the Motorola 300 in 
Madison, Ill. 
</P>
<P>
	Tom Anderson, team manager of three-time defending CART champion  
Target-Chip Ganassi Racing, said this is all just a first step in 
an evoluation toward more safety for spectators and drivers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a big investment in our fans and in the drivers, and  
we can't afford to hurt either one,'' Anderson said from the team's 
race shop two miles from the speedway. ``We've lost six fans in the 
last year and there's no way of telling how many people that has 
stopped from coming to races. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to react in a hurry to get something rolling. We're  
following Formula One's lead, and this is the best first step we 
could take.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eliseo Salazar, who has finished fourth and sixth at Indy and  
will be starting 18th on Sunday, said, ``It's absolutely necessary 
we try something. Nobody can say if this will be 100 percent 
efficient, but it's crucial we never put the spectators in that 
position again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The IRL announcement said all four suspensions on its cars will  
be attached to the chassis with multiple cables of Zylon -- a space 
age fiber Mehl said is two times stronger than Kevlar. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has a breaking strength of five tons,'' said Mehl, who  
added that it's the same material being used by Formula One. 
</P>
<P>
	One worry about using restraints is the possibility that  
tethered suspension pieces or wheels could rebound into the open 
cockpit, hitting the driver. 
</P>
<P>
	But Mehl said the IRL believes its system will actually make the  
drivers safer. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a lot of loose pieces out there right now (in a  
crash),'' Mehl said. ``The more we can keep attached to the car, 
the better off the driver and the spectators.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The cables will connect the rear hubs and the front hubs and  
will also be attached to the farthest points from the driver on the 
frame. Mehl said they should not be able to reach the driver's 
compartment in a crash. 
</P>
<P>
	But, even if they could reach the cockpit, most of the drivers  
have said they'd rather be at more risk than put spectators in 
danger. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some people say it might be dangerous for the drivers,''  
Salazar said. ``We live for this, and we know what can happen. You 
never want to put other people in the way of harm.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The restraints will not keep the tire itself from flying off in  
a severe crash, but Phil Casey, technical director for the IRL, 
said the problems have been caused not by the tire, which is 
attached to the hub with a locking pin, but by the hub and 
suspension pieces being sheared off the cars and taking the tire 
with it. 

</P>
</TEXT>
