<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> ProXeed Claims To Aid in Fertility </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A company is beginning to market a  
nonprescription fertility aid to couples struggling to have a baby, 
saying the dietary supplement may improve a man's sperm quality. 
</P>
<P>
	The direct-to-consumer marketing of proXeed gives fertility  
specialists a dilemma: Some are intrigued enough to try the product 
on their own patients even as they caution there's no proof yet 
that it works. 
</P>
<P>
	But doctors urged Americans to see a physician before buying  
proXeed on the Internet, because there are too many other causes of 
male infertility -- occasionally life-threatening ones -- that 
proXeed won't help but regular medicine can. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm anxious and excited to see how it works, but I'd not at  
this point tell patients it's going to work,'' said Dr. Larry 
Lipshultz, a Baylor College of Medicine urologist and president of 
the American Society for Reproductive Medicine. 
</P>
<P>
	ProXeed isn't thought to cause side effects, so ``the only thing  
you have to lose is the $100 a month you're going to spend,'' added 
Lipshultz, who is giving it to patients. 
</P>
<P>
	Other options such as in vitro fertilization can cost thousands.  
</P>
<P>
	Up to 40 percent of conception difficulties are believed caused,  
at least partly, by poor sperm. That means 2.5 million American 
couples potentially could try proXeed, said Sigma-Tau Consumer 
Products, which begins marketing the citrus-flavored drink mix to 
consumers Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	ProXeed contains two types of L-carnitine, a compound naturally  
present in the body important for cellular metabolism. People 
absorb L-carnitine mostly from red meat and dairy products. 
</P>
<P>
	Scientists know L-carnitine is highly concentrated in  
sperm-related tissues. The theory: Perhaps men with low sperm 
counts or poor sperm quality -- such as sperm that don't swim well -- 
lack L-carnitine. Small European studies suggest taking specific 
amounts of L-carnitine and a metabolite, acetylcarnitine, for three 
to six months gave subfertile men more normal sperm. 
</P>
<P>
	It won't create super fertility.  
</P>
<P>
	``ProXeed's not a miracle drug. It does one thing: It optimizes  
sperm quality, and it does that very well,'' said Brad Stewart of 
Sigma-Tau, an Italian-based company that also sells prescription 
drug versions of L-carnitine, including one sold here to treat a 
rare metabolic disease. 
</P>
<P>
	The European research is promising, but ``it's not all that  
firm, in all honesty,'' cautioned Dr. Jon Pryor of the University 
of Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
	He will perform the first U.S. study this summer, giving up to  
80 men at his clinic and Brown University either proXeed or a dummy 
pill. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors are reassured about trying proXeed because the Food and  
Drug Administration says the prescription L-carnitine that treats 
metabolic disease has proved very safe. 
</P>
<P>
	But L-carnitine also is sold as a dietary supplement, and  
dietary supplements are largely unregulated. The FDA cracks down 
only on dangerous ones, or those claiming to treat disease like a 
drug. FDA officials could not say if ``optimizing sperm quality'' 
would cross that line. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumers, however, can buy supplements without ever consulting  
a doctor. 
</P>
<P>
	Don't do that, Pryor urged infertile men. Much male infertility  
is something treatable like a hormone imbalance that proXeed won't 
affect, and a few men even may have testicular cancer or another 
serious condition. 
</P>
<P>
	Sigma-Tau promised to pass that message to customers, and says  
it is working closely with fertility specialists ``to develop the 
science'' behind proXeed. 
</P>
<P>
	So why not seek FDA approval as a fertility drug rather than  
sell it as a supplement? It would take about $100 million more 
research -- and wouldn't prevent unregulated competitors sold in 
health food stores from claiming to work as well, said Stewart, who 
will sell proXeed on the Internet and by phone. 
</P>
<P>
	Other L-carnitine supplements are sold mostly for weight loss,  
something Sigma-Tau's testing shows doesn't work, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sperm enhancement requires precise amounts of two specific  
types, not just any L-carnitine, Stewart added -- and he cited a 
1993 Duke University analysis of L-carnitine supplements that found 
most did not contain the amount promised on the products' labels 
regardless. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990525.0284 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 17:01:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> American Buys Sudan Slaves' Freedom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- In the 19th century, abolitionists came to Faneuil  
Hall to champion their antislavery cause. Now the Colonial meeting 
house is a tourist attraction with souvenirs and street musicians. 
</P>
<P>
	But for Charles Jacobs, it's still a place to speak out about  
the injustices of slavery. He has plenty to talk about: He heads a 
group that buys people out of slavery in northern Africa -- usually 
for about $50 a person. 
</P>
<P>
	UNICEF and other human rights groups criticize the practice by  
saying it encourages slavery by creating a market, but Jacobs says 
his work is essential. He is scheduled to testify before Congress 
about the subject on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is both sweet and sad,'' said Jacobs, a white man in his  
50s. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1993, Jacobs was working for a management consulting firm.  
Then he happened to read a magazine article about millions of 
slaves being sold: as prostitutes in Thailand, charcoal workers in 
Brazil, brick kiln operators in Pakistan and bonded farmers in 
India. 
</P>
<P>
	He decided to find a new career speaking out against slavery --  
specifically in Africa. ``How many people have a chance to do 
something that's important?'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jacobs co-founded the American Anti-Slavery Group and has since  
raised $35,000 to buy and free nearly 350 slaves in Sudan. Civil 
war has led Arab Muslim northerners there to capture and enslave 
black villagers who practice Christianity and traditional tribal 
religions. 
</P>
<P>
	The story of Abuk Deng Akuei is typical of those recounted by  
American Anti-Slavery. The Christian teen-age girl was captured by 
an Arab militia that raided her Sudanese village in 1997. She was 
sold to a man who beat her, raped her, forcibly circumcised her and 
made her work in the fields and sleep with his cows and goats. 
</P>
<P>
	She was freed by Christian Solidarity International, a Swiss  
organization that does the dangerous work of buying slaves from 
Arab middlemen, according to Jacobs' group. 
</P>
<P>
	In Mauritania, another African country, slavery was declared  
illegal in 1980, but human rights groups say it is still widely 
practiced. 
</P>
<P>
	Jacobs said slave owners there won't allow their slaves' freedom  
to be bought, but his organization pays for people like Moctar 
Teyeb, a Mauritanian slave who escaped to America four years ago, 
to travel around the country and tell his story. 
</P>
<P>
	At churches, schools and abolitionist conferences, Teyeb rolls  
up a sleeve and describes how his master broke his arm when he was 
9 and refused to have it set. 
</P>
<P>
	Jacobs has persuaded students from at least 100 schools around  
the country to raise money to buy slaves their freedom, and 
American Anti-Slavery has chapters in several other cities. 
</P>
<P>
	UNICEF, however, has severely criticized the practice of buying  
freedom for slaves. 
</P>
<P>
	Carol Bellamy, executive director of the United Nations' group,  
said in March, ``The sobering truth is that these efforts will not 
end the enslavement of human beings.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990525.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 00:21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  IRL Introduces Safety Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Unfortunately, the only place to crash test  
Indy cars at 200 mph is on a racetrack. 
</P>
<P>
	That's why Leo Mehl and the rest of the top officials of the  
Indy Racing League say they can't guarantee that the introduction 
of a ``suspension wheel energy management system'' will insure the 
safety of spectators. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody can test at 200 mph, and our cars spend a great deal of  
their racing life over 200,'' said Mehl, the executive director of 
the IRL and vice president of the Indianapolis Motor Speedway. ``A 
normal crash creates 60 to 85 G's of energy. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think any of us are sure what's going to happen when  
you hit at 85 G's. I think it's going to be much better. I think 
we're going to have less wheels, less suspensions running around in 
the middle of the racetrack that can be run into. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think anybody would be crazy to say this system is going to  
retain every wheel at 210 miles per hour.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He added, ``I think we're doing everything possible to make it  
as safe for the fans as it can be. I mean, there isn't a 100 
percent guarantee that we're going to walk out there and not get 
run over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mehl said the system designed to keep suspension parts from  
flying off the open-wheel cars will be installed prior to 
Thursday's two-hour ``Carburetion Day'' practice. That is the only 
time between the end of qualifications and the 500-mile race that 
the 33 starters can drive on the speedway oval. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday's announcement of the move to tether the suspension parts  
to the Indy cars came just 24 days after the tragedy at Lowe's 
Motor Speedway in Concord, N.C., where flying wheel and suspension 
parts flew into the grandstand. 
</P>
<P>
	Three spectators also were killed and several others injured  
last July at Michigan Speedway in Brooklyn, Mich., by a wheel and 
other debris from a crash during a CART event. 
</P>
<P>
	Both of those tracks are high-speed, high-banked ovals.  
</P>
<P>
	Formula One began the 1999 season with a tethering system on its  
cars, while Championship Auto Racing Teams, the IRL's U.S.-based 
rival, will debut similar wheel and suspension restraints -- though 
for the front wheels only -- Saturday in the Motorola 300 in 
Madison, Ill. 
</P>
<P>
	Tom Anderson, team manager of three-time defending CART champion  
Target-Chip Ganassi Racing, said this is all just a first step in 
an evoluation toward more safety for spectators and drivers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a big investment in our fans and in the drivers, and  
we can't afford to hurt either one,'' Anderson said from the team's 
race shop two miles from the speedway. ``We've lost six fans in the 
last year and there's no way of telling how many people that has 
stopped from coming to races. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to react in a hurry to get something rolling. We're  
following Formula One's lead, and this is the best first step we 
could take.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eliseo Salazar, who has finished fourth and sixth at Indy and  
will be starting 18th on Sunday, said, ``It's absolutely necessary 
we try something. Nobody can say if this will be 100 percent 
efficient, but it's crucial we never put the spectators in that 
position again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The IRL announcement said all four suspensions on its cars will  
be attached to the chassis with multiple cables of Zylon -- a space 
age fiber Mehl said is two times stronger than Kevlar. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has a breaking strength of five tons,'' said Mehl, who  
added that it's the same material being used by Formula One. 
</P>
<P>
	One worry about using restraints is the possibility that  
tethered suspension pieces or wheels could rebound into the open 
cockpit, hitting the driver. 
</P>
<P>
	But Mehl said the IRL believes its system will actually make the  
drivers safer. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a lot of loose pieces out there right now (in a  
crash),'' Mehl said. ``The more we can keep attached to the car, 
the better off the driver and the spectators.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The cables will connect the rear hubs and the front hubs and  
will also be attached to the farthest points from the driver on the 
frame. Mehl said they should not be able to reach the driver's 
compartment in a crash. 
</P>
<P>
	But, even if they could reach the cockpit, most of the drivers  
have said they'd rather be at more risk than put spectators in 
danger. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some people say it might be dangerous for the drivers,''  
Salazar said. ``We live for this, and we know what can happen. You 
never want to put other people in the way of harm.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The restraints will not keep the tire itself from flying off in  
a severe crash, but Phil Casey, technical director for the IRL, 
said the problems have been caused not by the tire, which is 
attached to the hub with a locking pin, but by the hub and 
suspension pieces being sheared off the cars and taking the tire 
with it. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
