<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hawks Season Ends With a Sweep </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- By the end, the Atlanta Hawks were too old, too  
banged up and too worn out. 
</P>
<P>
	The younger legs of the New York Knicks ran circles around the  
Hawks, sweeping them out of the playoffs in four straight games. 
Once again, Atlanta failed to make it past the second round, which 
has been the case every year since the franchise moved from St. 
Louis in 1968. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of course, you want to go farther,'' Mookie Blaylock said.  
``I'm not going to look back and say we did a great job, because we 
didn't. We didn't go nowhere.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Actually, the Hawks probably lost any hope of making an extended  
playoff run when they needed five exhausting games to beat Detroit 
in the opening round. Plagued by injuries, the Hawks were forced to 
use five 30-something starters in the deciding contest -- all of 
them playing at least 40 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	When it was time to meet New York, the Hawks had nothing left.  
</P>
<P>
	``They are disappointed,'' coach Lenny Wilkens said. ``Real  
disappointed, because they feel they are a better team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In all fairness, the Hawks were hardly at full strength by the  
end of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	LaPhonso Ellis, the team's most noteworthy addition after the  
lockout, lasted only 20 games before he was sidelined for the 
season with a sports hernia. Alan Henderson haggled over a new 
contract, was plagued by myriad injuries, then was knocked out for 
good when an eye abrasion in the final days of the regular season 
left him with double-vision. 
</P>
<P>
	Chris Crawford took over for Ellis and showed promise, but he  
missed three playoff games with a separated shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't say if we had this or if we had that,'' Blaylock  
said. ``We didn't have it and we had to go play with what we had.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What they had was very little depth, a familiar bugaboo for this  
team over the last couple of seasons and one that management worked 
hard to correct after the lockout ended. 
</P>
<P>
	Grant Long, who resurrected his career after two lost seasons in  
Detroit, was a valued player off the bench. But his weaknesses were 
exposed in the playoffs when he was forced into the lineup for 
Henderson. 
</P>
<P>
	Point guard Anthony Johnson, who had a solid rookie season in  
Sacramento, played erratically after signing with the Hawks. Ed 
Gray, the No. 1 pick in 1997, was even more of a disappointment. 
Instead of providing needed scoring punch off the bench, he shot 
less than 30 percent from the field, played only 30 games and spent 
a night in jail after being arrested on marijuana charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Whereas the Knicks had Latrell Sprewell and Marcus Camby to  
energize their offense, the Hawks had no one to turn to when Steve 
Smith was shooting poorly and Dikembe Mutombo was being 
double-teamed in the low post. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, Atlanta has shown all through the regular season that  
it was woefully inadequate at the offensive end. The Hawks averaged 
86.3 points per game, beating only the woeful Chicago Bulls. More 
telling, they averaged less than 16 assists per game, by far the 
lowest figure in the league. 
</P>
<P>
	Blaylock, the point guard, failed to keep the offense moving,  
seeming to age right before our eyes as the season went along. He 
often resorted to sitting outside and heaving 3-pointers, but made 
only 37.9 percent for his lowest shooting percentage since his 
rookie season in 1989-90. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite their flaws, the Hawks have plenty of reason for  
optimism: 
</P>
<P>
	--A move into the 20,000-seat Philips Arena next season, giving  
the team its first true home court since 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	--Four first-round picks in the upcoming draft, providing general  
manager Pete Babcock with an opportunity to package some picks for 
a higher selection. 
</P>
<P>
	--Room under the salary cap to upgrade the bench even more.  
</P>
<P>
	For now, though, the team is trying to get over the  
disappointment of being swept by the Knicks. 
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't give ourselves a good enough test,'' Blaylock said.  
``If we go out and play the way we're able to play, we can win some 
games. But we played terrible all four games.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
