<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Starr Won't Retry McDougal, Steele </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Bowing to legal setbacks, Kenneth Starr  
decided Tuesday he won't retry Whitewater figure Susan McDougal and 
another woman accused of hindering his investigation. Both cases 
ended in mistrials this spring. 
</P>
<P>
	After taking many legal battles all the way to the Supreme Court  
to uphold ``the rule of law,'' Starr said prosecuting anew Mrs. 
McDougal and Julie Hiatt Steele wasn't worth the trouble given 
earlier hung juries in the two cases. 
</P>
<P>
	``Retrials raise important questions of resource allocation,....  
The jury's inability to reach a unanimous verdict is a reality that 
we have taken seriously,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The independent counsel's decision Tuesday came after juries  
handed him consecutive setbacks in his effort to punish two 
witnesses he contended were uncooperative or gave false testimony, 
and delayed his investigation. Jurors deadlocked in both trials. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement also brought Starr a couple of steps closer to  
winding up a $40 million investigation that produced only the 
second impeachment ever of a U.S. president. Three of Starr's key 
deputies have left this spring for private law practice. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't believe he would have gotten a conviction and he would  
only have put my family through the misery of a retrial. I think he 
did the right thing,'' said William Henley, one of Mrs. McDougal's 
brothers. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr's decision ends five years of legal warfare with Mrs.  
McDougal, who with her late ex-husband, started the Whitewater land 
venture with the Clintons. 
</P>
<P>
	She was sent to prison after being convicted in the first  
Whitewater trial in 1996, was also jailed for refusing a judge's 
order to answer Starr's questions before a grand jury and then was 
tried this year for obstruction. From her jail cell to television 
interviews, Mrs. McDougal incessantly attacked Starr's motives and 
tactics. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Steele's lawyer, who also made Starr's tactics an issue in  
her client's trial, said the decision reflected an assessment that 
``this was a case that could not be won.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Whatever his motivation, we are pleased and relieved,''  
attorney Nancy Luque said. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr still has two more trials involving another witness he has  
accused of being uncooperative, presidential friend and former 
Justice Department official Webster Hubbell. 
</P>
<P>
	Hubbell, who has already served prison time on charges brought  
by Starr, faces separate indictments alleging tax evasion and false 
testimony. The first of those trials is set to begin in August. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr had accused Mrs. McDougal, a former business partner of  
the president and first lady, of obstructing his investigation and 
defying a federal judge's order by refusing to testify before the 
grand jury that probed the Clintons' Arkansas business dealings. 
</P>
<P>
	A jury in April acquitted Mrs. McDougal of the obstruction  
charge and deadlocked on the contempt of court charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr's office charged Ms. Steele, of Richmond, Va., with lying  
to federal investigators in testimony that undercut the claims of 
presidential accuser Kathleen Willey. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Willey alleged Clinton made an unwanted sexual advance  
inside the White House in 1993 and that she told Ms. Steele 
immediately about the episode. Ms. Steele testified that Mrs. 
Willey had not told her about the incident and later asked her to 
lie about it. 
</P>
<P>
	Though Starr provided testimony from friends that Ms. Steele had  
indeed told them about Mrs. Willey's allegation shortly after the 
alleged incident occurred, a jury in northern Virginia deadlocked 
and a mistrial was declared. 
</P>
<P>
	In both cases, defense lawyers made an issue of the tactics used  
by Starr's office in pursuing a wide-ranging investigation that 
included the Clintons' Whitewater business dealings, the gathering 
of FBI files inside the White House the firing of the White House 
travel office and the Monica Lewinsky affair. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal, who served prison time on Whitewater-related  
charges earlier in the investigation, testified in her own defense. 
She said she refused to talk to the grand jury because she feared 
that Starr would punish her if she did not give testimony that 
matched his theory of the case. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Steele's lawyers surprised many by resting their case  
without calling any witnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent interviews, jurors described widely varying views of  
Starr's work. 
</P>
<P>
	Donald Thomas, the jury foreman in the McDougal case, said he  
was put off by the ``arrogance'' of Starr's prosecutors and that 
some jurors were convinced that Mrs. McDougal's fears were 
justified. 
</P>
<P>
	But Jack Hawxhurst, the jury foreman in the Steele case, said  
the evidence against Ms. Steele lied was ``very persuasive'' and 
Starr should have sought a retrial. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
