<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NH Man Accused of Abducting Ex-Wife </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOWELL, Mass. (AP) -- Authorities arrested a man accused of  
abducting his ex-wife from her workplace, a shelter for women and 
children in crisis in New Hampshire. 
</P>
<P>
	Police arrested Gary Collinge, 49, and found his ex-wife,  
Marguerite Eno, apparently unharmed, according to Nashua, N.H., 
police Lt. Wayne MacDonald. He said tips from relatives led police 
to their location in a Lowell home. 
</P>
<P>
	Collinge was arrested on a fugitive from justice warrant issued  
in New Hampshire. He put up no resistance when arrested, police 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said Collinge abducted Eno, 46, at gunpoint Sunday night  
from Marguerite's Place in Nashua, about 12 miles north of Lowell. 
Sgt. Frank Paison said four shots were fired as she was dragged but 
were apparently not aimed at anyone. 
</P>
<P>
	The couple separated in 1995, five years after marrying. Eno  
filed for divorce last year, accusing Collinge of beating her and 
violating restraining orders. The divorce was granted last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Marguerite's Place is run by the Order of Grey Nuns and was the  
state's first long-term transitional housing for women and children 
in crisis when it opened in 1994. It's just a coincidence that it 
has the name of Eno, a longtime employee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
